text: Generous portions! And decent coffee. Not the best coffee in the world, but decent. They had some nice breakfast options at lunch time and it was completely and utterly deserted on a weekday (except for us). So if you can get over to HillV2 on a weekday - why not?

text: Decided to grab a quick lunch here. Modern vibes and spacious seating but definitely on the more expensive side. We got pasta and panini but honestly neither of them impressed us. Chicken in the pasta was way too dry and the dish wasn&#39;t too flavorful. Same issue with the panini. We didn&#39;t try their drinks so maybe that&#39;s their selling point. Great place to chill but skip the dining.

text: Nice, quiet place - though it may be a little bit out of the way for those people who don&#39;t drive (but I guess you can always check out their other outlets in Orchard Central!)<br><br>Food wise, it was good. I would recommend their truffle carbonara - comes with a poached egg! Their wagyu lasagna was average - meat was well done though! Portions were very generous as well!<br><br>Service by their manager was really good. The staff kind of forgot the lasagna so we ended up waiting for a really long time, so she brought us some soup and bread so we wouldn&#39;t starve in the meantime. With that said, the soup had a piece of paper in it, rendering it virtually inedible :/

text: Another excellent eatery in the new Hillv2 mall. Lots of organic stuff and healthy drinks, although cheeseburger is also on the menu.<br>Very contemporary atmosphere, brand new and icy cold aircon, accompanied by (too much) thumping music. It&#39;s nice for a quick meal. Don&#39;t stick around too long.

Laksa pizza! Interesting, but it&#39;ll never beat an actual Bowl of laksa', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "Laksa pizza! Interesting, but it'll never beat an actual Bowl of laksa"}]
text: I came by here for dinner after work, seeing that they close late (11pm!). It&#39;s located at the first floor of McPherson community centre, and utilises their wifi. It&#39;s very spacious, and it&#39;s even got a small slide in the corner for kids to play in. I wasn&#39;t that hungry, and ended up ordering their truffle fries and their laksa pizza, along with a &#39;matcha Kopi&#39;.<br><br>Their menu is pretty extensive and locally inspired, including things like a Chili crab pasta and a salted egg yolk prawn pasta. They also do burgers and pizzas. The laksa pizza I had was interesting conceptually, consisting of their own homemade bread topped with prawns, fishcake, curry leaves and boiled egg. I enjoyed it as it was a thin crust, but honestly it felt more like a glorified bakery bread. It wasn&#39;t bad, but at $16.90, it&#39;s a little steep. As for the truffle fries, the truffles it was topped with were questionable. <br><br>However, I have to admit that I really like the layout, and it&#39;s very communal. The staff need some work in terms of explaining the menu, but otherwise, I actually really liked the coffee! They also do a salted caramel latte, so next time I might try it. They&#39;re apparently famous for their rainbow cake, which looked really delectable, and topped with things like cookies and cream and salted caramel. Overall, seems like a good place to do some studying and work if you&#39;re in the area, though more for coffee and dessert than the food, which is a tad overpriced. Might try their pasta next time! Definitely a good concept to put it in a CC, I&#39;ll have to come back again and update my review then, with photos of the rainbow cake!

text: I called in to make a reservation for 5 which we ended up being a party of 8 with a child. NOM&#39;s interior is set up with several square tables so they can be very flexible with any party size. A great plus point over fixed sized booths, which only accomodate so many people.<br><br> <br>This is the entrance of NOM at MacPherson Community Club on a tuesday night 8pm. I parked across the street, at the HDB car park and there was a summon aunty walking around checking coupons, so do take note!<br><br> <br>Cheese and tomato pizza was okay, nothing fancy. Big enough to share.<br> <br>For the kids meal, we got pasta and the gravy tasted fine, except for the pasta penne itself, it was abit hard.<br> <br>Their chicken leg was done pretty decently and the meat pretty much fell off the bone and you wouldn&#39;t need a knife to eat this cleanly. So thumbs up for this.<br><br>I liked it better when they served full portobellos. For $9.90, this is literally one or at most two portobello mushroom caps sliced up, breaded and fried. Totally a rip off.<br><br>Everyone loved the ribs, even though I found it a bit too hard, there was only one bone in there though. So tons of meat for sharing.<br><br>Being that this is my second time, I figured I knew what I wanted. But I was so wrong, the quality has dropped. I am not sure if I would be back for the rosti. Refer to my previous review in SEPT/OCT and see the pictures of the Rosti, it looks so different. I even feedbacked to the young waitress whom politely asked if I wanted the Rosti recooked, but I said, forget it, my friends had already dug into it. But even my friend who came in JB, mentioned that Marches&#39; Rosti is so much better and even cheaper than this. <br><br>So, the newest addition to NOM is their rainbow cheesecakes which I did not see in September. It is quite solid, so I know for sure there&#39;s at least 2 blocks of Philadelphia cream cheese in there or more. It can be quite gerlat, so do share it, so just eat it and run 10km at the gym the next day.<br><br>I had tried their chocolate and oreo rainbow cakes before and this was my first time trying their salted caramel cake. Everyone really liked the salted caramel rainbow cake smile And some of my friends mentioned that they would be back to try other cakes, definitely not the Rosti though.<br> <br>At $8.90 a slice, rainbow cakes here aren&#39;t cheap but they&#39;re at least decent. The Rainbow cakes were priced at $7.90 a slice just 2 months ago.. :(<br><br>I&#39;m glad that NOM is sensible enough to price this rainbow cheesecake at $7.90, one dollar less than the rainbow cake itself. Being that I do bake cakes, I also know well that a rainbow cheesecake takes ALOT less time to make than a normal rainbow buttercream/sponge cake.<br><br>The best upside to NOM is that it is nett priced, but I believe their prices seem to be going up some dumb reason.

text: We went to NOM for brunch on a Saturday. It wasn&#39;t too crowded, there was just another family there with us. My first impression of the place was that it was bare and clinical, with the stark white walls, cement floor and white tables and chairs. It felt.. cold. The mandopop music played through the speakers made me feel even more like an outsider.<br><br>I would say the food was average. We had the atlanta eggs benedict, blackstone eggs benedict, truffle fries and chocolate rainbow cake. <br><br>Let&#39;s start with the best part- the cake. We got it only because it&#39;s supposedly the thing you must try if you&#39;re there. I&#39;ve never been a fan of rainbow cake because they don&#39;t really taste like rainbows (cheat my feelings, you know?), but I&#39;m glad I tried this one. The sponge was moist, fluffy and full of flavour, even without the chocolate icing. The icing was decadent - rich, creamy chocolatey goodness that melts in your mouth (and in your hands, I checked). <br><br>The truffle fries were amazing as fries, not so much as truffle fries. They were actually cut potatoes and I believe they were air-fried or baked, so they were not greasy. The fries were crispy on the surface and hot on the inside. Unfortunately, we could barely taste the truffles. In terms of taste, the shaved parmesan on top had more impact.<br><br>The poached eggs were not that great, to be honest. They were almost cold by the time they were served, and one out the 4 was not runny in the middle. Toasting the english muffins and grilling the tomatoes would have improved the dishes, i think.<br><br>In summary, as NOM is quite out of the way for those who don&#39;t live in Macpherson, I think I&#39;d need a stronger reason to go back. The cakes are definitely tempting, so i&#39;d stop by for those if i&#39;m nearby.

text: A new cafe located in Macpherson area that is welcoming with a very minimalist look to their interior design. Went on a Friday and surprisingly full in the late night. <br><br>Many were here for the pretty rainbow cakes with assorted creams. Today is the oreo and salted caramel cream. The former is a little dry and the latter a bit too caramel sweet. But its a decent rainbow cake. not overly creamy and the colors of the layers are impressively bright. Not the best rainbow cake I ate (as of now i have tried like A LOT of them) but its up there with a couple of my faves.<br><br>Savories - sweet potato fries were well done. could have a little more powdered sugar. Truffle Parmesan Fries - alright. The half and half pizza is served in its rectangular form and the crust is thin and filled with herbs (think foccacia bread). an interesting take with the pepperoni and mushroom<br>with arugula. Overall not a bad pizza. The crust saved the dish.<br><br>Drinks - as a coffee and chocolate lover I went for the latte which is small and decent (my girlies beg to differ, so you guys try it and let me know). I was attracted to the chocolate drinks especially with african red hot chocolate and chilli hot chocolate in the list. so we ordered them. THEY WERE NOT HOT. Lukewarm at best. *sad face. But the chilli chocolate had that spicy punch after a sip. so that was the saving grace of that. The african red chocolate had nothing to rescue it from its sad lukewarm (and by now cold) state. *sigh<br><br> The service staff are friendly and one was really honest to let me and my girlies know it was her first day. Not very proactive but attentive when called. So overall not bad. a very young team of girls.<br><br>For an estate like Macpherson to have such a cafe really brings a twist to the feel of the place. Will come back again to try the other things like their mains, all day breakkies (weekends only hor) and their non cake desserts. Oh they have interesting cheesecakes too. <br><br>Overall a very good cafe with quality food and a passionate service team. Come here before it gets popular!

text: Apparently the gahmen is focusing on healthy choices as one of the themes for SG50, so I guess it makes sense that Tan Tock Seng Hospital would have a cold pressed juice place open their doors in 2015. <br><br>This is more of a takeaway spot, though they do have a small counter that 3 people (at most) could use to eat their sandwiches and salads. If you&#39;re not interested in cold pressed juice, you can try their pure juices or some tea. Prices are okay; medium bottles start at $5.90. To be honest, I find their flavours a bit basic* (guava/pineapple/carrot, grapefruit citrus-y mixes) so I do hope they consider being more adventurous in the future.<br><br>I tried their Mediterranean sandwich and it was quite nice. The flavours went well; I just wish the cheese was more evenly distributed as I thought it&#39;s the one ingredient that made the sandwich. But that&#39;s just me being picky.<br><br>I really do think this is a lot healthier than Toast Box, Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf, and the Kopitiam, so extra star for being the only spot to offer cold pressed juice.<br><br>--<br>*Also, their name is way too generic. So hard to find them on social media and search engines!
The best cut and quality of meats and sausages, veggies, spices, etc. and all hormone/gmo free!!! Highly recommend :)

Omelette!', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Omelette!'}]
text: We happened to discover Oh Deli quite by accident and what an accident it was. <br><br>From the outside, it doesn&#39;t look like much. <br>Even at a first glance, the menu isn&#39;t fancily done.<br>But what it lack on these aesthetics was made up 100% by the food. <br><br>Omelette ($10.90)<br>Freshly made and piping hot, the omelette isn&#39;t your fold over, elegant omelette. These are more, cook-in-a-skillet, hearty, home made omelettes and it tasted like it too. <br>Made with really fresh ingredients, it was lightly seasoned and allowed each ingredient to be nicely highlighted. <br>Simple, fuss free, hearty and satisfying. <br><br>Egg Island ($14.50 + $4.00 for additional grilled mushroom) <br>This feels like the ultimate comfort British breakfast. <br>Baked beans were nicely cooked, soft without being mushy. <br>The poached egg was perfect. And I mean PERFECT! The white wrapped around the yolk beautifully and the yolk was nice, thick and runny.<br>Sour dough was pretty good without being too sour (which I personally prefer). The mushrooms were well cooked with minimal seasoning but was packed with flavor and the sausage was so so so good. <br>Not overly seasoned, the sausage had a great meat to fat ratio and was nicely coarse. Yummy!<br><br>The food here was very well done. Slightly on the mid-price side due to most of their ingredients being organic or free ranged (which is better than paying for for &#34;fancy&#34; all day breakfasts) but what they did was make a good hearty breakfast... well... good and hearty without being overly fancy or hipsterish. <br><br>Will definitely recommend you check out this place if you&#39;re around the area and Oh! (All pun intended), it&#39;s also a grocery store so you can grab some really great ingredients while waiting for your food to be served too!

Dropped by this place hoping to grab some items for DIY breakfast tomorrow. A very friendly nice lady behind the counter helped us with the items and provide a whole load of suggestions on what to make. We ended up with smoked salmon, sausage rolls, pies, and truffle oil. That&#39;s right! truffles oil! They directly import them and sell it to other places in SG. <br><br>The meat and sausages look tempting as well. Will definitely come back here to try the  items. <br><br>Great service. Great selections.

text: Tried on recommendation.. It wasn&#39;t bad. The wraps were nice and hearty. Lots of greens. Too little meat. <br><br>The ciabatta sandwich with kurobuta pork was nice too. Nothing exceptional.

Name could be misleading to an American. This isn&#39;t a Deli like you would go to to get a good Reuben sandwich, this is more like an upscale neighborhood bodega really.<br>Having lived a block away from this place it was a regular stop for fresh meat, veggies etc... It has high quality products and plenty of rare expat preferred items. I&#39;ve eaten there a couple of times, the coffee was good and the food was good to, it felt like tables and a menu was added to boost business a bit beyond the market items. <br>Not a bad place to eat, and a must visit for fresh expat preferred shopping.

The owner of the place, the lady is extra special. She is amazingly friendly and super nice. As their main business is the deli counter, don&#39;t expect super fast service but wen it comes, your food will blow you away with it&#39;s to die for deliciousness.

text: I understand they are about to mive toward normal Starbucks hours soon this but this has been a great 24 hour a day Starbucks. As a visitor to the city, I&#39;ve found myself in need of coffee at rather odd hours. They&#39;ve always been there for me.<br><br>The facility is immaculately clean and there&#39;s a great deal of indoor seating as well as outdoor seating. The staff is quite nice and always leaves you with a smile.<br><br>What can I say about their products? They have all the products that you would expect at a Starbucks along with consistent quality!

text: Starbucks is the place to go when one is attempting to write something, study for something or simply a place to chill and gossip with your friends. <br><br>Most people will go there for the ice-blended coffee, but how many really goes there for the food? Honestly, Starbucks is by far, the only place I know in town that serves awesome beef pie. Sure, it&#39;s already there for half the day waiting for someone to buy it, but it still tastes pretty good once heated up (you can&#39;t have everything). Where else in Singapore can you get a deep-dish beef pie that oozes out with the cheese? Most of the pies I know, it&#39;s more 70% pastry, 30% fillings. Rarely, the proportions are balanced out. <br><br>Another favourite of mine will be their eggwhite wrap. Afraid of packing on the calories? Eggwhite, mushroom, peppers and cheese filled to the brim in the wrap is sufficient to fill you up without feeling guilty. Next time at Starbucks, do try out their food, it&#39;s actually quite good!

text: Probably the most &#34;wholesome&#34; place at Orchard Towers/ 4 Floors! I came here with 4 friends randomly because we heard the live music immediately when we walked into Orchard Towers. The &#34;Pub&#34; itself is not very large but it is packed with about 15-20 Filipino girls in matching outfits and a Filipino cover band playing American music that sounds almost better than the bands they are covering. As soon as you find a seat hostesses will sit with you and help you order but, they don&#39;t take the orders. Basically their job is to hang with the customers, convince you to buy them drinks, buy yourself more drinks and they also do choreographed dances during the bands break. They aren&#39;t prostitutes like most of the other businesses in the building but don&#39;t think they are in love with you either. I thoroughly enjoyed this place spending way too much money but, having a lot of fun singing to popular songs and hanging with hot girls. We even came here twice in 2 days! I probably advise this place more than any other place in Orchard Towers unless you are looking for another level of trouble.

text: Newly opened Gastronomia outlet at the B1 central fountain location in Raffles City mall. Good menu with some great choices, stylish design, friendly service. Demand for seating seems higher than what is available. Some of the floor space is under utilized, looks like a couple more tables can be easily fitted in.

text: Just ate here for breakfast.  Mainly writing this review to warn Yelpers about the giant meringues.  We had to try one of these since they looked amazing.  Ordered the cookies and cream one and it was terrible.  Really hard and way too sweet.  Cookies were stale too.<br><br>We also got a ham and cheese croissant which was pretty tasty.

text: Came down this evening (Friday night) to grab a takeaway pasta carbonara. Receipt was time stamped 1924 and I only managed to get my pasta at 1947. <br><br>Granted it&#39;s (a) a Friday, (b) their 4th day of business and (c) the service staff was professional, but I think 23 mins wait for a simple pasta takeaway was way too long, especially for a restaurant chain of their standards, and it wasn&#39;t as if there was a long queue (only 2 pax in front of me). <br><br>Maybe I&#39;m being too demanding here, but thought service staff could have done at least a tad more in service recovery (eg. At least by offering a glass of water when waiting, or if food delivery exceeds a certain amount of time, some form of a discount next time, etc.) instead of continuously saying don&#39;t worry it&#39;ll be out soon and chasing the kitchen (that was appreciated but there is only so much a jammed kitchen can rush I suppose). But anyhow...  <br><br>Suggest to come back only once they have normalisation of operations, say in a couple of months time.

Some days, I want something more fancy than a plate of &#34;economy rice&#34; for dinner, but am not willing to endure the crush of the Central Business District. So I hop on a bus and go to Great World City, where I spring for a fantastic Italian sausage and browned onions sandwich. Crusty bread, savoury meat, sweetly caramelised onions--how can one go wrong with that? If I don&#39;t feel like a sandwich (but I always do--it&#39;s the onions that do it), there are also more hearty options from the deli, such as risotto-stuffed chicken, that you can ask them to heat up while you pick your Tekoe tea. And for afters, go to the chiller to pick out some cake (they have one that is essentially a Snickers bar writ large--you may think 2 people can handle it; I suggest you share with more. in any case, more friends in the office is a good thing, is it not?) or pastry for afters. They also have thin-crust pizzas with a variety of toppings, as well as salads, for those of us who absolutely need something green in every meal. I enjoy Gastronomia for the range of foods they carry--eye candy and most of it delicious, so sometimes it gets really difficult to choose because my eyes are far far bigger than my stomach, though one cannot say it is not trying to keep up!

text: If u don&#39;t know what popiah is, do yourself a favor and look it up, or u betta aks sum-body!! Whatever u decide to do, DON&#39;T miss out on this super light, tasty, vegan snack at this street vendor in the Sembawang Hill Food (hawker) Center. Only $1.50 SGD for 4 pieces of this must-try treat! U can order it on the spicy-zesty side, or not (whatever floats ur boat). It took around 10-15 minutes to get mine, but well worth the wait!!

text: I think this cafe served up pretty good chicken rice. Whenever I da bao (takeaway) to eat in the office, my office secretary will always come over as she is drawn to the smell. The chicken rice is really cheap, starting at only $2.20. Chicken drumstick rice (boiled) is what I usually order and it costs around $3.50. <br><br>The chicken meat here is really smooth and tender. The rice is also fragrant especially coupled together with its sauces. The chicken rice here never fails to whet my appetite!<br><br>One thing to note though is that the main boss, a old uncle in the photo, who has deep sounding voice talks like he is scolding you. He&#39;s got great hairstyle but he ain&#39;t that friendly uncle you wanna talk with. That&#39;s why there is an assistant beside him to take your orders. Sitting environment is also not really ideal. Best to takeaway!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/5QosloirWJe7YjJed1BeaQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ananas-cafe-singapore-2?reviewid=Bhb6_Wz6-uJg2XTWRlOJ1A&select=5QosloirWJe7YjJed1BeaQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Ananas Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. soy sauce chicken + veggies $4', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'soy sauce chicken + veggies $4'}]
text: **3.5 stars**<br>I discovered this place after getting off the train. They have two kinds of chicken to choose from: soy sauce and Hainanese. We opted for the soy sauce chicken. A small portion with rice is only $2. We opted for the larger order which was $3. For about a $1 extra, you can add veggies. I was surprised they wrapped it up in paper but it worked. It held together until we got back to our hotel. The chicken was packed with flavor and super soft. It was warm, salty and went great with the fresh rice and veggies. For food right off the train and at such a low price, I was impressed.

Ananas used to dish up really affordable and delicious bee hoon at 50 cents a pop. But with expansion and many outlets later, the standard has dropped incredibly. Carbs like bee hoon, noodles, fried rice are all slick with oil, and the dishes like vegetables, fried egg, fish filet are even oiler, if that&#39;s even possible. They serve chicken rice as well, which comes in at close to 10 am, and the dude dishing out chicken rice is annoyingly flirtatious. Ever since Ananas opened at Outram Park MRT, one gets a heady dose of pungent fried chicken once the train doors open. Which was mouth watering the first couple of days, but with the greasy olfactory assault every single day, it&#39;s now descended into just plain nauseating.
Pretty chilled out place. Good finger food (chicken wings! Fries!). Cold beer, bourbon. a pool table.<br><br>Sometimes that&#39;s all you need.

text: Balestier Midnight Bak Kut Teh is definitely not the best on Balestier road. However, as the name suggests, it&#39;s the one you patronise when you stumble in search of food at 4 am because it will most certainly be open. <br><br>The bak kut teh is pepper-based and tasty, but the sides were disappointing. Our preserved vegetables were bland and watery, for instance, and the braised egg was ok but not particularly note-worthy. <br><br>Still, this makes for a decent alternative when no other choice presents itself to you. Kai Juan, at 395 Balestier road, stays open till 2 am and serves far better bak kut teh and preserved vegetables, so if you make it to the stretch earlier or during the day, you may want to check this one out instead.

text: A wonderful little local food place with friendly staff, free Wi-Fi, unlimited water and serving up some delicious brunch items, as well as specialty coffee and gonenade cakes! Not to be missed if you are in the area. Also the hours are wrong they are open Sundays as I&#39;m here right now. Everything I had was delicious from my fat free flat white to the passion fruit and orange pound cake and the fresh fruit oatmeal, and not a bad deal for all that at 23 sgd. They also aren&#39;t rude and kick you out or anything like that, they are a real local place smack next to a tourist trap. No wait no fluff and no nonsense. I loved the decor too very cute!

text: Most refreshing and healthy drinks at your disposal to beat the heat!<br><br>They have cool loyalty card as well which gives discount after a certain number of purchases and many more promotions keep happening!<br><br>Fresh fruit juices with Yakult are just amazing!

The second branch of the hugely popular bubble tea shop in Tanjong Pagar, Woobbee continues to deliver the same refreshing and cheerful experience with their bubble tea at the Shaw Tower location. There is also a stronger emphasis on coffees over at this branch, which also contains a small seating area for people to sit and chat for a bit. <br><br>Try their breakfast sets or coffee - I am convinced that it will be as good as their teas which range from milk to black and green, among some special seasonal flavours like lychee.

This is the all day dining at King&#39;s Hotel. It&#39;s main claim to fame is its Penang buffet, which seems to be available year round.<br>I was satisfied with the quality of the Penang food. Authentic, delicious, and premium priced. Expect all the usual Penang favourites buffet style without making a trip to Penang.<br><br>Reasonable value if you have a M&amp;C a-la carte card discount.

text: A refreshing place with a quiet ambience and nice view. The coffee has great reviews, although I did not try it myself. Food wise it&#39;s a variety of brown rice dishes or salads. Probably very appealing for the health-conscious. My friend had rendang chicken. While the taste was not bad, she preferred a stronger flavor. I had BBQ chicken. The meat was tender and the taste was fragrant. I like the mixture of different textures from the brown rice, potatoes, cashew nuts and chicken. Ala carte is $4.80 whereas a meal with honey lemon iced tea is $5.90 which is a pretty good deal.

text: French toast ($2.40) - 5 stars<br>On the eggy side, which was fine with me. Not too sweet.<br><br>Homemade barley ($2) - 5 stars<br>Great, not too sweet!<br><br>Steamed white bread ($3) - 4 stars<br>Good, but best when it&#39;s steaming hot. After you&#39;ve eaten the first 1-2 pieces and the others have cooled down it&#39;s really just bread. My sister was tired of the taste of the bread after the french toast and she wished we&#39;d gotten the regular kaya toast.<br><br>Ambience - 4 stars<br>Be warned it gets noisy and you can hear echoes which cause a din so we ended up having to raise our voices a little. Not the ideal place for a conversation but it&#39;ll do.

I like Earl Grey cupcake and one of the lemon taste cupcake.  Always have it go to.  This is not a big shop or a trendy cafe, but it can always fulfill my desire of sweets <br>This place is right across Geylang Bahru MRT( soon to open) so it would be easily to access.

text: I&#39;ve been wanting to visit Whisk and Paddle ever since I saw the green trees and a river that was just within a stone&#39;s throw from the café. I almost took a taxi there but decided to use the MRT instead because it was about a 21 min drive from Lavender. So during our first day in Singapore I dragged Hubby along for a joyride to Riviera LRT. Don&#39;t worry, we had never even heard about the LRT line before today but the café was within 5 minutes walking distance from the LRT.<br><br>Whisk and Paddle was a popular choice for cyclist and families especially since it was a bit of a mini getaway place from the always busy city. I think a lot of people appreciate the change of scenery that they could find within the small area. <br><br>Service was really good and the staff was quite attentive as every customer were given glasses of cold water right as they sat down. There was a small kids&#39; corner where little boys and girls can enjoy some activities using toys provided by the café. If you can&#39;t bear the humidity, there is also indoor seating available for customers.<br><br>One important tip: as soon as you get off the Riviera LRT, take a lift / stair down and use your google maps to locate the Punggol Police Station. Once you&#39;ve found the police station, there&#39;s a restaurant complex nearby (Popeye&#39;s Chicken, Seafood restaurant etc and you will see the Whisk and Paddle café soon enough).<br><br>FOOD<br>The humid weather made hubby crave cold drinks more than usual so he ordered a glass of yellow mango smoothie. I went with the black sesame latte instead, a drink that will certainly make a person conscious of having black sesame powder stuck on their teeth after a few sips. I like my black sesame latte since it wasn&#39;t too strong and it came with pretty coffee art too.<br><br>We tried the Pandan Melaka waffle that came with Movenpick Vanilla Dream ice cream, cubic butter cakes, roasted cashew, gula Melaka and bits of cornflakes. Today&#39;s waffle was crispy and it had a really good texture. The Madagascar vanilla icecream didn&#39;t disappoint too and to be honest it was probably the best vanilla ice cream that I ever tasted! Every material worked well together and also perfect to be shared between two people. Next time I will request an extra bowl of gula Melaka ;-).

text: After seeing a billion people posting pictures up on Facebook/Instagram, and since I got the car this weekend, we finally got to try Whisk &amp; Paddle. <br><br>Note that it may be a bit out of the way for those that don&#39;t drive, but hey, it&#39;s Singapore, there&#39;s MRTs&amp;LRT: everywhere! The place overlooks a waterbody so you&#39;ll have a really beautiful view while having your meal. <br><br>We had the carbonara, fries with truffle mayo, and the whisk breakfast (or something like that). To be quite honest, there was nothing super special about both. I felt the carbonara was nice, but there was this strange aftertaste I couldn&#39;t put my finger around, but I assume it was because of the garlic. The breakfast platter was nice, I especially liked the scramble eggs. <br><br>On another note, the portions are beyond generous, and their vanilla latte was  loved the fact that they had Brother&#39;s toffee apple cider there as well. Would probably come back for the drinks and atmosphere.

text: One of my favourite places, whether for meeting up with friends, or just having some quiet time. Even though it&#39;s usually packed whenever I go there, there are smaller tables set in a corner of the restaurant where it&#39;s a bit quieter and I can get some work done. The staff are always accommodating and attentive, and I love the desserts, especially the waffles, though they&#39;re a bit pricy. Food&#39;s pretty good too!

text: Service and Ambience are pretty good. The dishes we ordered were decently prepared. Though the fish did have a different batter, the marination could have been better. If not for the fish, would have given a rating of 4.<br><br>It also has a small play area for patrons with young kids.

text: This little stall at the corner of the coffee shop is like a hidden gem. The only thing that the stall sell is peanut pancake aka Ban Chiang Kueh. There are two types of it. One type is the big round peanut pancake where it will be cut into different equal parts. The other type is the small oval shape one.<br><br>I particularly like the small oval shape one. I will usually ask the uncle for red bean flavor and sprinkle peanut over it. The red bean wasn&#39;t too sweet but very generous. Peanut used will overlap the red bean. Amazingly, uncle is only selling one for 70cents. <br><br>Finding the stall may be quite hard but you will be lead by the smell of peanuts and recognize the stall as it is usually filled with peanut spilled all over the counter. Whenever I am there, I will see Uncle preparing large order. People place huge order like 20 and above and you will see uncle baking the pancake nonstop. <br><br>For someone like me who don&#39;t usually like Peanut Pancake, I strongly recommended the stall and it deserve the 5 star. Open from Mon to Fri: 8am to 5pm
Recently opened and I doubt it will be around for long! $7 for a small, so so, slice of cake. With a distracted and careless service... Won&#39;t go back!
Wonderful food, wine, and service!  Just finished up a meeting in the area and wanted something hearty and healthy.  My hats off to Mahota Commune.

text: A feast for all the senses! Sustainably sourced ingredients are delicately crafted into whimsical and flavorful dishes at the restaurant in Mahota Commune. The service is also to notch and impeccable. <br><br>Tip: Call ahead to make reservations especially if your party is big.<br><br>I enjoyed a Heidinger pale ale poured into super chilled Steins. Then they served bread at room temperature with nutty olive oil and balsamic. At the table, there is cracked pepper and salt to dress the dip. Furthermore, there is a sauce station where you can dip your bread or accompany your meal with delicious bursts of flavor: Black sesame, pesto, ginger, tomato, konbu, And a secret Spicy Mahota blend. At the station, they also have thinly sliced chilies, minced garlic, green onion and cilantro.<br><br>I chose the 9 Element Set with meat. There is also a 9 Element Set that is vegetarian.<br>This tasting set arrived in a lovely wooden box with a lid. The server revealed my meal with flair. It was overwhelmingly beautiful. I ate across the rows from top to bottom, left to right. I enjoyed the cold kebab of handcrafted sausage, cantaloupe ball and grape tomato with a tangy citrus sauce. Cold cut thinly sliced roast beef with carrot filigree and caviar-like goodness. I accompanied that course with the ginger and black sesame sauces. I also enjoyed the Konbu salad and the smoke salmon. My parents shared the hot pot. Wow! The broth was super tasty after all the raw ingredients were added and enjoyed. Our table also ordered the mushroom soup that was smooth and creamy. The humongous pork knuckle was tasty and texturrific! The crackling was fabulous. Try the meat with the different sauce offering!<br><br>The wait staff was always there clearing plates and making sure that there was plenty of water and other libations desired. Mahota is a great place to eat and feel good about sending love to Mother Earth!

Man, the food here is healthy and delicious. <br><br>And the staff is so friendly and smiley. It&#39;s so rare for good local service so that really made an impression for me. <br><br>It&#39;s seriously a great find! We devoured the food so fast, so didn&#39;t have time to take pictures. We had the organic quinoa fruit salad, the tagliatelle and the salmon. The Tagliatelle was delicious! Those hand made pasta has the right texture. And the sauce was just nice. And so was the salad, fresh and yummy. Everything was tasty yet felt clean after eating. <br><br>They have hotpot for one, so will have to be back to try that next time. <br><br>Great ambience too and they have a supermarket and a cafe next door, and yoga studio, even a childcare centre across a bridge, all part of the Mahota family.

text: I love this place, mainly because I work nearby and it&#39;s amazingly convenient to get good quality organic produce without having to go out of my way.<br><br>Prices are not cheap (as with most organic produce in Singapore). While they have their own organic farm in Shanghai (why China I wonder...), the fresh produce looks to be mainly from Australia. <br><br>The dried grocery are all healthy and wholesome. Case in point: you can&#39;t even find white rice here, only brown rice, quinoa, etc. <br><br>There&#39;s also a restaurant and cafe that serves up food that&#39;s sold in their supermarket. You get the pasta, pizza, sandwiches and even hotpot. <br><br>Join as member and you get some loyalty perks.

text: In Singapore looking for a great coffee! Mahota Commune occupy the entire third floor, at 809 French Rd Singapore. Entirely devoted to healthy living. A kitchen, DIY space, Activity studio, Pantry, Market Wellness Centre. All set out in a modern open plan design. As we walked around the third floor, we were impressed with the fresh, organic choices available. The Cafe is situated near a child&#39;s play area. The Barista David is X Sydney and is fully aware of the Australian coffee scene. We were impressed with the service, the functionality, of this wonderfully created business area. If you are in Singapore and from down under, desiring a good coffee, with some healthy food choices, this could be for you. An excellent find, will return, very impressed.

text: Excellent service and food, prices are cheap and reasonable. If you order rice they even offer you extra rice. Delivery is done only within the building. Definitely a recommended place to go, thanks for all the warm meals:)

text: a tiny reminder, in the form of a tip, was posted not too long ago, that i have not written a review for this nondescript outlet. <br>thank you!:)<br><br>this place is always crowded but their staff seems to be able to cope with the captive volume of patrons, nonetheless.<br>ever prompt in clearing the tables and always courteous whether taking your order or when thanking you as you leave.<br><br>food on the average is of the a-ok variety but their soft boiled eggs are done as it should be, just cooked enough to still remain softly curdled whites yet with runny rich yolks.<br>two small warm dishes are provided instead of what many competitors will provide, one.<br>you see, one is for you to crack your eggs into and the other is for you to dump them shells, instead of messing up the table.<br><br>their teh c, kosong(sugarless) for me, is always the right consistency in terms of colour, taste and temperature.<br>and to recently discover orange chiffon cake here, wow, a fluffy citrus consummation with teh c kosong, indeed.<br><br>and if you happen to take the mrt to novena station, like i do everyday, you will be sheltered, rain or shine, as you walk over for a pit stop here before going home.<br>if it rains, then it might well be a longer pit stop penalty than in F1 races.  <br><br>there, done and dusted!:)

Always been a big fan of Toast Box, particularly this location in Novena. The curry chicken rice set is good enough... However, my favorite is the noodles topped with fried chicken. Unfortunately, this dish seems to have been replaced with noodles topped with hot dog / sausage??? WTH. The sausage is good, but it&#39;s no fried chicken! <br><br>Getting your morning teh c or kopi c before you head to Novena MRT can be a bit of a pain (I.e long lines) but in my view is well worth it, especially if you live on the other end of Tan Tock Seng Hospital. The other teh c / kaya butter bread places just don&#39;t cut it my view, particularly the ones in Marina Square.<br><br>Heaven forbid you find yourself in Tan Tock Seng Hospital or like me have to walk through TTSH to get to the MRT, this is the place to eat or to get your cup of joe.

Sundried tomato loaf', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Sundried tomato loaf'}]
text: I absolutely love the bread loaves here. I have never tried any of the small pastries, but everytime I get the sundried tomato loaf, I wonder how does something so simple make me so happy munching it.<br><br>The olive loaf is also good, much softer in the centre than the sundried tomato. But I personally still prefer the sundried tomato one. It has a great crusty top layer, with a doughy chewy moist and flavorful soft centre. So good that I can eat it on its own. You have to like chewy bread though. Yum! <br><br>They supply mostly to other restaurants and cafés. The store itself is tiny and not meant for a lot of walkin customers.

text: I&#39;m into sourdough bread. But disappointed that there&#39;s yeast in the sourdough bread too, although in minute amounts. There is no sour tang in the bread. Crust is chewy and crumb is moist and chewy, I like. But not much flavour in the bread.<br><br>The olive bread is salty. Crumbs are airy and soft. Lots of small pieces of olives, fragrant.

text: First time I tried something from the Bread Project was at Toby&#39;s Estate. There couldn&#39;t be a better combination than Croissant and coffee. No wonder the Parisians love this. The croissant was an airy, flaky and buttery delight that left me wanting. Heard that its from TBP and I knew I had to try more at its store. <br><br>So I did. It&#39;s a small shop front in the joo Chiat area and people were streaming in for the artisan bakes and breads. There weren&#39;t many options left for the pastries and I managed to get hold of a Kouign amann, orange cream tart and croissant. <br><br>Long story short, the croissant was still as delightful. Not too impressed w the orange cream tart. And I prefer the texture of Tiong bahru bakery&#39;s KA.

It was the next big bread thing... <br><br>In the early days, I&#39;d struggle to get anything when I stopped by their bread bar - they&#39;d sell out so quick! I even considered pre-ordering, but I&#39;d have had to buy $30 worth of bread and pastries, and that was more than my belly could handle. Thankfully, they started supplying a couple of cafes I frequented, so I finally got a chance to try them out, at a different price of course, but beggars can&#39;t be choosers.<br><br>I marvelled at the fresh artisan breads, tasty stuff too! this was a time before Maison Kayser, Paul and Baker and Cook came into the picture. I really enjoyed their sticky buns and the exotic sounding bostok. When I saw a Kouign Amaan as well, I had to get one - this is after I tried one for the first time at a Joel Robuchon bakery in Tokyo -  so I found myself picking up a couple whenever I saw some.<br><br>Then as the story goes, they got popular, and the bread tastes a little different now. They still run a brisk business, and I&#39;d say still worth a try.

Yes! Without any doubt the best bakery in Singapore - better than the posh French in Takashimaya. I love going there on a weekend morning to get my croissants and wholewheat bread and some sweet treat. Last time: appleflap. THis is as Belgian as it gets, although the bakery is Malay run (as far as I can judge). Only negative point: they only open at 9 am.

I can&#39;t stop eating! And yet my attempts to put on weight and keep it on have been futile. I think I have worms in my tummy. <br><br>A little birdie raved about this place to me. She went on and on about their breads, especially the Épi de Blé, Orange Cream Tart and Almond Croissant. She adviced me to go early - regulars just come and swipe the items off their shelves! So earlier this week, I hurried to this bakery before noon on Tuesday to get my breakfast before reporting for my afternoon shift in town.<br><br>Hungry, I bought whatever my buddy recommended.  I was surprised to discover that the base of the Orange Cream Tart is not the crusty kind but is actually soft bread. I found it a little too sweet though. The Almond Croissant and Épi de Blé were winners! The latter may appear alien, but it makes eating bread less messy - you won&#39;t grumble about crumbs falling on your clothes anymore! <br><br>The bakery is too far for me to visit more often though. I don&#39;t go to Joo Chiat that frequently, so I&#39;ll just try out other offerings at the cafes they supply.

text: It used to be better...<br><br>I used to frequent Bread Project on a regular basis but a recent visit made me disappointed with the quality. Got myself a baguette, pain au chocolat &amp; a kouign amann. <br><br>The pain au chocolat was ok but the baguette unfortunately was hard and the kouign amann equally disappointing. I&#39;d recommend Maison Kayser to get your baguette fix, and Tiong Bahru Bakery for the buttery &amp; flaky kouign aman instead.

text: Great great views of the Marina! The beer was top notch - excellent variety and very smooth. Definitely worth getting the beer paddle / flight. Service was also very good.<br><br>The food was decent - perhaps price outweighed the quality which is why I am knocking down a star. Pork chop was good, as were the fries. Brussel sprouts not my fave. My coworkers had the sirloin and didn&#39;t think it was worth it.<br><br>I would still 100% come back here and I definitely will!!!

text: If it&#39;s raining, don&#39;t bother to come here. <br>U need to see the spectacular view on sunny day and night time.<br><br>Great combination to hang out with your partner/close buddies or at least someone you enjoy to be with. <br>Food and beer is decent.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/xxpNmRPfRTdpEVHZfBgF5g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=juOj0R_fihCwYEwBZZ5mVQ&select=xxpNmRPfRTdpEVHZfBgF5g', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Breathtaking views, very meh beer.<br><br>Wow, the views from this bar are absolutely phenomenal and a must see at least once in Singapore. <br><br>The bar prides itself as the tallest brewery in the world, which is rather gimicky. I tried the beer flight, and the beers were just not good. We also ordered the sweet potato fries, which were much better - really well seasoned and loaded with flavor. <br><br>If you call in for a reservation, make sure to ask for an outside table, because the inside views are blocked by the windows. Otherwise, there are a few standing tables outside for walk-ins if you&#39;re lucky!

text: This is one place which has managed to get the food, drinks and view all in one place. and have done a great job. <br><br>There&#39;s internal seating where the food menu leans towards finer dining and the outside veranda where the view is absolutely awe inspiring but with limited small plated menu. <br><br>Our party of 3 had dinner inside and moved to an outside table for drinks and dessert. This was a great combination!

text: Where to start...the view is incredible if you do end up finding this tucked away place. It can be difficult, but not to fear yelpers are here! You will find this snazzy restaurant and craft brewery perched high from the 33rd level of Marina Bay Financial Centre, Tower #1. My recommendation is to follow the pictures I posted if you are unfamiliar with the area.<br><br>Looking out across the wonderful Marina Bay city scape is sublime and the main reason to have this place as a must see! Sure the alcohol and food prices might be high, but so are you taking in a view that can only be paralleled from a small list of places (unless you happen to work in these skyscrapers) and you can post some of the coolest pictures of a Singapore trip from here! <br><br>One of the unique features is the in-house brewery itself which is decent, but the view is paid in the premium and it is a place I would be back again to bring a group out to enjoy the view as well.

It was about 14$ for a .5 liter beer but in the US you pay up to 25$ for a beer at a ball game. This is a microbrew brewery beer.  The stout was lite and so tasty. It put a smile on my face. The views are a hell wow yes; We will be here every night we have left!! Seriously the views and beers prices are not that bad considering the cool experience.  It&#39;s an ambiance to be part of.  <br>Casual wear outside on the patio.  Inside nicer attire is preferred. Dinner I&#39;d make reservations and ask for our door seating. It looked very popular. <br>Desserts the cereal was the best.  The stout ice cream espresso.  The Coffee had a dark bold taste. If you&#39;re a coffee fan. This is the dessert for you. It was for me. <br><br>I&#39;m going to tout the beer again. I only had the stout but again the first sip I had a smile on my face and felt at home.

text: This microbrewery located at the top of Singapore overlooking the Marina has one of the most breathtaking views of the city. The atmosphere is smart casual, buzzing with activity. Our server was gracious and knowledgeable, providing the right level of attention that one would expect at a restaurant of this stature. <br><br>For my meal I ordered the beef tenderloin with a fried potato. The meat was cooked to perfection. I had a great meal in a great spot with a great view with great company. This place is a must.

text: LeVel33 is currently the World&#39;s Highest Urban Craft-brewery.  Enjoy a full food menu, craft beers, and/or crafted beer cocktails, with an amazing view of the Marina Bay and city skyline.  They also have a wine selection.  The restaurant has an awesome modern vibe, with warm wood tones.  A reservation is highly recommended to secure a spot here.  When you enter the large Financial Center building head to tower 1.  There will be a desk at the base of the elevators were you confirm your reservation and they will give you admittance to the elevator that heads straight to the restaurant.  The elevator will take you up 33 floors quickly (my ears popped). The doors open directly into the restaurant were you will be greeted by the smell of brewing beer.<br><br>Their crafted brews are of European heritage and made using state-of-the-art technology by SALM &amp; Co Gmbh. They have a 33.1 Blond Lager, 33.15 India Pale Ale, 33.3 Stout, 33.4 House Porter and 33.9 Wheat Beer, with seasonal brews on the menu.  You can see the beautiful copper kettles, and silver beer vats as you walk throughout the space.  You can order a beer paddle which gives you a 0.1 litre taster of five LeVeL33 craft brews (of your choice from the options available).  This is a perfect amount for sharing.  The seasonal Golden ale was the table favorite.  The other beers were OK.  Very 1 dimensional.  Lacked character or flavor.  Had a single flavor profile which made it pair well within their beer cocktails.  Their beer cocktails are unique and tasty.  I would highly recommend them as the way to go here for the price. <br><br>The food menu highlights European classics with a twist. The food was GREAT.  Out of the sides our table favorite was the pumpkin.  The broccolini, corn, and heirloom tomato were also tasty.  <br><br>The starters are also good.  The Ploughman&#39;s board was the best.  The seafood medley was OK.  I would definitely suggest the ploughman&#39;s board as the cured meats were addictively tasty.  I loved the crostini and rye bread that they came with.  Be sure to save room for the mains!<br><br>Our table had a mix of different mains.  From fish, to the different options of gnocchi, to the Beef &amp; Reef, and grilled meats.  Everything was cooked to perfection. The chevre gnocchi was OK, the original gnocchi was better.  The Beef and Reef was pricey, but good.  It is quite the show as they bring out the lobster and throw it in a pot of boiling water for a minute.  The meat cut like butter.  Amazing flavors and large portions.  You will leave full.  <br><br>The prices are high. This would be a place for special occasions.  You pay for tasty food and excellent views.  Unfortunately, the beer wasn&#39;t great, but if you stick to beer cocktails or their other selection of drinks you will be OK.  With the large price tag you want to ensure you are getting something great.<br><br>The service was friendly and prompt for Singapore.  <br>.

text: Always a pleasure! The view rivals most in Singapore as you look out from over 30 floors above the Marina Bay. The night show at 8:30 is clearly visible and the city is stunning. I advise getting there before 6 for a view at the railing. The fries are tasty and the beer sampler is a good value. Still haven&#39;t actually had dinner there, but the food looks good!

text: We have the ultra lounge, Singapore has the sky bar or rooftop bar.<br><br>Quintessential to the culture these bars are located on the top floors of office buildings.  They showcase incredible views of the city with both indoor and coveted outdoor seats.  Pricey mixed drinks and upscale bar food satisfy the up-and-coming youth and the well established alike.<br><br>Level 33 has it all including incredible craft beer brewed on site.  The beer has a strong European influence. More classic malts and hops result in a cleaner, more restrained aroma and flavor than the in your face American style.<br><br>On this visit, a very British style IPA. Extremely refreshing finishing only slightly better. Extremely clean on the palate. The stout, dark and brooding with excellent roasted grain notes and a sweet finish. Finally the wheat beer, very German in flavor. Unfiltered, beautiful citrus and banana notes, finishing sour.  Basically any of these beers could be bottled and sold as European. They&#39;re that good.<br><br>All beer served in 0.3 L or 0.5 L pours.<br><br>Note: prices increase on all drinks after 20:00.  Think of it as a nighttime view charge.<br><br>Sadly no food sampled. I could not get my dining companion to eat the kangaroo or a dish called pig and snails.<br><br>Excellent, proper service.<br><br>Located in CBD, MBFC T1, 33rd floor.  Look for its separate elevator. Reservations recommended. It gets busy by 18:00.<br><br>Note: despite how busy the taxi stand is,  it is incredibly difficult to hail a taxi.  Be sure to use Grab.<br><br>And essential experience while visiting Singapore.

text: This review is based on two visits. Both were very enjoyable evenings.<br><br>The view from the restaurant/brewpub is quite extraordinary and is an obvious draw to LeVel33. There are other restaurants and bars with great views but you can&#39;t go wrong with a visit to the bar for a cocktail or brew.<br><br>In addition to the bar, there are indoor and outdoor tables. The ambiance is interesting. It&#39;s  rather loud and appears to be a mix of after-work office workers and other patrons who go for the view. Overall, it&#39;s very pleasant. <br><br>The staff on both occasions that I visited were very friendly and attentive. Service was excellent.<br><br>It&#39;s a brewhouse and restaurant in one. I tried about 4 different beers. All were good but none were special. Like the beer, the food was good but it wasn&#39;t great. Unlike the beer, the food is pricey.<br><br>Our steaks were cooked to order. The tenderloin was very good. The ribeye was very thin. It was definitely disappointing. I expect ribeyes to be triple the thickness of the steak that I was served. It was tasty but the flavor fell short of top notch steakhouses.<br><br>My party split a Level33 Mess, which was a mess of shapes, colors, textures and flavors. It was good but nothing special. I think whoever created this dessert was trying too hard to come up with something different and unique.<br><br>Prices are what you might expect for a restaurant with a view in the financial district of Singapore but not ridiculous given the restaurant&#39;s decor, service, and the view.<br><br>It&#39;s worth a visit for the view, nice ambience, and good service. The food is decent too; just don&#39;t expect great food or beer.

Better than your other rooftop bar options because you get an in-house brewery along with the best night time view (why go to the top of MBS when MBS IS part of the view??). The place was packed on a weekday night, but you can definitely still snag a table outside with a little wait. We got the beer flight -- IPA was good and I liked the ordering from light to dark brews. Combined with the elevated ambiance and stunning city view, LeVel33 should definitely be a top visit for rooftop bars!

text: I like coming here at sunset on a weekend because it&#39;s quiet and there&#39;s a great view without having to fight off the crowds that you&#39;d get at One Altitude or on the MBS rooftop. The fact that there&#39;s a microbrewery on the 33rd floor of a building is pretty cool and I think some of their beers are quite nice despite not being a beer drinker at all.<br><br>The beers and drinks are on the pricey side, as are the food options. However, since it&#39;s a bar with a view, it&#39;s not bad. And at least they taste pretty decent. Service is pretty non-existent but it&#39;s nice to be left alone. If you go early, you won&#39;t need a reservation but might get kicked out by 6 or 7pm.

text: I&#39;ve been to this place a few times and what I have to say will mostly be about the beer and the views. <br><br>First off, if you&#39;re planning a visit here for a meal, do yourselves a favor and book a reservation beforehand. If you love eating outside and beautiful views of Singapore; make sure that reservation is outside. The views at this place are spectacular! Some of the best in the city. Now, the food is in my honest opinion, nothing to write home about. I&#39;ve had a few different things off the menu and nothing ever knocked me off my feet. Last night, my wife took me here for my birthday dinner, I had the truffle linguine, she had the brewery burger. For sides we shared the roasted potatoes and the mushroom dish. The potatoes were cooked well, but were mostly bland and flavorless. The mushrooms had some taste, but still quite bland for my tastebuds. The linguine was excellent, a perfect portion that paired well with my IPA. Do not forget that this place is a Brewery, so have a beer. Leave the wine for other restaurants! The IPA was so great I had 2. I&#39;m a huge IPA fan, but you can follow my reviews on Untappd, not on Yelp. <br><br>All in all, the restaurant gets a 3 for food and a 5 for the views and the atmosphere.

text: [Directions: Go to Tower 1, then walk around to the left-hand side past Standard Chartered and you will see the LeVeL33 lift]<br><br>I&#39;m super-surprised this hasn&#39;t been added already to Yelp, with a good 50-100 reviews, as the views of the Singapore skyline from the balcony here are absolutely incredible. <br><br>The bar opens around 11-30am, and has a wide-range of craft beers brewed on-premises. There are two separate parts to LeVeL33. There is a restaurant, which caters to well-dressed office people; and a bar on the balcony, which sees casual groups of flip-flop wearing individuals in shorts, sunnies, t-shirts. I&#39;m reviewing from the latter point-of-view.<br><br>The balcony is just a great outdoor experience with a ~240 degree-view of Singapore. You can see visually from Fullerton Hotel -to- The Esplanade -to- the Marina Bay waterway -to- The Float -to- The Art Science Museum -to- MBS -to- Gardens by the Bay -to- Ships in Singapore Strait -to- the other towers of Marina Boulevard (and slightly beyond).<br><br>The beers are interesting and tasty. I tried the IPA (quite strong and heady) and the Lager (much easier drinking) and enjoyed both. Given the location, the drinks were expensive, but this was to be expected, and I cannot fault them on pricing.<br><br>However, where there is a disconnect to the bar is the lack-of-food options. There is a food menu that accompanies the drink menu, but whilst the bar opens at 11-30am, the bar food is not available until 2-30pm (I think this is because they do not want a clash with their restaurant). This 3-hour window of difference between drink-and-food ensures that if you are interested in a session you&#39;ll have to basically go elsewhere because you&#39;ll be drunk well before 2-30pm arrives.<br><br>This is exactly what our crew did (there was 8 of us). We were 3-4 drinks in, and needed food to accompany any further alcohol, and since there was a significant wait ahead of us, we decided to leave and go elsewhere despite this location being fantastic.<br><br>Service *appears* to be patchy. Before arriving, one of our team was reporting that service was very slow, whilst upon my arrival I had no trouble gaining the attention of servers whenever my beer was running low. So this might be something to think about when it gets busy (it wasn&#39;t very busy when we were there).<br><br>I feel like this bar is a must-visit, even if you just come up for 1-2 drinks and enjoy the view (take a video or a pano) then head back down. For tourists it&#39;s literally 30 minutes of your day to capture an incredible view of the city and won&#39;t cost you an arm-and-a-leg like MBS does. <br><br>NB: LeVeL33 has its own lift in Tower 1 of Marina Boulevard, and is located to the very left-hand side past the Standard Chartered signage. You cannot miss the LeVeL33 signage, once you see that, the lift is located in the alcove next to it.

text: We visited on Singapore Day and had a great time. The rooftop terrace has incredible views of Marina Bay and it was the perfect place to watch the holiday fireworks! We ordered the beer tasting paddle which gives you five 0.1 liter of craft brews and is a great option for sharing and two beer cocktails. Definitely worth a visit if you&#39;re a beer lover!

text: This place is actually such a hidden gem. There is no cover fee to enter and the views were amazing. I got a pale ale for around $14 which was quite expensive but the views made it super worth it. Plus, the ale was brewed right in the bar--they have a huge brewery. <br><br>You can see the whole MBS from here plus the flyer and almost the whole downtown core! The outdoor patio was absolutely gorgeous, but too bad there were no seats and the tables could not be reserved (FCFS). Still, this place is spectacular to bring a date to or to come alone for a beer and enjoy the views of Singapore!

text: What a find! I heard about this place because they were promoting it on my hotel&#39;s travel channel. We decided to check it out for some drinks and small bites on our last day in Singapore. Glad we did! Beautiful views of the Singapore skyline and great drinks to enjoy. If you&#39;re not a beer person, worry not. They have an awesome list of craft cocktails that you can choose from. The food was very good as well. The shrimps were probably the largest I have seen in Singapore. I would highly recommend this restaurant.

text: Came here for pre-dinner cocktails in Nov 2019 on the recommendation of a family member who&#39;s a local. I give it 5 stars for the amazing view and the beer, 5 stars for the amazing service and minus 1 Star for the funny tasting mojitos.  Clearly one of the best views from a bar in Singapore!<br><br>I wish I could remember our server&#39;s name because he was so kind and attentive!  We were there with my 80-year-old mom and we had been standing while waiting for a table for about 30 minutes. This server was attending to the tables on the other side of the outdoor area.  He came up to us and told us that as soon as the previous customers left, he had reserved a table next to the railing with a prime view, so that my mom could get off her feet and have a lovely place to sit!  How nice was that.<br><br>No question, we will come back to LeVel33 whenever we&#39;re in Singapore.

text: I think this hits the sweet spot in terms of value for money and views of the singapore skyline. Has the worlds highest craft brewery which might sound a bit gimmicky but the beer is pretty good and if you get in before 8 its not even that expensive (~8-9 SGD). The view is staggeringly good, if you don&#39;t have a table, order a beer and head outside and enjoy the cold brew while you have the entire SP sklyline as a backdrop.

text: My wife and I celebrated our wedding anniversary at LeVeL 33 two days ago. The first impression was &#34;great, they have mini brewery all the way up at level 33&#34;. The beer of course was refreshing and nice. I must say that the ambiance and view from level 33 looking out to the Singapore river and Esplanade was fantastic. <br><br>Now come the food. Well,  I was a bit disappointed with the food as it  was just &#39;ok&#39;. We ordered the Pig &amp; Ssnail and Hokkaido Scallop for starters. The starters were fine. Unique mixture of the cream sauce blended well with the pork belly. The scallop was much nicer, again with good blending with the cream sauce. As for the mains, we ordered the Jumbo Prawns and Australian Bangalow Pork. The presentation was great but the they tasted as I mentioned earlier &#39;ok&#39; only. They were pretty plain and &#34;not enticing&#34;. The portion was more than enough for the both of us. As for the desserts, the mini chocolate lava cake was good. Not so much the same for the rest of the chocolate stuffs. <br><br>Finally, their service. I must say the service was excellent. The staffs were firendly and they replace new clean plates after each course. <br><br>In conclusion, if you are going there for the ambiance and the beer, that   would be a great place to go. If you are expecting great food, other places like Morton, Ruth Christ, Lawrey&#39;s might be a better choice.

text: Been here a couple of times to unwind after work. They labelled themselves as the &#34;world highest urban craft brewery&#34; and man, actually the view up here is splendid! Take the inside seats facing outdoors, as it&#39;s really not that chill after all staying outdoors in this 365 summer Singapore.<br><br>I chanced upon a post by a friend on the Saturday brunch buffet and decided to give it a try for my big boy&#39;s birthday. It&#39;s a minimalist brunch compared to the hotels buffet we usually come across, which I like about it as the selection is small but great individually! We made reservation through a 3rd party app, and the staff called to confirm my reservation the day before. On Saturday itself, we were held up by some errands on the morning which we called to delay our reservations twice, and the staff responded positively to our request and I&#39;m truly thankful for that!<br><br>The selection are very clear in 1 small confined area. Cold selection, hot selection, cheese, soup, desserts. That&#39;s all we&#39;ve got. There&#39;s nothing international about the Saturday brunch. Cold selection includes salami, some seafood, salad. Hot selection includes foei gras, mini eggs ben, mini blue cheese quiche tartlets, roast beef, sausages, and 2 more dishes I couldn&#39;t recall. Desserts and cheeses are cluttered at one corner. Well, I&#39;ll pass the soup next time. Soup served on that day was a tomato relish sort of soup (well it&#39;s not labelled), and it tasted super salty which I stopped after 2 mouthfuls. There&#39;s also a selection of bread which you can choose to go with it. Apart from the soup, I love how all the rest are served so nicely.<br><br>The highlight of the brunch is definitely their craft beers, beer cocktails, and special beer cocktails of the month! It&#39;s your a hardcore beer drinker, you can opt to top it up for the &#34;beer buffet&#34; version from the normal buffet price of $58++. Alternatively, you can order the beer separately. For a brewery, buffet and beer combination is definitely the way to go!<br><br>One of the nays will probably go to the service. Staff do not give you much attention and you just gotta try your best to wave hard, or go up to them. My plates are not cleared promptly, neither was my water filled. I don&#39;t know if it&#39;s the privacy time which they are trying to give us, or they simply don&#39;t care. However, they are not rude la, still can make it.<br><br>Finally, the view up here is a true win! We enjoyed the lovely view over brunch, which makes our Saturday slow paced and relaxed. They also live up to their name as a brewery for the tasty draft they served! It was an enjoyable weekend brunch which I&#39;ll be back again.

text: Quick the interesting place. I went there mainly to try the beer, since back home in Bellingham WA, we have several craft breweries. <br><br>I tried all 6 of there beers, 5 via a beer flight. All were good, their stout was probably my favorite, porter coming in second (porter is not in the picture though).<br><br>The atmosphere was great and the view was absolutely amazing. <br><br>I would definitely recommend visiting for a beer. There food looked delicious, all I had was a salad and their mushroom flight. Things started adding up fast so I didn&#39;t get a main course. It is rather expensive, but that&#39;s how it is in Singapore. <br><br>Will definitely visit again during my next trip.

text: I&#39;d give this place a solid 4 star but their beer is just mediocre. With such high taxes being levied on alcohol in SG, I can&#39;t really complain about it as it&#39;s an uncontrollable factor. But at $22 a pint in the evening hours, you&#39;d expect the beer to taste somewhat decent, considering the place claims to be a &#34;craft beer&#34; brewery. But it&#39;s no better than what you&#39;d find in a 7-11 or such.<br><br>One thing that&#39;s worth coming here for is the awesome view! And furthermore, the light show going on right across the water is one great thing to watch while you&#39;re here soaking in the backdrop. They didn&#39;t lie when they said it was the world&#39;s highest brewery at 33 levels above ground. <br><br>Don&#39;t come here with hopes that you&#39;ll get a good beer craving satisfied. There are plenty of other places in town that offer better tasting beer just in bottles. But it&#39;s totally worth it to come just for the view alone, which makes up for their average tasting brewskies.

Honestly the best view of Singapore I&#39;ve seen since my time living here. Yes drinks are &#39;pricey&#39; --$13.33 for half liter, but with the incredible view outdoors (and my conversion of the prices to USD) it&#39;s completely worth it. <br><br>My boyfriend and I came for drinks on a Friday around 6- no reservation and of course no seated table, but we managed to get a standing table right next to the viewpoint on a pleasant evening. <br><br>Their beers were delicious and you can easily watch the gardens by the bay and marina bay light shows in the evening. Decided to get some appetizers to pick on while drinking- the lamb chops were relatively good, but the chicken winglets were not worth the cost. <br><br>Great atmosphere- can&#39;t wait to return to try their pumpkin beer.
Great lunch venue with excellent views! Appetizer buffet was great and really enjoyed the diverse selections. Salmon presentation was gorgeous colored with beets. A bit over cooked on the fish.

text: Ticking off the rooftop bars, we headed here largely because they have their own on-premise brewery. <br><br>We managed to get a table (but no seats) at the balcony, ordered some snacks, and sampled their wares. Their own brew beers are good, on a par with some of the better craft beers I&#39;ve tried, and whilst a little pricey due to the location it wasn&#39;t extortionate.<br><br>Our food was good, a mix of sausage, hummus, and bread, and the service was top notch, very attentive and friendly.<br><br>Obviously the view is the main attraction, it&#39;s one of the better views available, but I&#39;d definitely go back to try the full menu.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/HDd8Nq4yD_93pSyIJd7xag/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=v6Rj9Wx4qRKvttmVpDslZA&select=HDd8Nq4yD_93pSyIJd7xag', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore. caramel and goat&#39;s cheese', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "caramel and goat's cheese"}]
text: nice, chill place to hang out with a glass of wine - and have a dessert (or two). this local microbrewery is pretty top-of-its-class, with a view up on its place on the thirty-third floor (the name&#39;s a no-brainer, really), with a good selection of food and drinks, a good mix of standing and sit-down space - and it feels pretty cozy, even with the throngs of people that come here post-work.<br><br>I&#39;d like to talk about their desserts too (a proper meal here is still a pending to-do) - and in particular, this interpretation of a sticky date pudding with triangular block of cake topped with a fig compote and goat&#39;s cheese caramel. it&#39;s a subtly sweet cake that plays up to the sharp savoriness of the goat&#39;s cheese (which isn&#39;t something I usually eat, but this was properly moderated), and the soft vanilla ice cream on the side.<br><br>very pretty, very modern, and a well-portioned plate of enough sweet to sate without cloying.<br><br>I&#39;ve also tried their fondant previously, and it&#39;s pretty good too - but I&#39;m working my way up to the assiette, which is a two-person platter of dessert. I could really do with one right now.<br><br>p.s. it&#39;s a nice view outside, but too damn hot. I&#39;ll stick with the aircon.

text: LeVeL33 has no cover charge like 1-Altitude and in my opinion, offers better views of MBS/Marina Bay, but does not offer 360 degree views of the city.  I personally preferred this chill spot over 1-Altitude.<br><br>LeVeL33 specializes in craft beers, but I opted for a girly drink instead.  I ordered a skyline (gin, blueberry stuff, ginger beer, mint) which the bartender generously gave me for free for my birthday - he didn&#39;t even check my passport!  It was actually quite delicious and you couldn&#39;t taste the alcohol at all - perfect girly drink.<br><br>Drinks here are pretty pricey at $20-30/pp for your craft beer and cocktails.  Unfortunately, I didn&#39;t try the food so I can&#39;t comment on that.<br><br>Overall, I enjoyed the vibe and views of this lounge - definitely a good place for a fun and chill, but classy late evening.<br><br>(They close pretty early, like midnight on the weekday)

text: Straight Trash and inconsiderate! I have heard of all my friends raving about this place so after a very long week I decided to take my wife out and give this place a try. text: Disclaimer- tourist review. Get here early or else everyone will take up the prime spots outside with the gorgeous view. Luckily a group of us 4 came and snagged a pretty nice spot and was able to take awesome pics. Great beer and wine selection and we all just had 2 each. Of course I can&#39;t remember (not very useful, sorry) what I got but there was a pretty strong stout that was really really good. Really liked the ambiance of the entire place. It was obviously more upscale and the prices reflected that. Service could get a bit tricky at times but not a big deal. Didn&#39;t get a chance to order food except little nuts and olives. <br><br>I didn&#39;t get to dress up very much in Singapore since most people dress pretty casually but this is the one place where I could have and fit right in. I was actually a bit surprised by such a different crowd of people than what I had seen all week walking around. Anyhow, that&#39;s from a  tourist POV!

text: Views are fabulous. I went during the afternoon and sat outside. The beer price was not any more expensive than anywhere else but the view was phenomenal. text: SUMMARY: Went for a work dinner with my team with a reservation. Service was excruciatingly slow and the food was &#34;Meh. I&#39;ve experienced better.&#34; The ambiance was very luxury/formal and the view was great, but would never go back nor recommend it - even on someone else&#39;s tab.<br><br>WHAT I TRIED: Foie Gras + Seafood Medley + Ploughman&#39;s Board + Wagyu Steak + Red Wine<br><br>-------------------MORE DETAIL-------------------<br><br>FOOD: OK: Food was actually good, but not worth the price. There are so many better places for the price (and even for cheaper). I was very unimpressed with the food. The Ploughman&#39;s Board had a TON of meat, but no cheese or veggies and not enough bread/crackers - we didn&#39;t even get halfway through it despite having about 10 men in their 20s in the group! The Seafood Medley had a &#34;meh&#34; selection of seafood. The shrimp was good and that was about it. The wine and foie gras were good, but nothing special. I ordered the steak medium rare and it came out medium. It was too chewy, but it was flavorful.<br><br>SERVICE: SUBPAR: This is some of the slowest and inattentive service I&#39;ve ever had. We asked for water several times to several different waiters before half our table got water - and then the other half about 10 minutes later. I ordered a glass of wine, which was delivered to another woman in our party at the opposite end of the table - and it was only when I asked where mine was 20 minutes after ordering it that they said they had already given it to me.... except they had given it to her. <br><br>AMBIANCE: GREAT: Topnotch luxury with a great view and beautiful interior. Very fancy.

text: The best view in the city, better than the Marina Bay Sands, mostly because you get to see the Sands from here. The beer is solid and the waiter ensured we paired our flight with just the right appetizers. Its called beer dining on the menu and we tried it all pretty much, my favorite thing was the rillettes trio, the beef was so good, and the beers cleansed my palette so well, keeping me eating the entire $110 worth of apps. But even if you just want to stop for one beer and the view its worth it. The staff was very welcoming at every level. I wish I worked in this building. Thank you level33

text: Kind of gimmicky.  Great ambience and view (which is what you pay for). Food not so great. Had the Spanish octopus and beef tartare apps (so-so), jumbo prawns (tasted like soap), sirloin and asparagus for main.  Porter and stout drinks.  Porter was a little on the lighter (watery) side.  Stout tastes like what the porter should.  But we can say we have been to the worlds highest brewery :)

Here&#39;s an alternative place to view enjoy the beautiful Singapore skyline without having to push and shove against too many people. While it&#39;s best to book for the outdoor seat, you should be able to get a standing table after 9PM. Service is usually great as well!<br><br>They have a variety of beer to choose from. If you can&#39;t decide, order the sampling set first. I haven&#39;t tried their food nor their cocktails, but they look decent.
