The skyline view from the top', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The skyline view from the top'}]
text: What a great view! You can see across Marina Bay and all the shiny lit up buildings that Singapore is famous for. I met up with a decently large group of friends here with a reservation for 2 tables outside. We tried to get moved to a smoking spot because we saw some were free, but they said it was all taken, so my friends were not able to have their cigars.<br><br>The spot is very chic and modern. There&#39;s an elevator within the financial building that goes directly to the venue.<br><br>We got the craft beer sampler, with 5 samples of their own beers, then got more based on what we liked. Overall, the beers were alright. I liked the blond. I did not like the stout or the mixed stout with the pale ale, which they said was one of the beers. Lots of color but not much flavor. I know Singapore has high alcohol taxes, but you think for like $20 the beer would be better than that.<br><br>Anyways, a nice hangout spot, if a bit expensive. It does get a little windy up there.

This is my favorite go to spot for a view in Singapore.  You can get a great view of the light show at the Marina Bay Sands as well as the Gardens by the Bay.  <br><br>The service is top notch. the best anywhere in Singapore.  I have been to some of the high end restaurants here and this place is A+++ on staff.  <br><br>Food is always fresh and well presented.  Menu changes a bit but we always go for the Steak Tartare.  Just the best here. <br><br>They brew their own beer, but you can also get the usual suspects of Tiger and Heineken.  I prefer their owne brew as its always tasty.  <br><br>Do make reservations as the staff will give you the best spot in the house.  I am not a regular, but I do come as much as I can!  Way better than the other high dining, drinking spots in the area.

This resto has the best view in singapore, better than one altitude and kudeta marina bay sands. Best time to come here is sunset time around 7-7.30pm to see the sunset and changing color of the sky and buildings. 5 stars for the view, always bring visitors to visit this place to enjoy the view with snacking and beer <br><br>Food is mediocre, i would rate 2.5 stars for the food, it would be excellent if they can improve their food so it will match with the best view resto and have a great food as well<br><br>Beer - i love wheat beer, they house brew beers

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/7RKQ5tIQVwMOqZwOrfFK0Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=B7mXD54VQBV1iJHkQNw4uQ&select=7RKQ5tIQVwMOqZwOrfFK0Q', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore. Beautiful view', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Beautiful view'}]
text: Away from the tourist infested marina bay sands. Level 33 is a less crowded option with a spectacular view of the marina.  You can see at night random flashes from people&#39;s cameras at the merlion to the amazing laser light show of marina bay sands. Only part I mark off is that the staff assumed I was just their to enjoy the view and did not order my beer until I was pretty much ready to leave. But wow what a view. Go at night. You can see the heart of Singapore just buzzing from the 33rd story.  You see the lights of the garden by the bay and with Such a beautiful view. I forgot I needed a beer to enjoy myself. So where I would normally give a 2 I give this place a four.  Rule of real estate. Location location location and man what a location.

text: Great for HH.  Not a big selection of beer but what they brew is pretty good.  Awesome views of Marina Bay!  I got there at 1630 and had my choice of tables on the patio, 30 minutes later the place was packed!!

We came here for dinner and it was pretty unmemorable. The food that is. The view is awesome though. I would suggest to come here for a drink or two. Grab a table outside and enjoy the sunset.<br><br>Bar food is decent. The mains are very average, not worth the price. Also the layout of the restaurant section is quite bad. Diners seated towards the window or middle could be hemmed in when it is full as all the chairs are back to back when seated, leaving no space for people to pass through. Not sure if that layout has changed now.

text: 5 Stars for the view, 3.5 stars for the food.  These views over Marina Bay from the outdoor patio are amazing.  Definitely worth the price of admission.<br><br>I dined here with colleagues from work and had a fun time and a good meal.  The meal was not spectacular but it was tasty.  The views from atop Singapore are the reason to dine here.<br><br>The wine selection is fairly good, I found several bottles of French wine that met the needs of our group nicely.  The wine list mostly consists of Australian wine which you would expect in this area of the world.<br><br>I would come back again for a leisurely dinner with colleagues to take in the great views.

text: It was the mom in law&#39;s birthday and the missus wanted to treat her to a luxurious Sunday brunch. if you have ever tried looking for a good Sunday brunch, most of the recommendations are for hotel buffets. but if you, like the missus, are not fans of buffets because you simply do not eat enough to make it worth your while, then you will have trouble.<br><br>That&#39;s when we discovered that Level33 serves Sunday roast - the wonderful English tradition of pubs serving Roast and other food on Sundays that still lingers fondly in my memory of England. <br><br>Sunday brunch at Level33 had a quiet expensive bustle with mostly rich customers on the 33rd level of the marina bay financial centre. The view is quite spectacular but nothing compared to MBS or One Altitude of course. the food was decent for its price. it&#39;s handcrafted beers were ok but we had better. To be honest it was one of those places we would go once to experience it and see what the fuss is about and probably never go back again. But the girls had fun playing tourist and taking photos on the outdoor balcony. you will also get an entertaining, but not necessarily pleasant, view of scantily clad residents walking around Marina Bay Residences.

text: Being at the Marina Bay Financial Centre, you can probably guess the type of crowd that congregates here - there&#39;s lots of groups of bankers coming straight from work, which gives the place a very smart atmosphere and you&#39;d probably feel out of place (but not unwelcome) in more casual attire. The atmosphere was buzzing, and the view is outstanding.<br><br>The craft beer here isn&#39;t anything to write home about - I ordered five samplers of ale and was a bit disappointed in the lack of diversity in the flavours between the ales. They&#39;re very conservative flavours, and the ales will be enjoyable by most. Hailing from the UK, though, I might be being a bit harsh compared to the selection I enjoy there.<br><br>We interacted with at least three waitresses/waiters, and the I have to say, the service was absolutely phenomenal. They must have taken recent criticism of the other yelpers into account! The wait staff did a great job of helping us order the right amount for our party size and making sure the meals came on time. The food was great, but boy do you pay for it! It&#39;s overpriced, for sure, but it is pretty decent. <br><br>The view is fantastic, and Level33 is definitely a great place to bring visiting friends to get a wonderful sunset view of the bay. Will I be visiting again for dinner without guests? Not really, as the price doesn&#39;t really justify the quality of the food to me.<br><br>That said - the pre-8pm $13 for 500ml is a pretty good deal, so I&#39;d highly recommend you visit for a drink, the view, and the ambience, at least.

text: They have gotten some selections of beer, thought it is over priced for the view that you get - nothing outstanding in terms of selections either. <br><br>Their food doesn&#39;t taste good at all - I have tried their platter, lamb, and pork and all of them were big disappointment.<br><br>It&#39;s just conveniently located and thus I brought my leadership team and customer a few times, but a few visits have proven that it&#39;s not really a place to go for food. Atmosphere and the view are what you are paying the high price.

text: 4- stars for the view....minus one for the food/drinks/price.<br><br>I was only here for drinks. Heard enough bad reviews about the food for me to waste any calories here. It&#39;s a microbrewery and the beers are ok. nothing mind-blowing.<br><br>Snag a table outdoor in the evening, and you will wow any guest that you bring there. Of all the rooftop bars surrounding the Bay, I think this place has the best view. Come in the evening and you can watch the sunset and the changing colors across the entire city. Enjoy!

text: You come here for the amazing view of Singapore at night, not the beer. They might brew their own beer here, but they really aren&#39;t very good at it. The beer is alright, but not interesting or worth the price tag. On top of that, I&#39;m not sure that understand what an IPA is. Their Indian Pale Ale certainly haven&#39;t seen too much of the lovely hops. A pale ale, yes, but not indian.

Went here recently on a business trip. Prices are higher here than in the U.S. but thought for the quality and ambiance that the price was reasonable. I had the chicken which was amazing and my co-workers had the steak. All entrees were incredible. We had the scallops and beef tartare for appetizers. The scallops were just OK. Nothing fantastic. But the beef was excellent. The view is amazing. I would most certainly come back on my next business trip.

text: I was trying to make online reservation for dinner on 13th January but the website indicated N/A. I then called few times but transferred to auto voice machine. After few attempts finally a lady answered my call and made the reservation for us.  Went earlier than our schedule time and received a warm welcome from hostess. The food was delicious but some servers need more polishing in terms of talking to guests and body language, One server was pouring my glass with water while talking to another waiter at the other side. Some waitress are very attentive and polite while others seems to be blind when I was raising my hand to get their attention to Ask for water while my partner was coughing. Nice view and food but service needs a lift.

There was no way we could resist a visit to a brewery 33 stories above Singapore. The views are most definitely worth the visit. Possibly even better than at MBS, because you get to see the enormous building in all its glory, as well as its surrounds. <br><br>As for the place itself? The beer is expensive and extremely bland. I&#39;d take a Tiger over the offerings here for a fraction of the price. The food is just as bad, if not worse. Super expensive pub-fare, very bland. <br><br>Honestly, all of this is to be expected. This place is all about the wow factor and they are hardly the first restaurant to capitalise on the tourist trade! We enjoyed our visit as a must-stop on our list and were happy to pay for the beer as the price of entry.

text: Great view of Marina Bay sands and decent beer and great food.  We had their version of a charcuterie, sizzling beer and fish and some amazing bread and dips.  We had to wait for a table outside but the staff was good about not asking people to block us which was nice since we had waited an hour for a table with a view.<br><br>But it all went downhill when we got the bill.  The reason we had sizzling beef and fish was because we had ordered the fish, but they brought us the beef.  For their mistake they let us keep the beef while they brought out the fish. They said no charge.  Of course, it ended up on the bill.  When I pointed it out the guy went back to fix it.  When he came back the charge was still on because he had &#34;called his manager and his manager had said that we had ordered one in the first round and the other in the 2nd round.&#34;  There were no two rounds so I&#39;m not sure if the server was lying or the &#39;manager&#39; he called but regardless I said it wasn&#39;t acceptable and to take it off the bill.  He came back with it off but what is with that?  And then when we were paying cash and sorting it out, he was like &#34;don&#39;t you think it&#39;d be easier to put on your card?&#34;  Felt very odd he was trying to force a credit card transaction.  The whole end was sketchy and ruined what had been a good night.  Unacceptable service.

text: A pretty awesome view, in fact one of my favorites in Singapore without requiring a cover charge. While a dinner here is pricy and I have only tried it once (was delicious). The drinks are very reasonably priced and their own craft beer and craft beer cocktails are well worth the visit. Sometimes the balcony gets rather crowded but usually you can get a table after 20-30 minute wait or can always enjoy the view and come back inside for drinks. Overall I highly recommend to visit here. In terms of food - I had the steak + shrimp combo dish and it was well prepared and presented though expensive!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/lpwdTdVbrnoPXWrbwoz8Ew/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=BjAKcu8XpxA1gMNbXc8f5Q&select=lpwdTdVbrnoPXWrbwoz8Ew', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/NUg8DbaQplUfUVM3n5O5KQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=BjAKcu8XpxA1gMNbXc8f5Q&select=NUg8DbaQplUfUVM3n5O5KQ', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/re11BCHgSk3-zSmpfhV-uQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=BjAKcu8XpxA1gMNbXc8f5Q&select=re11BCHgSk3-zSmpfhV-uQ', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/d40wtvnbyJU5iDJz9lIsRg/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/level33-singapore-4?reviewid=BjAKcu8XpxA1gMNbXc8f5Q&select=d40wtvnbyJU5iDJz9lIsRg', 'altText': 'Photo of LeVeL33 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}]
text: The Food - We had the Vday set meal so I am not sure if all the items listed here are on the regular menu. <br><br>1. Starters: <br>- Fresh rolls with 3 different types of butter (love butter!!!)<br>- Scallop (my favorite) &amp; pork belly <br>- Foie gras (excellent &amp; Normally, I don&#39;t like this dish but this one was good. Whatever else I write will be an understatement for foie gras lovers so I&#39;ll stop here. <br><br>2. Mains: <br>- Overall, quite disappointing especially after the spectacular starters. I have a feeling that this place excels in its niche - starters/finger food/desserts &amp; (of course) cocktails/beers. However, not in their mains.  <br>- The pan fried sea bass had a fishy smell that was not musk well which really irks me. Another big downer was that the fillet had so much small-annoying-hard-to-see bones in it. Beware! It was a chore to debone it and isn&#39;t worth the effort because it wasn&#39;t even that tasty to begin with. <br>- Beef. I ordered mine medium-well. A precarious task because as most restaurants do not do this well. It comes often comes out over cooked (well-done). Level 33 was no exception. Also, they topped the steak with a strong cheese (melted on top of it) which really overpowered the flavor of the steak. The steak sauce was great but they gave too little of it, and whilst I tried to ration my meat to sauce ratio carefully in the end the sauce ran out before the meat. <br><br>3. Desserts: <br>- Chocolate lava cake - Good! I love who they balanced out the sweetness of the chocolate with sea salt and cream cheese at the side. <br>- Mascarpone - Great!!! even though they got our order wrong! We were suppose to have the banana dessert (whatever that was, it was recommended by our server) but this was excellent! I am a big fan of mascarpone so I might be biased. If you like cheesey-sweet treats like me, this one is definitely for you! <br><br>4. Drinks: <br>- Excellent. I am not a big fan of beer. In fact, I NEVER order it. However, this microbrewery has changed my opinion. All their cocktails are beer based (I believe) and they were sooo good (with the exception of the stout. I am still, and forever will be NOT A FAN OF STOUT. The bitterness puts me off.) Even the plain beer alone is good. It has a really light taste, even lighter than Heikien.<br>- Paris - Love x2! Very sweet though. <br>- Blond mojito - Love x3. My favorite drink. <br>- Beer - Love<br>- Unknown stout cocktail with berries - Cannot Love, because of my predisposition to be biased against stout!!! The bf thought it was ok though. <br><br>The Service <br>- Good. The waiter was kind enough to throw in 2 free drinks. The first because I hinted it looked good. The second because our desserts took 45min to come. <br>- Really appreciated their effort to be efficient. <br>- They had a pre-set the dining table with a rose &amp; a box of chocolates so definitely good news for the guys. Half the work has already been done for you. <br><br>The View<br>- It was AWESOME. Overlooking the entire marina bay :) How singapore has grown. I feel old already! <br>- It&#39;s a bit chilly up there so definitely bring a jacket along. <br><br>Overall: Will definitely be back here again with friends to grab a cocktail &amp; snack on some starters.

text: Came here before during weekday and was impressed with appetiser buffet.  Returned for the roast Sunday lunch and was less impressed.  The food was just decent and the service was very Ho-hum.  Except for the kids menus and plastic cutlery there wasnt even paper or crayons to draw, let alone toys.  The dessert was very very average.  Go there for the beer, cocktail and the view (which was stunning even on a hazy day) but we wouldn&#39;t be rushing back.

text: LeVel33 claims the distinction of being the highest brewery at least in Singapore if not the world. The beer is actually very good including their seasonal brews. It is definitely a sign of the increasing popularity of micro and nano-breweries popping up in Singapore. If you head here for happy hour you can find the beer of your choice for a reasonable price and get a seat outside for the spectacular views of Marina Bay, the Singapore Flyer and the ArtScience Museum. Definitely worth a visit!

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=Adzb5v6YpltZ7HmeOzQARg', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Richard Z.', 'displayLocation': 'Elk Grove, CA', 'altText': 'Richard Z.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=Adzb5v6YpltZ7HmeOzQARg', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 148, 'photoCount': 501, 'reviewCount': 349, 'eliteYear': None}
text: Mid 30&#39;s international traveler walking around town with camera gear, hungry and thirsty. <br>Went to Level 33<br>Took Private Elevator<br>Receptionist didn&#39;t acknowledge me at all. <br>Went to the balcony myself. <br>No table so I stood in a clear section to look at the view. <br>First thing waiter said to me when he saw me is &#34;No Tripod&#34; to take photos. <br>I ask for a menu.<br>Menu never came. <br>I left with my camera, my tripod and my American Express.<br>Went to a food center in China Town<br>Pigged out<br>Went back to the hotel. <br>Writing a review. <br>GREAT VIEW from the balcony tho. <br>Make sure you dress up.<br>Don&#39;t bring your camera gear and act all touristy. LOL<br>It is a fancy place, but unfortunately too fancy for me...

I like to come to L33 occasionally for a drink or microbrew to relax and hang out for a while. It&#39;s okay and I find it kinda fancy how they for example serve a Gin Tonic with a mini bottle of Hendricks on a small board. That plus the check surely let&#39;s you get big eyes haha. But I guess it&#39;s ok. L33 has a nice view, the service is nothing special but then again there are not many places in SG where I find service to be excellent.<br><br>I like their Executive Lunch when I&#39;m into the Lunch thing every now and then. The quality is consistent. Due to it&#39;s location at the MBFC (Marina Bay Financial Center) this is a typical ExPat and Business Folk hangout as I experienced, convenient for a quick bite and drink in between or after work.<br><br>Pay it a visit and get the picture! :)<br><br>Cheers<br>-s
Great taste of food, great atmosphere and an outstanding view of Marina Bay.

text: I went to sample the beer and to check it the fabulous views! Neither disappointed, but they didn&#39;t offer a burger for dinner so I skipped the dinner part. It&#39;s a great place to take visitors for a nice view.

text: Fantastic view, great balcony, strange dining room laid out like a canteen, menu not very good, I struggled to find anything&#39;s g that I liked, bathrooms need to be cleaner.....a shame, lots of potential......
How much fun was this! It was a bit windy when we were up there but I loved taking the elevator up and then having a good IPA on the patio. We didn&#39;t eat--just sipped and enjoyed the view.

Decent beer, the view is the best part. Beers are not that bad in price about US$10. I didn&#39;t have any food, but overall good beer for it being in Singapore, which is not known for craft beers. I would go again for sure.

text: The view is spectacular of Marina Bay up here.  Only came for a drink and the view so couldn&#39;t say anything about the food. Nice atmosphere for a date.  I would come back.

amazing amazing views.  that fancy hotel with the pool on the roof really looks cool with your eyeballs and also in pictures.  also the servers were very accommodating.  we had reservations for 8 pm, showed up at 6pm, they seated us and never rushed us out.  service was attentive enough.  happy hour prices on their beers before 8pm - 300 mL and 500 mL sizes available.  beers were fine, i&#39;m not much of a beer drinker but the happy hour prices seemed reasonable enough for singapore and also kinda a schwanky place.  it was filled with banker type looking people, a very ny looking scene but not too loud at all.  the food was actually pretty tasty, the lamb shoulder was super tender, flaked off the bone, had some really gigantic baby corns and i think shishito peppers and came with 5 sauces.  yeah it&#39;s a 100 bucks but it&#39;s a lot of food, 5 of us shared.  got two sides the leeks - which are difficult to slice and the cabbage which was many different leaves of leafy vegetable (i.e. one brussel sprout leaf) but actually super tasty and flavorful.  we also had the ploughman&#39;s board for two which had enough meat for 4 and the beef tartar.  i am told the beef tartar was good.  it reminded me too much of the walking dead so i couldn&#39;t eat it.  overall seemed like a classy place, beautiful views and they didn&#39;t rush us out.  we spent like 3.5 hours there.

This is the place to go if you are missing real american food in Singapore.  The steak is delicious!  Ask to sit outside and overlook Marina Bay and you can see the light show at night.  I was here for the final Formula 1 race a well which they showed on a large projector inside.  It was very cool to be able to see the track outside and watch the race at the same time.

Quite average brewery with a phenomenal view of the bay. Went for a quick beer after work, but the seating wasn&#39;t open on the patio. Had the Blond Lager, which was average for a craft beer. The excitement of this place is relegated to the overall urban chic atmosphere and the outdoor seating. Not a place I&#39;d return for the beers. I&#39;d recommend visiting at night, catching the lights, and going for the food.

text: Went just around 7 to wait for sunset. Lovely view but with prices to match. Definitely must check it out though!
So there is the view...  Terrible service, mediocre food, awful beer.  Why people congregate here baffles me.  Plenty of better options.

text: Beautiful food, friendly service, and great 2 for 1 lunch specials. This eatery does not disappoint. <br><br>Tip: If you modify or try to substitute any of the dishes, it is no longer eligible for the 2 for 1 deal. We ordered a Caesar salad and asked for dressing on the side. The Romaine was crisp and fresh. The dressing was rich, full of flavor.<br><br>We had the pizza with mushrooms and olives, the spaghetti al funghi, spaghetti bolognese, and the pasta carbonara. The pizza had a lovely crust, sauce and the ingredients were fresh. My niece slurped up every bit of spaghetti bolognese. The carbonara was good, but not the best I have had. My favorite entree was the lovely al funghi. I believe they had 3 different kinds of mushrooms and the sauce was so fragrant.<br><br>Last but not least, the desserts were amazing. The gelato is freshly made with great flavors. The pistachio lava cake was rich and decadent and wonderfully balanced with the passionfruit sorbetto. The waffle with apple caramel was paired with chocolate gelato. Dessert was to die for. <br><br>Thank you Chapter 55 for a fabulous meal.

text: My group of girlfriends, a total party size of 8 decided to check out Chapter 55 at hipster land. So I called in to make a reservation, but an automated voice answering machine told me I would receive a text message to complete the reservation, which I did. It was a short URL to make a reservation via Chope. However on Chope, I could only select a maximum party size of 6. So in the comments I asked for 2 more seats.<br><br>A few hours later I got a call saying that their cafe&#39;s reservation policy requires each person to spend at least $25 and order a main course. Waffles which are priced $18.50+ with 2 scoops of ice cream are not considered a main course. Even the staff encouraged me to walk in. This is ridiculous. So we decided to walk in, and the food better be worth the effort!<br>Despite the phone call, I was delighted to be greeted by the beautiful ice cream display!<br>And I pinched myself to be sure I wasn&#39;t dreaming when I saw the $23 per pint price tag. Okay, let&#39;s see if their ice cream is really twice as good as other competitors, to be priced this high.<br>The interior has a very homely, retro feel to it, the lighting isn&#39;t instagram&#39;s best friend. You will have to improvise or try and get a table by the windows.<br><br>1. Beef Bolognese Cheese Fries $15+<br>With truffle tries price at $14, we decided to try something else. Sadly, this dish wasn&#39;t what we expected, even though there is supposedly cheese in the sauce. We couldn&#39;t taste any. It was a plate of very soggy fries, with a very under seasoned beef bolognese sauce.<br><br>2. Squid Ink Risotto $25+<br>Tasted cheesy and I felt gerlat very quickly. This is the first plate of Risotto that I didn&#39;t like, I am normally a huge fan of Risotto.<br>It&#39;s waffle time! Despite the unsatisfying experience with the main courses, I was so certain the highly instagrammable waffles with ice cream would be the highlight of my night!<br><br>3. Waffles with Mao shan wang durian and belgian chocolate $18.50+<br>I liked that the durian ice cream colour wasn&#39;t overly yellow, which a lot of ice cream parlours, normally add yellow colouring to, it didn&#39;t smell very fragrant but it tasted good. I liked the durian ice cream. The Belgian chocolate tasted okay, it didn&#39;t leave an impression for me. The waffles, which I was looking forward to, tasted ok, I&#39;ve definitely had better waffles in the surrounding area.<br><br>4. Waffles with Pulut Hitam and Pistacchio $18.50+<br>The only redeeming factor that Chatper 55 had for me tonight, was the Pulut Hitam ice cream, which I truly enjoyed. However not all the girls at my table liked it. It wasn&#39;t displayed, but they had it in the freezer. You could bite into the black rice bits in the ice cream. It a legit, pulut hitam ice cream! The Pistacchio was also a memorable ice cream flavour. You can distinctively taste the pistacchio.<br>The bill for 6 girls and we weren&#39;t very big eaters, so asking all 6 of us to order a main course each isn&#39;t the wisest cafe policy, even from a business stand point.<br><br>The staff weren&#39;t well organized and took a long while to clear our table. The first staff cleared one plate, and a male staff cleard 2 more plates. We were done with all our plates and when the waffles came, we still had half a table worth of dirty plates. Only after the second waffle came to our table, did another male staff who served us the waffles, clear the rest of the dirty dishes.<br><br>The chinese local lady at the cashier who spoke mandarin was very friendly and polite. I had higher hopes for their ice cream and waffles with such a high price tag on each plate. <br><br>On the bright side, they have BOGO weekday lunch offers.<br><br>wifi password : chapter55

Great place for their 1-for-1 weekday lunch promotion and it accommodated our group of about 12. No problems getting a seat at 11.30am on a Friday.<br><br>Vongole spaghetti ($18) - 3.75 stars<br>Hearty, more clam shells than meat, but at half the price I&#39;m not complaining.<br><br>Strawberry gelato ($4.80) - 3 stars<br>Too sweet after the first few spoons.

text: My colleague who had accidentally ran into this bistro a week ago bugged us to accompany her soon to sample the food. So today, despite the heavy afternoon rain, we walked from our office to sought out the place. Walking along Eng Hoon Street, the restaurant was easily noticeable by the corner of Tiong Poh Road. It&#39;s pretty big. One thing that I found very attractive on their signboard was how they highlighted their &#34;1 for 1 on weekdays&#34; offer.<br><br>We went as a group of 5. Seeing that the restaurant is not Halal-certified, I couldn&#39;t try out their main courses, hence I went with the desserts. Like one of the popular quotes that I snapped stated, &#34;Life is short. Eat dessert first!&#34;<br><br>The appetizers came as bowls of mushroom soup. The mushrooms weren&#39;t in chunky forms but they were grounded in, which was nice!<br><br>Two of my colleagues ordered one plate of white wine pasta (Vongole?) and the other, some sort of seafood pasta. Can&#39;t recall the names of the dishes, but both of them commented that the spices in both of their pastas were too overpowering; one even masked the white wine sauce. They also ordered buffalo wings (5 pieces). Personally, from what I see, those wings were overpriced. Such small pieces for $16?!<br><br>Came my Salted Caramel Waffle and a glass of Black Cow. Funny names to give the floats: &#34;Black Cow&#34; for Coke Float and &#34;Snow White&#34; for Sprite Float. <br><br>Well, as you can see from my waffle photo, I just loved the presentation. What a plating! Loved how they stenciled in cocoa powder of their logo at the corner of the plate. The waffle itself cost me $17 due to the fact that I opted for 2 scoops of ice-cream. Otherwise it would have been $15 for one. I opted for a scoop of Salted Caramel and Hazelnut gelato on my waffle, while I got another scoop of Hersheys gelato for my coke float. Loved the waffle!<br><br>We even sampled a teaspoon of some of the gelatos on display. I had the Salted Egg flavoured, Cotton Candy flavoured and Strawberry Cheesecake flavoured... Nice. But definitely, I have tasted better and creamier gelatos elsewhere.

Fresh pasta with seafood', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Fresh pasta with seafood'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/v4gP8XCAVduMgBAi-JQVEw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/chapter-55-singapore?reviewid=7P6z1jv2nAo7e01xggY75Q&select=v4gP8XCAVduMgBAi-JQVEw', 'altText': 'Photo of Chapter 55 - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: This place opened late last year in December right before Christmas and occupied a spacious corner on Tiong Bahru Road.  It is on way home and I noticed that it was always packed at night so I wanted to give it a try.  <br><br>We went for Sunday brunch and I have to say I was skeptical at first because their menu was so extensive.  Usually when a restaurant is trying to offer everything it is a bad sign - on top of their brunch menu, they have a long list ranging from pasta to pizzas to risottos to appetizers and desserts (waffles, pancakes, gelatos). We ordered buffalo wings to share, I remember it being decent but not particularly authentic but on the spicy side.  The dish that blew me away was one of their fresh pasta dishes. The sauce was AMAZING, it is very flavorful and seems to be saffron based.  The seafood was very fresh, which is quite a rarity when eating out and reflects their attentiveness in sourcing ingredients.  It is also very reasonably priced.  To be honest, it was really out of my expectations.  I later read from other reviews that the chef is from Pasta Brava - that explains it.  Also read that its owner is the same as Ice Edge Cafe, a popular cafe in Kovan (ok too far for me so good they open one in TB). I tried a piece of the pizza that my friend was having, the crust was pretty good too.  The pasta was really filling as the sauce was so rich, so I didn&#39;t have any room for desserts.   That is a pity though as they appears to serve a great selection of gelatos.   I read that they have a 1-for-1 pasta deal during weekday lunch time and that&#39;s a pretty good deal, I would totally take advantage of this if I work around Tiong Bahru.  This is a pretty big space and can accommodate any group dining comfortably.

text: i like the one for one lunch deal even though there are limited choices for it.<br>and you got to go there early to get a table if not you&#39;ll have to wait in line or sit outside in the heat of the day. <br><br>my friend and I both had pizza; she ordered the bonito and i ordered the good old funghi pizza. it didn&#39;t leave me swooning but i&#39;d say it&#39;s definitely one of the better pizzas i had in Singapore. the bonito was interesting to try but i am not sure if i want to order it again. pizzas are still better eaten the Italian way than fusion is my take on this. give me sausages, funghi and olives on a pizza anytime!!<br><br>it was actually nice to have a gelato counter in store; the server was friendly and willing to give in to our undying want of trying almost all the flavors and then still smile at us as we try to make up our flippant minds. some were misses like the yuzu lacked the tangy taste i desire and the passion fruit mango was more like just mango. eventually i went for the belgium dark chocolate which i think is one flavor that could never go wrong and i was right. oh to note, they do have pretty powerful tasting mao shan wang gelato.<br><br>in all I paid $20 for a pizza, a drink (nothing worth mentioning even though it was lemon grass) and a scoop of gelato.

I&#39;m surprised this place rates so low. It&#39;s a popular lunch spot among my colleagues because of the buy one get one free lunch deal, and the fact that the food is pretty good<br><br>They don&#39;t take reservations for lunch on weekdays, but it wasn&#39;t a problem for our party of 17. We made sure we arrived by 12pm to get a table. <br><br>The menu that qualifies BOGO isn&#39;t large, but it&#39;s still decently diverse. You don&#39;t have to get the same item, just anything on the BOGO menu. A lot of people got the salmon with balsamic vinegar, and the Dory main dish was pretty popular too. I had the beef lasagna, which I thought was excellent. At half the price, it was a steal. <br><br>The service was not outstandingly bad or good.<br><br>Definitely a good place for a fancier lunch.

3 stars! 1 star each for FOOD, AMBIENCE and &#34;WILL I COME BACK?&#34;. No stars for service and price.<br><br>Also, I apologise in advance for the epic length review.<br><br>The word &#39;hipster&#39; is overused, really. This is a typical brunch restaurant. I don&#39;t see where it&#39;s &#39;hip&#39; or &#39;ster&#39;.<br><br>Food is average. Mushroom soup is not Campbell&#39;s. Or at least to my un-hipster taste buds. Buffalo wings were like sweet and sour chicken wings, not spicy. Pasta was meh. The only thing I would come back for are the pizzas, Super thin crust and light. Nice.<br><br>Ambience is homely. Lots of wood benches and tin pails for decoration. Seats are tightly packed and walk space is narrow. I might have seen a mason jar or two. /shudder<br><br>&#34;Will I come back?&#34; Yes, for the pizza and for the &#34;buy 1 get one free&#34; lunch special. Now the mechanics of this BOGO is dreadfully complicated and very sneaky if the customer is not careful. I will explain this in the next section. This would have been so easy to fix when asked, and would have won a life-long customer. But. hey, which restaurant manager would want to do that?<br><br>Service is non-existent. Poor guys are overworked and do not have time for pleasantries. <br><br>Price. Ahhh, the only thing this place has going for it is the 1 for 1 lunch special. When you get seated, you will see from the menu that not all items qualify for this. Items that do, have a little label next to it.<br><br>So! Imagine the following scenario:<br><br>Ah Beng and Ah Lian decide to try this new &#39;simi-lai eh hipster&#39; cafe near Ah Mah&#39;s flat in Tiong Bahru.<br><br>They order two muchroom soups ($11 for 2) This items is automatically 1 for 1. Don&#39;t know why they have to make life so confusing.<br><br>Then Ah Beng orders a Vogole pasta MAIN for $18. Ah Lian orders a Funghi Pizza for $18.<br><br>For appetisers, Ah Beng orders Buffalo Wings ($16) and Ah Lian orders Calamari Rings ($16).<br><br>So, quick recap: 2 soups, 2 mains, 2 appetisers.<br><br>QUESTION: How much was Ah Beng and Ah Lian charged for their lunch? (Assume no service charge.)<br><br>ANSWER: You would think, this is easy! <br>1 for 1 mushroom soup + 1 for 1 MAIN + 1 for 1 appetiser = $11 + $18 + $16 = $45<br><br>Wrong. Because Chapter 55 is so scared that customers will &#39;take advantage&#39; of the 1 for 1 deal, this is how they calculated the bill:<br><br>Mushroom soup is $11 for 2. (Written in the menu, don&#39;t argue.)<br>Higher cost items are charged, lower cost items are free. (Written in the fine print, don&#39;t argue.)<br><br>Actual bill is: $11 + $18 + $18 = $47<br><br>Ah Beng and Ah Lian pays up and leaves, vowing to never come back and also something about mothers and fathers.<br><br>Ok, ok, the story is a little dramatic for a difference of $2. But it is the principle of the whole thing. Even if it is not for principle, then it is about making a quick decision to make Ah Lian and Ah Beng happy customers. <br><br>Long story short: After the trauma of mathematics and Chapter 55. Ah Beng and Ah Lian grew closer and lived happily ever after,

Had dinner here last night with family and friends. Our group of 6 had buffalo wings, pesto salad, truffle fries. Squid ink risotto, osso buco, mushroom pasta and anchovy pizza with Bonito flakes. We also had a few scoops of gelato for dessert. I got salted caramel, which was good but not the best I&#39;ve ever had.<br><br>All the dishes were good. The wings were juicy and spicy and the risotto was creamy, although a bit stingy with the shrimp and scallop (there was only 1 piece of each in the dish). Service was pretty fast and friendly.<br><br>The place was almost full, which showed the terrible acoustics. There was a group of 8 seated about 3 meters away from our table and their loud chatter and laughter echoed. The table size is odd too--- definitely squeezy for 6, too roomy for 4. <br><br>Overall it is a nice casual Italian place, and I would consider going back.

text: Chapter 55 is right in the heart of Tiong Bahru and, literally, just a short walk away from where I work. I ended up coming here with my husband for lunch and we were super stoked to utilize the 1-for-1 deal. It&#39;s unfortunate though, the pizza and the pasta we ordered were pretty bland... But the gelato was super rich and creamy and did make up for the mediocre lunch.

Sheng Chen fried kway teow', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Sheng Chen fried kway teow'}]
text: I used to stay on the second floor of this block when I was a child and I used to frequent this uncle&#39;s store whenever I came down to play tamiya cars or collect beer bottle caps with the other kids living in the same block. My favourite dish last time was always his char kway teow. Little did I know how famous he was until now. <br><br>After moving away from Bukit Merah at the age of 6, occasionally, we&#39;ll go back to visit my grandparents&#39; old friends at the temple nearby and the char kway teow uncle (as I used to call him). Recently, my dad had a craving for his char kway teow and we went back to eat it. However, the uncle has slimmed down quite a fair bit due to his age and he doesn&#39;t recognize me now as it has been a good 10 years or so since I have ate his char kway teow. He does recall my grandparents though. <br><br>So this time, instead of being the bratty kid that I was who only wanted his char kway teow with eggs and no beansprout, lard and cockles (which he always used to prepare for me as a child) I ordered it without removing anything and with chili. I took a photo of it and went on Instagram and Twitter promote it as my childhood favourite dish.. and out of curiousity I decided to google his store&#39;s name. To my pleasant surprise, I found out that he was actually one of the last great char kway teow men (<a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Fieatishootipost.sg%2F2010%2F11%2Fsheng-cheng-char-kway-teow-last-of-char.html&amp;s=3a22897715d0e309e7bb6e2fb414d81cc94c38a2f8f3659207bbe6d9c3a546c2" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">ieatishootipost.sg/2010/…</a>). Only then I realised how important this plate is because well, in a melodramatic sense, you can&#39;t get good and nostalgic char kway teow like this anymore. So in a way, this is a heritage dish. So if you happen to be around Blk 132 Jalan Bukit Merah, do pop by this store and order a plate of his char kway teow.

One of my favorite go-tos for consistently good char kway teow! This stall has been around for ages, run by an old auntie and uncle. When they aren&#39;t hard at work with the wok, you&#39;ll catch them preparing their ingredients throughout the day. <br><br>Situated in a fairly non-descript coffee shop, Sheng Chen char kway teow is located in a small hole-in-the-wall units beneath a HDB block. Nonetheless, they&#39;ve managed to garner quite a loyal fanbase, as evidenced by the trickle of maids streaming in for takeaway orders, and the fair number of newspaper cuttings displayed. I really enjoyed the cripsy pork lard, as well as the fresh cockles, freshly shucked every morning by the auntie. It had just the right about of chilli, and the firmness of the noodles was just right (though some might prefer it a little softer). <br><br>At $2.50 a plate, it&#39;s a sinful treat on the cheap. While paling in comparison to the epoch of char kway teow that is Hill Street in Bedok, this is definitely one of the best traditional wok-fried versions you&#39;ll find in the south of Singapore.

text: This Germanish place is outstanding value, and has good quality food. It isn&#39;t even inaccessible either, being a stone&#39;s throw from Kovan MRT, albeit hidden behind some HDB blocks.<br><br>The interior design is reminiscent of a place that should cost at least 50% more. Sitting inside, I could almost imagine I was in Holland Village.<br><br>The clam chowder was $5 and was alright - nothing special but still decent.<br><br>Pork schnitzel was $8 and was crispy, juicy and tasty. It came with creamy mushroom sauce which I suspect wasn&#39;t authentic, but it was tasty. And the portion was bigger than I expected for the price.<br><br>The pork knuckle was $10. The skin was very crispy. The meat was alright if a bit dry  - it could be a bit more tender and moister. It also could&#39;ve come with a bit more sauce.<br><br>Earlier I described this place as Germanish rather than German. Among other things that&#39;s because they only had one type of sausage. And chicken sausage at that. But it&#39;s homemade...<br><br>There isn&#39;t any air conditioning and they only accept cash. But at least you know they&#39;re cutting overheads in those departments (they don&#39;t charge GST or service either).

text: I&#39;m a bit surprised that this place was not on Yelp&#39;s listing since it&#39;s been around for quite some time now. <br><br>Knuckles serves the CHEAPEST pork knuckles in town at just 10 dollars. They also don&#39;t cut corners but serve you a really good dish. If you prefer a whole knuckle, that would cost you just $30 dollars. <br><br>The owner also mentioned that all his burgers are made with quality meat. Home made stuff and not frozen patties. I would have tried if we had not ordered two mains already. Will definitely be back to try it soon. <br><br>If you are in the area,want to try cheap Western/German good, and don&#39;t want to queue, do try Knuckles. <br><br>Lots of beer selection. You get to sip your cold beer and chill while watching people queuing up for Nakorn Thai food next door. <br><br>No GST no service charge. And open till late.

text: Good food! But prepare to queue. Beef steak was great. Pork knuckle is good too. But only cash payment available

Cheaper than abc (Artisan Boulangerie), but more expensive than Breadtalk and Four Leaves, this place suffers from location. It tries to serve French baked goods, but hasn&#39;t taken into account Singapore environment.<br><br>Star Vista is an outdoor mall.  Hence, ibake is exposed to the Singapore air and humidity. If you get your bread by noon, it tastes good -- crunchy outside, soft on inside, (but still twice the price than Four Leaves which has A/C!)  But get your bread at 6 pm, and the crust is chewy when it&#39;s supposed to be crunchy. The bread is kept behind the counter, but every time the workers open the door, humid air gets in and the bread spoils fast.<br><br>Their garlic bread is over $3, but at St. Leaven (a four leaves branch) you can get a better more crunchy garlic bread for less than $2.  I used to come here for their garlic bread until I discovered I could get it cheaper and better and some of the Four Leaves outlets.

text: Location: Walking distance from Telok Ayer MRT station so it&#39;s convenient to get to. <br><br>Service: 10/10! Staff was super friendly and relatively quick to serve my needs. Water was always refilled and I had no problem calling over the waitress.<br><br>Food: I had the Vanilla Vodka/Tomato Cream Pasta for main. It was just like any other tomato based pasta. Good but not exceptional. The serving size was smaller than most places. But I&#39;m a small eater so it was perfect for me. For dessert I had the Dirt Cake, which is a light cheese cake sprinkled with oreos and gummy worms, served inside of a flower pot bowl with a flower stuck into it! Super cute looking, but also super big. Best for sharing. The cheese cake wasn&#39;t too sweet had good consistency but the bottom was still frozen (I assume they freeze-store it). For drinks I had English Breakfast Tea. They served Twining&#39;s brand, and offered free refill of boiling water. <br><br>Ambience: The cafe was a bit warm (temperature). Other than that, I liked how quiet it was. I went Friday night and it wasn&#39;t bustling which I liked because I could relax and eat at a leisurely pace.<br><br>Definitely would recommend checking out!

Really wanted to rate this place higher as they have some good dishes, unfortunately though it just averages out to be; well average.<br><br>I have eaten here 3 times with friends and always ordering different dishes<br><br>Let&#39;s start with the bad, drinks are served in very small glasses so there is no value for money. Especially considering the prices of soft drink and beer! This is perhaps the biggest criticism as an asahi at sgd11.50 should be a whole bottle not a small glass. Coke should be the can with a glass on the side etc <br><br>The food some dishes are great (vodka penne pasta with bacon and for that matter most of the pastas as well the sandwiches are all very good meals) it&#39;s the other items that miss the mark.<br><br>Cordon bleu and the fish etc all appear to be frozen/pre package food and whilst I don&#39;t expect an outstanding meal at close 20- a dish it should not be frozen. <br><br>Also had the green curry with egg and its every lacked in a coconut/green curry authentic taste <br><br>Portion sizes are ok but I could easily eat 2 mains here and I&#39;m not a big eater. <br><br>Atmosphere is nice when not too busy but when they are busy it&#39;s way too noisy inside and hard to have conversation. <br><br>Overall 2.5 stars.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/CyCoDgGzZbUebWZfKIUnxQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/vanilla-bar-and-caf%C3%A9-singapore-2?reviewid=JKYMtkD4iLk5cxHdRQI7CQ&select=CyCoDgGzZbUebWZfKIUnxQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Vanilla Bar & Café - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: It&#39;s often hard to find a nice quiet air-conditioned place for lunch that doesn&#39;t cost a bomb or stink like one in Raffles Place / Shenton Way / Tanjong Pagar. Most places leaves you smelling like stale oil and food which just kills the rest of my day.<br><br>Walking into the cafe, the first thing you&#39;ll notice is the wonderful sweet aroma of vanilla in the air. Ladies rejoice, you&#39;ll only smell the vanilla scent instead of other patrons&#39; food in your hair!<br><br>Designed like a quaint designer Japanese western cafe, its artsy and modern. The food is also a mixed Japanese-Western style. Food portions arent large but personally I was happy with the yaki udon with chicken katsu and teriyaki sauce that I ordered.<br><br>They are famous for their dessert, especially the dirt cake. Presented in a pot with a fake plant on top of it and sometimes even with gummy worms to make it looks like you&#39;re eating a real plant. And yes, you&#39;re to eat the &#34;dirt&#34; which is actually oreos sprinkled vanilla ice cream.<br><br>A great alternative for lunch with colleagues, birthdays and other office celebrations. But do bear in mind the place is really small and the biggest party it can accommodate is probably about 8 persons.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=gj-TFb1iPmwBWCKN1qIgAA', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/60s.jpg', 'srcSet': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/ms.jpg 1.67x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/120s.jpg 2.00x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/90s.jpg 1.50x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/168s.jpg 2.80x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/kT8Ur0y2i4MwejsHZd_3Zw/180s.jpg 3.00x', 'markupDisplayName': 'Al C.', 'displayLocation': 'New York, NY', 'altText': 'Al C.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=gj-TFb1iPmwBWCKN1qIgAA', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 86, 'photoCount': 111, 'reviewCount': 161, 'eliteYear': None}
text: This is my second time here.  Location is good and the space is cozy. Service is slow.  Food did not meet my expectation in terms of taste based on the photo they advertised. Today I ordered a pork belly salad special, which looked tasty from the photo. However what I got in the end was a small salad with some mediocre pork belly on top.  Underneath the pork and the salad were a lot of unappetizing, deep fried potato cubes (&#34;tater tots&#34;) which made the dish much bigger than what it really was.  I had a similar experience a month ago when I ordered salmon spaghetti which was drowning in cream sauce which looked nothing like the photo.  Never again!

Rating Vanilla Cafe a 3/5 reminds me of how many ok but not excellent places there are in Singapore. I&#39;d actually lean towards a 3.5 stars for this joint because it is kind of a cute place and the food isn&#39;t bad. I&#39;m just not excited enough to rate it higher. Do note this place is small and gets really crowded at lunch so call ahead to make a reservation.<br><br>Vanilla is a Japanese western cafe serving lunch bites like Katsu sandwiches, yakiniku don and salads. They also have this cute plate of silver dollar pancakes called the &#34;Simple Start&#34; that I&#39;ve been wanting to try. Note to the hungry, no not take the cafe&#39;s brochure back to the office or you will be salivating over the well taken pictures. In reality, the food portions are not very big. I&#39;ve tried the yakiniku don and had the rice replaced with a salad and it did the job. Smoked Salmon sandwich is also not bad but so small. I think the only item that won&#39;t leave you hungry is the dirt cake. If you haven&#39;t heard of it, walk by the cafe and have a look at their dessert display case. It&#39;ll put a smile on your face.

Agree that portions are a bit small. Enough for me but I don&#39;t eat all that much (or so I think!) anyway, popped in ard 830 on a Friday night after work, it filled up pretty quickly. Thought it&#39;d be a nice quiet cafe but boy was I wrong! Decor is nice and all, but the chatter quickly magnifies too.. I was somewhat assailed by all the noise.<br><br>My pan fried salmon took 20mins to come. And when it did, I was first wowed by the crispness of the salmon, but not so much the texture inside. It was a little overdone/dry and the sauce wasn&#39;t sufficient to save it. <br><br>That being said, it seems that the potatoes were more the saving grace. Nicely roasted and herbed, very comforting and deliciously savoury!

Stopped by for a quick lunch because my colleague was dying to try their Dirt Cake. It&#39;s very amusingly served, in a flower put with the oreo bits looking like soil, replete with gummy worms and a flower sticking out. Beyond the cute factor though, it was really quite mediocre in terms of taste. Not bad, just not special.<br><br>I had the Japanese curry with chicken, and it was pretty good. Chicken was super crispy and very well cooked (not as in &#34;well-done overcooked&#34;) but executed well and turning out crispy, light, and tasty. The curry was so-so, good enough to go back for, but not good enough that I&#39;d highlight it as a MUST TRY. They&#39;re also a little stingy on the curry, but we asked for more and they were very nice to bring an additional bowl of curry with carrots in it at no additional cost.<br><br>The &#39;half wings&#39; are, not a half portion of wings, but half the wing joint. While this reduces the amount of meat on each wing, it does make it really easy to eat. The crumb-coating on the wings is a little bit salty though, but if you just eat one or two, it&#39;s really quite tasty, and they&#39;re really crispy. Salt factor is the only point they could improve on. <br><br>Beyond that, nothing really left an impression. It&#39;s a stable place. Better than 2 stars, not really solidly three. Not such I&#39;d go back within a month of my first visit, but maybe when I&#39;ve exhausted all my other regular places I&#39;ll give it another try.

A really small cafe that is typical of shophouses along the telok ayer district, i was attracted to the name of the place. When I visited it, it was quite a surprise to find that there are strong Japanese influences in the cafe&#39;s decor and personality. Which makes it slightly on the unique side.<br><br>What made it really unique however was this dessert called the Vanilla Dirt Cake. It comes to you as a plant on top of a flower pot! Wow. When you actually dig into the &#34;dirt&#34; you will find it&#39;s just oreo crumbs on top of vanilla ice cream. The presentation is really humourous though and there&#39;s even a gummy worm beside the plant. <br><br>They also serve all-day breakfasts, and I had their All-English Breakfast for 9.90. What a steal! Anything less than $10 that includes egg, bacon, tater tots, 2 sausages and a salad is super worth it. Now I might need to remember this fact next time I am craving for an all-english breakfast.

I think for the price and location, this cafe is great! The meal portions are a good size and won&#39;t leave you feeling hungry. And the finger foods are always good. The desserts are great for sharing, but alone they may be too much for one person. It&#39;s definitely worth the time to check out!

Low country boil, but with salted egg sauce', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Low country boil, but with salted egg sauce'}]
text: Not another typical food court in Singapore.  The selection and food vendors here offer out of the ordinary choices.  A mediterrean grill, a &#39;low-country&#39; seafood shack, gourmet craft burgers , K-Chicken..  the only thing missing is cold beer and Anthony Bourdain..<br><br>Seating is a mess. Its first come , first serve and our party of 14 managed to snag a long table and quiet corner. I don;t know how it happened, but we managed to find seats all together.  Food is ordered from various vendors and they give you a pager to summon you back when your item is ready.<br><br>The burgers from Wolf burger was good.  The sushi / poke was good too.  The seafood , crab boil was not really &#39;low country&#39; boil. Instead it was covered in a dollop of the famous salted egg sauce.  This salted egg sauce is all over everything in Singapore.  I guess we have ketchup here, and Europe has mayonnaise, and Singapore has salted egg sauce..

text: Cool and funky hangout. Nice place to have causal dinner with friends.<br><br>An upscale concept of food court. There are several shops offering different cuisine - Vietnamese, Grill, Western, Seafood, Sandwiches, Italian and a salad bar. They managed to squeeze In a drinks bar and fruit juice to cater for those who want a healthier option.<br><br>The fancy color and whimsical decor makes the place feel fun and cheery. They play loud but not overbearing music. They definitely got the ambience thing right!<br><br>Food wise - we ordered from the Grill. Ordered a Yuzu Salmon Bowl, Short Ribs Bowl and Sweet Potato Fries. Total cost was around $30. <br><br>The short ribs bowl was the best, the sauce, meat and rice were perfectly done. Was really delicious! The Salmon was ok, while the sweet potatoes fries was below average. <br><br>Wish we had a bottomless stomach to try the rest of the stalls. <br><br>It&#39;s a great place to hang with friends over dinner and drinks.

text: PasarBella was an absolute breath of fresh air for me. I will be honest, I am not a fan of most Food courts or hawker Centers. Please do not burn me at the stake, my Texas pallet just needs a little time to adjust. I will put it this way, no adjustment needed for PasarBella. It is an inviting, hip food court. The feel is very sleek and everything is spot on. The decor is fabulous and inviting and the music is awesome. I was overwhelmed by the choices. I ordered a sushi roll from Rolly Ollies. It is by far the most delicious (and filling) sushi roll that I have had in Singapore. My Husband had a Wolf burger, sweet potato fries and a vanilla milkshake. He kindly shared a couple of sips of his milkshake with me. It was outstanding. PasarBella is the perfect jumping off point for a food court trip. I will be back!
Probably could be considered a high end food court. Nice variety, from local to seafood to Western/European  selections. Slightly pricey but its still good value.

This place is a bit hidden away in the corporate surrounds of Suntec City Mall. Seems quite new and the concept is a food court in a mall including Western food like bars, burgers and coffee shop with Asian favourites. The mix of stalls was great and would suit most appetites. I had burger from Wolf Burgers. Not bad for good old Singapore. Bottom lime nice concept &amp; good fresh food!

text: Came here for dinner last sat night. Wasn&#39;t too difficult to get a seat for 4 at 7 so that was pretty good. We waited about 5 mins?<br><br>Food overall was disappointing. Looked/smelt better than it tasted.<br><br>Wagyu onsen bowl$14.90<br>Looked amazing in the pics and the first bite was heaven. I loved the mix of the sauce/egg/rice. Amazing; might almost pay just for that. However found the beef lacking, it was too chewy and also rubbery. Not sure if it was because it was too raw or that it was just like that. <br><br>Chorizo sausage$6.90<br>Didn&#39;t like this at all. <br><br>Truffle mash $2<br>Friend liked this but I found it extremely average. <br><br>Creamy spinach $2<br>I quite liked this. Reminded me a little of panek paneer. Decent to share<br><br>Lamb<br>Friend ordered and said it was good. <br><br>The Mexican store.<br>Friend tried it and thought it was average. I tried the hummus, it was ok but I wouldn&#39;t order next time.<br><br>Seafood store<br>Friend ordered the grilled fish. It took around an hour to arrive! So we pretty much weren&#39;t hungry by then and found it average. Sides of Chicken luncheon chips and sweet potato fries were very average too. <br><br>Probably wouldn&#39;t go back unless someone really wanted me to

Death by chocolate cake ($12++) - 3 stars<br>The cake was on the dry side (mitigated by the ice cream) and the frosting was too sweet but it was overall decent. The ice cream tasted pretty regular, nothing amazing. Without the frosting it wasn&#39;t too sweet. Satisfies a craving.<br><br>Service - 5 stars

Corned beef croquettes', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Corned beef croquettes'}]
text: We went to Riders on a Saturday for brunch and it was packed. We overheard the staff saying that the waiting time was about half an hour. Fortunately, we&#39;d made a reservation, so we practically sailed right past the waiting line. <br><br>I like the atmosphere of the cafe. It was open, inviting and bustling with activity. Perfect place for people-watching. We were seated on the balcony facing the stables. My initial concern was about the smell, but it was unnoticeable. <br><br>We had the corned beef croquettes, Riders Burger, and homemade sausages with creme fraiche scrambled eggs. The croquettes were good - the crispy, golden brown breadcrumbs gave way to creamy potatoes with the occasional chewy beef bits. The corned beef offered a pleasant pop of flavour that accented the mild potato taste. They were truly enjoyable to eat. The portion was generous too. I expected maybe two pieces of croquettes but there were four - more than enough for a starter. <br><br>The Riders Burger was all about the beef. The other ingredients were reminciscent of Burger King&#39;s Western Whopper, but they were all overwhelmed by the beef. This burger would be perfect for meat lovers.<br><br>I chose the homemade sausages and creme fraiche scrambled eggs because they came with a leek and potato rosti. Unfortunately they looked better than they tasted. The hollandaise sauce was the best part of the dish. The scrambled eggs were fluffy and creamy, but for the most part tasteless, but that was ok as we had salt and pepper at our table. The rosti was, strangely, creamy. It was essentially fried mashed potato and leek. There was a mild taste of leek on the fried surface, but that was overpowered by the flavourless mush that was underneath. Next to the mild flavours of the eggs and mush, the sausage tasted too strong, which shocks the taste buds. I dipped most of what I could in the hollandaise to get some flavour, but there was barely a spoonful of it to begin with. <br><br>The food may have been slightly disappointing, but the service was excellent. The crew was attentive and proactive, and we could really tell that they were properly trained to provide high-level service. For that, kudos to the staff AND the owner/management of Riders Cafe for caring. <br><br>Service really contributes half, if not more, to customer experience and satisfaction. For this, I would definitely go back to Riders (and order other things on the menu instead).

Pacific benedict', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pacific benedict'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/v3WBQ3Os2YpJRGEf02VB6w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/riders-cafe-singapore?reviewid=paErq8DmfomF8FU6AR8LQQ&select=v3WBQ3Os2YpJRGEf02VB6w', 'altText': 'Photo of Riders Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. French Toast with bananas', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'French Toast with bananas'}]
text: It is definitely advisable to make reservations at least 1 day in advance (they don&#39;t take same day booking) as it is still full house at Riders Cafe on weekends. They do take walk in customers but likely you just have to wait for at least 30 minutes or more. It is not so bad as you get to gaze at the lush greenery, clear blue sky (if it is not raining) and listen to the neighing and clopping of horses every time they are led back into the stables. Quite enjoyable as it is not a common sight in this concrete jungle.<br><br>Being my 2nd visit in a span of a few years, I am glad the food is still as good. <br><br>We shared the pacific benedict and brioche french toast with bananas. They were excellent. <br><br>Quite a generous serving of swimmer crab meat with nicely poached eggs and spinach and shrimp hollandaise (couldn&#39;t taste the shrimp) sauce. Something different from the usual egg benedict or eggs royale. <br><br>The soft brioche made a perfect french toast. Loved the grilled banana caramelized with a thin layer of sugar, crispy bacon and maple syrup. <br><br>The cafe mocha was also decent. <br><br>Being a full house, service was a bit slow but not as bad as some places. There is no air conditioning throughout, except for the washrooms below stairs, adding to the charm of a rustic setting with fresh air coming in through the verandah. <br><br>Note: You need a car or taxi to get to the restaurant.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/oPQAc-GID4XML9p0YeNcGg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/riders-cafe-singapore?reviewid=cH4uL-EcDnugeH437r9wfQ&select=oPQAc-GID4XML9p0YeNcGg', 'altText': 'Photo of Riders Cafe - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Riders Cafe is one of the earlier brunch spots which was so popular that reservations have to be placed in advance. Fortunately and coincidentally, there was a table cancellation when I called on the previous day of visit and so we did not have much problems securing seats. <br><br>The usual brunch suspects were delicious and certainly lived up to the predominantly positive comments that were aplenty in the media or online community. <br><br>Brioche French Toast with Fresh Berries and Vanilla Mascarpone $14 are great for those who like to start the day on a sweet note. The alternative french toast option comes with maple butter, smoked bacon and burnt bananas. <br><br>Unlike &#34;The Usual&#34; ($16), Black stone Benedict ($15) comes with the extra hollandaise sauce on poached eggs and crispy bacon instead of bangers and mushrooms.To me, hollandaise sauce is the supporting cast that makes the leading cast (soft poached eggs with bursting egg yolk) shine. <br><br>I had been tempted all along to challenge the Death by Chocolate Cake with Vanilla Ice cream $12 but I was disillusioned eventually. This won by quantity and not quality. The chocolate ganache was not velvety and stood unmoving like a rubbery coating. There was not much contrast in the taste because everything from the cake to the ice cream was cloyingly sweet. <br><br>Instead, the Salted Caramel Cheesecake with Crumbled Honeycomb $8 would attract one to take a second bite or even more. The cheesecake itself tasted as natural as it could get, without too much sugar added. Would be ideal if there is more of the salted caramel frosting. <br><br>Special items of the day are written on the black board. Even though many other brunch spots and cafe have sprouted incessantly in Singapore, Riders Cafe is a good option for brunch or even dinner with the accompaniment of horses. But the location is only convenient if you can find your way there in a car or by a taxi.

text: Reservation is essential for brunch, especially on weekends, if you do not want to be turned away in disappointment. Nice ambiance for couples and families for a morning of chill and relax. Travelling in is a problem, though. Would be great if you have your own transportation.<br><br>Food is very good for such a hipster location. Really loved their french toasts and big breakfast, quality of food matches up to its aesthetics. Dinner crowd is significantly smaller than its brunch&#39;s, superb for couples who value some quiet time.<br><br>Outside of norm must trys: french toast with caramelised banana and bacon (brunch), and seafood risotto (dinner).

text: We alighted at a bus stop at Dunearn Road and then walked in from Eng Neo Avenue. <br>Poor people like need to <br>take public transport. :( As we don&#39;t drive, we had to walk in and it is a LONG journey. <br>The road aren&#39;t exactly people friendly. <br>I suggest people who are going there to drive in.<br><br>The place is located beside ranches and you can probably see some horses outside the window.<br><br>The decor is nicely decorated and place looks cozy for a lovely afternoon brunch. <br><br>I suggest you can try this. PACIFIC BENEDICT WITH SWIMMER CRAB, POACHED EGGS,SPINACH AND SHRIMP HOLLANDAISE.<br><br>Theres a pleasant surprise underneath the eggs. You can see huge chunks of crab meat. yum yum.

text: One of my favorite brunch places in Singapore! I always have trouble deciding between the crab omelet and the Blackstone Benedict, but the best part of the meal: the molten lava chocolate cake. Rather indulgent for breakfast, but it&#39;s worth it! I especially love being able to enjoy brunch while watching the horses.

text: I haven&#39;t really explored many brunch spots in Singapore. But from those that I have visited so far, Riders Cafe is my favorite. We tried to get a reservation the day before and was told that they were fully booked. They would still accept walk-ins though, and that&#39;s what we did. We had to wait for about 30 minutes for our table. Not too bad, considering you can wait in the car until they call you.<br><br>I had the poached egg, portobello, sweet corn polenta and it was cooked very nicely. It&#39;s a very simple dish but the execution was very good. Another dish that we had was the almond-granola crusted fried chicken. I think the crispness of the almond &amp; granola matches very well as a batter for the fried chicken. I must note that they also served the corn polenta in this dish, too repetitive IMO.<br><br>We also ordered the roasted pork belly and it was the letdown of the meal. It was such a sin to cook a pork that way. The skin was hard and not crispy and the meat was just dried out.<br><br>I&#39;ll definitely go to Riders Cafe to try the other items in their menu again though. I heard that their dinner menu is also good and that&#39;s another reason to come back.

text: The Riders Cafe is decidedly one of my favourite brunch places in Singapore. You don&#39;t get too many awesome poached eggs around here (or maybe I just haven&#39;t tried enough), but they do it pretty good here. Coffee&#39;s also good, and being in the middle of nowhere is fantastic. It&#39;s a great way to get away from the skyscrapers and clogged roads that characterises much of Singapore these days. Smell a bit of green grass, smell a bit of horses.. it&#39;s very therapeutic. If you&#39;ve eaten too much of it&#39;s good food, you can always loiter around afterwards and explore a bit. A very nice way to spend a morning. <br><br>The only gripe I have is that it&#39;s extremely inaccessible. Even if you are up for a bit of a trek. It&#39;s quite impossible to walk in from Dunearn Road, or I haven&#39;t found a way yet! Then again, it&#39;s a small price to pay for the wholesome experience.<br><br>Oh and I never never manage to squeeze in a reservation for weekend brunch unless I call at least a week in advance.

text: Love the chocolate lava cake! The eggs benedict is great too. My friends and I really enjoy the pleasant setting on a Saturday or Sunday morning - if you like horses, it&#39;s a plus too. Remember to call ahead to make your reservation, as it can get quite busy.

text: Choose this place for friend&#39;s meet up suggested by my friend. This place is only accessible by car so we took a cab in. We went there around noon time without any booking made. As expected, we need to wait to be seated. Waiting time was 45mins and since we are already there, there is no reason why we don&#39;t wait. Located at the Bukit Timah Saddle Club, we take the chance to walk around the place enjoying the scenic around us. On and off, someone will ride a horse pass you.<br><br>We were seated and served. service was good where service crew introduced the different dishes to us. The food was passable but on a hot day without wind can be quite unbearable for people who can&#39;t tolerate warm like my friend. We still managed to sit there for 2hr of chit chatting without the crew any hint to suggest us to leave. Definitely a good place to gather for meetup. <br><br>If you come in by cab, most probably, you will need to call a cab out again. Very inaccessible.

text: One of the best places to head to for a good breakfast/ brunch on the weekends!<br><br>The place is non air-conditioned, but pretty well-ventilated with the in-house ceiling fans and outdoor natural wind (and lots of sun in the morning!) The best spots to dine at are the few tables on the side of the cafe that overlooks the stable. (Check out the pictures I&#39;ve uploaded!) <br><br>For breakfast, meals are usually accompanied with eggs that you can have it your own style: poach, scramble or omelette. <br><br>The waiting line during the weekends is pretty long. So, make sure you call up the cafe to make reservations before heading down. <br><br>Getting there is another obstacle. The nearest bus stop is a good 15- 20 mins walk away. I would suggest driving  or cabbing in.  <br><br>But hey, I assure you the experience, food and service is worth the all the trouble! (especially to wake up early on an early Saturday morning just to have brekkie!)

text: We went for lunch to rider&#39;s cafe on a day when the weather was amazing - very pleasant, not too sunny. The ambiance is very laid back and nice. <br>Food for us was ok, nothing spectacular. We did like our milkshakes and juices though.  <br>We had scrambled eggs, chicken blt, beef burger and pasta.

text: Rider&#39;s is on the favourites list of many brunch-goers, which is why if you plan to have a brunch date here on weekends, you better plan well ahead because its hard to get a seat if you didn&#39;t make reservations. <br><br>Fairways Drive is not a place you want to go to if you don&#39;t drive, if you&#39;re taking a cab, you&#39;ll have to direct the cab driver because not many are familiar with the place. <br><br>But even with its remote accessibility, its still packed! Because the food and ambience are something you&#39;d travel for, they&#39;re that good.<br><br>To me, they have the best pancakes! Fluffy, buttery, creamy goodness with fresh blueberries and cream. Their poached eggs and salmon comes a close second. Plus enjoying it in a cosy setting against the greenery with horses grazing in the background doesn&#39;t hurt!<br><br>You can take a walk outside and maybe have your kids go on a pony ride (only $10!) after brunch, its not just a nice romantic brunch place but good for families too.<br><br>Final verdict: One of the most quaint brunch places in Singapore in one of the last countryside corners of this urban jungle.

Riders Cafe is a lovely quiet cafe with alfresco dining available. Was there for dinner, and thought it a great place to chill out over a nice dinner.<br><br>Food: A better option than Marmalade Pantry @ The Stables. The pork chops were absolutely delicious, and so was the Chilean cod. Really liked the lavender creme brulee, and the chocolate cake is to-die-for.<br><br>Ambience: Quite a nice chill out joint for dinner, one can opt to sit alfresco if the weather is cool. There&#39;s no aircon, so if you&#39;re not one to tolerate heat and humidity, highly suggested you go in the evening. Slight pong of horse manure, but not overwhelming and one gets only very faint whiffs now and then.<br><br>Service: Generally friendly and polite, but seemed a bit lost.<br><br>Only reason I wouldn&#39;t recommend this place is &#39;cos I wanna keep the crowds away.

NAAAAYYYYYYYYY. That was me imitating horses.<br><br>This riders café is a little bit atas, you can&#39;t deny it. It&#39;s not every restaurant that can have horses at their backyard. Okay, not exactly backyard, it&#39;s the Bukit Timah Saddle Club. That said, it&#39;s a great selling point. You get to see horses galloping by and reconcile the Black Beauty part of you.<br><br>They serve you jars of water the moment you sit down (WOOTS), service is prompt. Go early and try the egg dishes from their breakfast menu, couple good choices are poached eggs or baked eggs. Their Death by Chocolate Cake is a must-try dessert. OMNOMSNOMSNOMS.<br><br>The al fresco atmosphere was very wind-in-my-hair, especially on Sunday mornings. It&#39;s been a while since I went there, not sure how it&#39;s like in the recent heatwave though. Be sure to make bookings in advance, now that everyone knows about this café with horses in the backyard.<br><br>Check out <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Featlikeawhale.blogspot.sg&amp;s=073078668bba0d0a43c2d19980dbd9384767b13a2e1457c8da39273937aa332c" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">eatlikeawhale.blogspot.sg</a> for more pictures and reviews.

Where else can you watch ponies trot by as you enjoy brunch? <br><br>In a lovely little cottage-like house with wooden beams and everything else that makes it feel like a modern ranch, Riders cafe is as laid back as brunching can get. If you take a sanity leave day from work, this is where you should come to get away from it all. Eggs benedict, smoked salmon and pancakes next to horses, the world might be alright again.<br><br>It&#39;s a little out of the way, best if you drive, or else it might be a pain getting in and home.
