text: A non-airconditioned place which is great for brunch. Do get there by car/taxi though, as it is relatively unaccessible otherwise. I love the lush greenery this place is set in, and how it is housed near horse stables. The eggs benedict here with salmon is pretty good -  the portions were not that generous but sufficient. Do remember to make reservations if you want your date to be impressed.

One of my favorite brunch places because of the excellent food and view they have, I am quite sad to find that more and more people know about this place. That&#39;s because then it gets really crowded and the quality of the food/service might be affected as well. However, barring that, yes I would recommend this place since I last had it because their brunch was really delicious. It was wholesome, yummy eggs and sausages with the usual other sides. An iced coffee while watching some horses gallop by is nice as well.<br><br>Prices were also reasonable if I don&#39;t recall wrongly.<br><br>Getting there however will require a car. Otherwise it is too much of a hassle to travel in and out of the place. Reservations are definitely required because it is super popular with the expats and locals alike.

text: Very kids friendly and excellent brunch menu.  It is a popular place on the weekends - the ambience is nice - old black and White House.  The highlight is the weekend pony rides at S$10 / person.  A place recommended with small or big group.  Book ahead.

text: Excluded location tucked away in Fairway Drive near the Singapore Turf Club. Rocked up on a Saturday for brunch one weekend. I didn&#39;t have a booking, and Im not too sure if they take brunch bookings, though had to wait for a wee bit to get a table on the verandah. No air con in this place, though they have done well to make sure it quite comfortable and airy. Straight forward comforting food here, think shepherd&#39;s pie, beef burger, eggs ben etc etc. Well priced items, freshly squeezed orange juice always wins extra brownie points in my books. Had the shepherd&#39;s pie which was ok, would of gone down better if it was perhaps made in the classical way with mince lamb as opposed to braising diced lamb.  Service, at least the young girl who served or table had to be one of the cheeriest I&#39;ve had in Singapore.

text: Salads for only $4.90! So if you&#39;re tired of spending more than $8 for a salad (I&#39;m looking at you Salad Stop!, Sumo Salad, Salad Shop, and the many other that I can&#39;t think of on the top of my head!), then Sun Moon is definitely the place for you. They also make fresh fruit juices! Prices for juices range from $1.50-$3.00 depending on the juice or added ingredient, ie honey, sugar, etc.<br><br>I also like how Sun Moon carries a lot of healthy, organic snacks, many of them aren&#39;t even sold in the local Cold Storage! The prices here are slightly higher than the average NTUC but the quality is def. there. The shop is closed on Mondays but will continue to make fresh fruit juices by request on Saturdays -- unlike the Sun Moon over at Raffles MRT :(

text: I never knew Liho had a cafe place; always thought that they were a &#39;grab and go&#39; kiosk kinda business.<br><br>Anyway, we were craving bubble tea and wanted a place to sit down. Luckily, we chanced upon this after walking past Starbucks and were plesantly surprised to learn that this quaint set-up belongs to Liho!<br><br>Love, love, love their decor; it&#39;s so simple and classic. Luckily, again, for us, we dropped by just after the dinner hour and there wasn&#39;t much people in the cafe. They even had an elaborate set-up for tea-brewing!<br><br>We ordered the Honey Milk Tea with Pearl. We weren&#39;t asked for the sugar level because most Honey drinks are already sweetened naturally. However, my daughter took a few sips and found it too sweet. I tried and gosh it was sweet! I brought it back to the guy behind the counter (he looks like an ah beng but was so gentle and soft-spoken! Surprise!) and asked if he could add more ice as it was too sweet. Without a word, he proceeded to add more ice and even top up our tea! I was shocked! He then passed me the cup and said that he added more tea &#39;on the house&#39; to balance the flavour. This is what I call excellent pro-activeness and good service!<br><br>The only downside (that&#39;s why my review is 4 stars!) was that they still give plastic cups/straws even though customers opted to dine in. They should, perhaps, consider glass cups and steel straws/or no straw policy.

text: whether you are driving to work or a taxi driver taking a break, and looking for a place to grab a cheap, peaceful, tasty, filling bite without worrying about them parking pontianaks(summons officers), this is the oasis for you!<br><br>in fact, the parking pontianaks themselves come here to eat too!:)<br><br>this is by far the cheapest place in SG for a meal!<br>(do let me know if you come across other cheaper places!)<br><br>got only $5?<br>no worries mate, this is the place for you!<br><br>seek out the chinese kway chap/bee hoon stall!<br>here, you can get a big fat juicy chicken wing, fried egg and luncheon meat plus a mountain of yummy mommy&#39;s bee hoon fried with vegetables for only $2.80!<br>grab a teh c peng kosong for only $0.90 cents from the drinks stall on the far left corner.<br>pay $1, for the same, if you choose to be a far right supporter.<br>even if you had two drinks, your $5 will still get you some change!<br><br>if you seek something halal, the muslim stall in the middle dishes out all the staple for between $2-$2.50!<br>be it mee siam, mee rebus, nasi goreng, nasi ayam etc!<br>all comfort, home cooked and sedap sia!<br><br>plentiful free parking within the compound itself and along both sides of jalan benaan kapal.<br>just make sure you can differentiate dotted white lines from continuous white ones and never be selectively colour blind and park where double yellow lines rule!<br>else your parking ticket will surely be way more expensive than your meal itself!

text: I had both the Oyster Omelette and the Oyster Egg. I prefer the Oyster Omelette. The sticky dough portion of the dish is crispy (which can be a rare occurrence) and a delight for folks like me who do not like gooey-tasting dough. The proportion of oysters to egg to dough is also perfect.<br><br>The chili sauce is normal, just how it should taste like.<br><br>I have had fresher tasting oysters in a oyster omelette but overall this is a good dish and I will come back for more.

text: Stayed at V Hotel across the street and decided to stop by for breakfast. It was the only restaurant nearby that had a line out the door so I decided to give it a try. <br><br>You queue up and order your food first. They&#39;ll make you your drinks right a way and give you a buzzer to let you know when you&#39;re good is ready. My group of 3 ordered 3 of the specials and we enjoyed them all. All the food seemed high quality. The laksa was really good with a tasty broth. <br><br>It gets pretty busy around 7-8am, but the line dies around 9am. Seating wasn&#39;t too bad, not much of a wait. Toast box is a must try when you&#39;re in Singapore.

text: Five stars for the gelato - I had the peppermint and Pistachio. Gelato is a new addition just two weeks ago . Would definitely come back for gelato and coffee !

I went for lunch here one day. I had a ham and cheese sandwich, severely overpriced and nothing special for $8. Not filling either. On the side I had a lemon tart, which tasted generic  (most likely ordered from a supplier). <br><br>The acoustics are terrible. I heard the whole conversation of the guy sitting behind me ranting about his girlfriend, and then a group of office workers came for lunch and the din of their voices plus the clinking of cutlery gave me a headache.

text: A few of my colleagues and I checked this place out during lunch time as it was pretty near to my office (around 15 mins walk).<br><br>If you&#39;re like me and crave for some good &#39;ole local (and cheap) food for lunch, don&#39;t bet your lunch money on this cafe. Have some wantan mee or teochew porridge around the area before heading here for some coffee and cakes.<br><br>The local offerings on the menu doesn&#39;t go beyond the 5 fingers on my right hand but it was ok for a cafe standard with the price range around Wang Cafe&#39;s standard. My colleagues ordered the Curry Chicken Set, 1 Slice of Mushroom Pizza, Yam Cake and Glutinous Rice. I had a few bites of it and it was not too shabby. <br><br>For my, I had my own lunch at the nearby famous Teochew Porridge stall but that&#39;s a review for another time.<br><br>On another note, I absolutely love the lemon curt tart which boost the same texture as MacD&#39;s Sausage McMuffin Bun with a sweet lemony stuffing which takes you by surprise. Very nice dessert which I will return for. Didn&#39;t try the coffee as I was abstaining from coffee for a week following my food poisoning but the brew that my colleague was nursing smelt oh-so-good!

text: The coffee is good. The cakes are not. The cakes are dense and feel a bit dry.<br><br>What I like about the place is the relative quietness compared to the more hip and happening Tiong Bahru (Yong Siak and surrounds) area. This place has a bit of family run feel to it with its limited menu serving local food with a twist. The decor is simple and minimalist, with some likening it to a Muji-like ambience with its use of aluminium and wood. Pots of plants on the table and around the place does make it a bit homely too.<br><br>A bit of background on this place from what I have read in the news and from friends living in the area. It used to be a stationery store for decades and now the grandchildren have taken over the premise by turning it into a small cafe. According to the media, the grandchildren pay rent to their grandpa who still owns the place. I thought that is a nice touch, plus the shop still stays in the family. <br><br>Besides cakes (probably outsourced from other place) and beverages, you can get local delights such as yam cake, glutinous rice, laksa, curry chicken rice and fried chicken wings (I read some are made with their family recipes). The typical kaya toast with soft boiled eggs has been changed to kaya with clotted cream. Mmmm....clotted cream. Besides kaya, you can also choose lemon curd or fruit jam. There are also regular basic ham and cheese sandwiches and simple pizza for savory food.<br><br>If I live in this area, it will make a pretty great spot to chill with a cup of coffee. It is not overly crowded for now. Tables are spaced out nicely that you do not feel claustrophobic or that you can accidentally eavesdrop on others&#39; conversation.

Probably a good comparison would be Food Junction, Kopitiam.<br><br>There are different stalls serving different food like the above places. Clean, and not much strong smells that stays on the clothes. Variety is decent, although there&#39;s a few empty stalls. <br><br>We had the 小蒙牛 spicy pot. Average pricing, decent quality, fresh meats, crunchy vegetables. Portions is reasonable. Two of us the pot is $17, consisting of 3 types of meat, 5 type of vegetable, medium spiciness.<br><br>We liked the taste, comparable to the other spicy pots around the country.

text: A bubble tea shop has recently taken over the space that was formerly occupied by a shop which used to sell natural soaps, and candles. The location is at the back of the hotel. It was a small area which most tend to miss it. The standing area in the store is very small, with 2 stools by the wall, with another 2 stools outside the store.<br><br>Unlike the usual bubble tea stores where we selected the sugar level of the drinks ranging from 100% to 0%, here the system is to increase or decrease from the prefect sugar level. <br><br>Brown Sugar Milk Tea 黑糖经典奶茶 ($2.90)<br>I had the drink at the prefect level, which I felt not too sweet but the brown sugar flavour was not as distinct as I would prefer.<br><br>The store offers interesting toppings available such as Osmanthus Collagen, Matcha Pudding, Panna Cotta Pudding, Rose Q Star, Passion Fruit Q Star, Honey Q Star, Amber Q Star, Matcha Ice Cream, Royal Ice Cream, and Purple Mood (Purple Sweet Potato Ice Cream).

text: Since this Starbucks opened, students have been flocking here like flies to honey. Seriously, unless you&#39;re incredibly lucky to enter just when someone&#39;s leaving, it&#39;s unlikely you&#39;ll find a seat.<br><br>Same goes for the iMacs in the middle of the coffee shop: I&#39;ve never seen them unoccupied. And hey, iMacs in a Starbucks! Is anything cooler than that?!?!<br><br>That said, if you&#39;re not fussy about air-conditioning, you can always get takeaways and sit at the much bigger study area just outside the coffee shop. It stays relatively cool no matter how hot the whether gets thanks to the huge fan spinning above.

text: Nice little Kopi shop in the Takashima shopping centre. Located in B2.<br><br>Was fairly busy when we got here so maybe a sign that it is popular. They have a selection of breakfast and noodle soups (which are also breakfast here).<br><br>I had the Kaya butter toast (pandan jam) and my wife had the savoury chicken, ham and mozzarella cheese toast. Bother we&#39;re delicious. The Kopi (coffee) was excellent. I had mine black and hers with milk and sugar. <br><br>Good quick breakfast snack!
Quite good for breakfast and lunch. <br>Serves local food like kaya toast, soft boiled eggs, local coffee and tea. <br>Noodles

text: The kopi is surprisingly good. I like it a lot. Robust and sweet with a generous lashing of evaporated milk. The kaya butter toast was equally good and could give Ya Lum a run for its money in the crispy toast department. <br><br>The laksa was not that great. I liked the ingredients but the gravy lacked flavor and punch. Eat Laksa is much better in comparison. <br><br>At 4pm on a weekday, it was about 50% full. It made a nice respite from shopping or the heat.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/u-oTBckYUQla139POxosJA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/hai-sing-coffee-stall-singapore?reviewid=ICyPB3ZnVyYrufqLJDuvVA&select=u-oTBckYUQla139POxosJA', 'altText': 'Photo of Hai Sing Coffee Stall - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: My second favourite coffee stall in this hawker centre, due largely to the friendly service. You have to walk up to order and it&#39;s all self-service, and it tastes okay, but the stall is friendly and accommodating to whatever outlandish coffee requests you may have.<br><br>An example: once, an auntie tried to cut the queue, but the owner was politely insistent that she get in queue and continued serving the rest of the customers instead of giving in to her demands.<br><br>As usual, on top of hot brewed drinks, you can also order canned beverages, but I don&#39;t think they serve toast and soft-boiled eggs.<br><br>The good service coupled with its long history in this hawker centre has earned the stall a bunch of loyal customers, even though the coffee and tea is honestly nothing remarkable.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/foZBkfhuWist6mnnbzdqhQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ya-kun-kaya-toast-singapore-20?reviewid=azYzduQtSh84GjPp8KhT-w&select=foZBkfhuWist6mnnbzdqhQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Ya Kun Kaya Toast - Singapore, Singapore. Kaya Toast set #1 with eggs and kofi', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Kaya Toast set #1 with eggs and kofi'}]
text: It&#39;s one of those things that you do when you are in Singapore. No, seriously. You have to have a kaya toast breakfast with eggs and some kopi. When you do some research and homework, one spot comes up on all of the lists: Ya Kun. <br><br>Now, they are a chain and its locations sprout up around the city offering convenience. Yet, this location in the Far East Plaza is the first. So you are almost taken to its humble beginnings with the wooden stools and the almost simple posters adorning its walls. <br><br>Head over and order combination #1 if you have absolutely no idea what to get. It&#39;s simple and gets you that kaya toast, a poached egg, and that cup of kopi. The kaya toast is pretty respectable with the sweet kaya jam made form coconut, pandan, sugar, and eggs. Dip the crisp bread into the soft poached eggs to bring that saltiness to contrast the sweet flavors of the jam.<br><br>Service is pretty good and the wait isn&#39;t very long as they briskly made your order and the price pretty reasonable. It&#39;s location is tucked in the back corner of the plaza&#39;s lower level, so it could be easy to miss. Head down the stairs and head to the front left hand corner fronting Scotts road and you&#39;ll find it.

text: This quite literally was my first meal in Singapore, having arrived late the night before, but as breakfast goes there was nothing really special about this place. They open early in the morning when Singaporeans and tourists have not started their day yet which is a big plus. However, the offerings that they had resembled what is available in most American diners, but distinct at the same time.  I opted to have the French toast and eggs with coffee. The French toast was cut into bite size pieces and served with a rather sweet, thick caramel sauce. The egg was lightly poached, but broken up so that the yolk was floating in the water. It wasn&#39;t my favorite egg dish. My subsequent breakfast in Singapore was better but for those interested in checking it out when you are in the area it&#39;s located in the Far East Plaza basement at a food-court of sorts.

text: I found the Asian secret to staying Skinny in Singapore. Eat here. The toast you eat is one piece of bread, open up the middle of the bread and stuff it with yummy stuff. Cut down the need for eating 2 pieces of bread (excess carbs) in a sandwich. I also found the secret why Singapore is SO Clean. No trash or junk on the ground. There are no napkins at restaurants. So no opportunity for you to litter your napkins on the ground. And we bring our own tissue.

text: Forget Starbucks, whenever there&#39;s Yakun I head straight for its coffee. Not all local coffee shops are the same, Yakun is just richer and has its own unique flavor. <br>Whenever I go shopping at Far East Plaza I recharge at this outlet when I&#39;m tired from walking.

text: This is one of the Ya Kun outlets that is always buzzing with activity. It is quite a nice place to rest your feet after a whole day of shopping. The service is good, and there are considerably a lot of seats for such a small shop space. I like that their staff are familiar with the regulars and make friendly exchanges. The taste of the food and drink is also up to the Ya Kun standard; nothing that needs to be complained about really.

text: Star Visa food options are geared more for the expats staying around the area. Qiji provides an option for those looking for everyday price options. They serve the local favorites, ranging from Nasi Lemak to Mee Siam. For just below $5, you can get a complete set of Nasi Lemak that comes with a fried chicken or fried fish.<br><br>The seatings are cleaner and in an air-conditioned environment although you are paying for hawker food prices. The staff are mostly friendly although there is one or two that don&#39;t seem to understand English. <br><br>Flavor-wise, they are as good as the Ananas but with a bigger portion and freshly prepared. Recommend if you want something cheap and fast!

text: Located at a quiet corner near Serangoon Stadium, Jim Foods Supplier is probably one of the safer bets when it comes to getting fresh seafood - especially crabs. The juicy, succulent, sweet kind. My cousins swear by this shop: they come here regularly when they want their monthly fix of crabs and other seafood for grilling and barbecuing. The shop prides itself on being a major importer of the latter, and starts selling them in the early morning. The shop opens as early as 7-8am.<br><br>If you&#39;re looking for fresh scallops in amounts equalling or exceeding 0.5kg, Jim Foods deals with high-quality frozen scallops (I had a quote of $18 for half a kg). You should call ahead in the morning (maybe 8am or so) to check if they have them available before you head down. On one occasion, I called at 11am and they said they had run out. On another occasion, I reached the place at around 8.45am and the person there told me that availability for scallops was never an issue. In light of contradictory evidence, it&#39;s best you play safe and call first!

text: if you are looking for crabs of good quality then this is the place to buy. they might not have the cheapest price around town but the quality and freshness can always be assured. i&#39;ve been buying crabs for my family from them since a few years ago and i can say that they have the freshest crabs. they also have quite a large variety of frozen foods selling a a cheaper price than ntuc. i always buy frozen food and crabs for any steamboat parties i have. but be sure to call them in advance to ask if they have any crabs left as on some occasions that i make the trip down, the crabs have already been sold out or are reserved so remember to call to avoid disappointment. i heard from a few friends that they supply to coffee shops, restaurants and large scale hotels all over singapore!

Crumbly, melt-in-your-mouth butter cookies fresh from Hong Kong. <br><br>This *is* the famed Jenny Bakery from Hong Kong, and Singapore is the FIRST official store outside HK. The fresh butter cookies are airflown directly from HK factory to Singapore by DHL.<br><br>Just like in Hong Kong, the cookies come in their signature teddy bear tin. Not every cookie flavor is available, and payment is cash only. Each customer is restricted to a maximum 3 tin purchase, stock is limited, and they might sell out early so call ahead. You can also reserve cookies online on their website, for in-store pickup.<br><br>I have no idea why their first store is buried under a nondescript block of apartments in Ang Mo Kio. It&#39;s a short hike from Ang Mo Kio MRT station, but it&#39;s not visible from the street. Check the directions on google maps before going there.<br><br>I personally like the coffee flavored cookie, but I find the price of S$45 for the large can of cookies rather steep. (The small can costs S$25) It&#39;s much cheaper buying them in Hong Kong but hey - the trip to Ang Mo Kio is much nearer.

Working in Asia Square, I am always on the hunt for a quick, healthy lunch.  Always.  So, when a collegue read that Jar&#39;d by Sarnies opened up, I was all for it.  I had been making salads in jars for a few years (thanks to Pintrest) and was curious how this idea was going to translate to a business.  I loved the branding, and the concept, and the fact that I could keep the jar, so off we went to the Raffles basement to get our salads.  It&#39;s a small little kiosk like everything else down there, but easy enough to find.  They had a few options, a vegetarian zoodle (zucchini noodles I think with a thai dressing) a chicken pesto one, a tuna one, and one other one I forgot.  They also serve them in two sizes, and the prices vary depending on the protein.  My friend got the vegetarian one ($14) and I went for the tuna one ($16) both were the smaller jars, but the salad was quite a bit, and I only finished about half.  They also serve coffee, and this coconut whip thingy that is supposed to be like soft serve, but according to my friend who had it tasted like nothing.  I have to admit my tuna one was pretty disappointing.  It had seaweed (which was just weird, and the taste was off putting) as well as lots of other good veggies.  The tuna was good and fresh, and I liked the dressing.  I really think the seaweed just killed it.    My friend who had the veg said that there was just no flavor, and needed more spice, or a stronger dressing to help the lack of protein.  You do get a $1 off if you bring back the jar.I&#39;ll go back and get the chicken pesto and try and it, as the service was really good, it was quick, kinda decently priced, and I really like the concept.

text: Late lunch.. found this place inside the Scott Plaza. <br>Surprisingly, it&#39;s almost full house at 3pm+. Ordered a cold brew single origin. It was actually quite good, even slightly better than Starbucks and far better than TCC. And the price is reasonable $5.50. <br>I ordered the all day breakfast, Scandinavian. Salmon wrapped with asparagus, on top of deep fried thin hash brown (I hope I got it right), drizzled with hollandaise dressing. Sadly, I didn&#39;t like it. Not at all. Especially I didn&#39;t know what to do with the tomatoes. The deep fried &#34;nest&#34; made of hash brown was very tough and oily, I was slightly worry about it flew out of my plate when I cut it with knife. That would be embarrassing. I didn&#39;t finish the main, I thus ordered a brownie with vanilla ice cream. Not bad! Good for sharing. Too much for one person. <br>Conclusion, a place good for coffee and dessert.

text: Ah, comfort food, comfort place.<br><br>Wild honey has been a favorite to-go place for brunch in Singapore. But because they&#39;re so famous, make sure you have reservation prior or be prepared to wait. There are 2 outlets around Orchard Road vicinity - one at Mandarin Gallery (first outlet) and they accept no reservation, so you&#39;ll have to pray hard there is no queue and the second outlet - at Scotts Square has bigger dining area capacity and accepts reservation. My favorite is always their second outlet at Scotts Square as the sitting area is more spread out and the verandah sitting area has the best natural light for you food &#34;pornographers&#34; out there.<br><br>Their menu has been the same since I visited 2.5 years ago until today. That&#39;s pretty unacceptable in Singapore since the dining scene is always fast paced and people always crave for something different from time to time. But it got me thinking, the main reasons that they&#39;re maintaining their stellar items in the menu is probably because it still sells like hotcakes? The superstar items like the Tunisian (baked eggs with chorizo in thick tomato sauce) or their perfectly poached eggs benny that we won&#39;t get bored eating or the simple-yet-so-delicious French toast that we crave. If one main isn&#39;t enough to fill you up (for my case all the time), consider getting &#34;small plates&#34; of chorizo, sautéed mushroom, bacon and the likes. They have a long list of items under this section for you to mix and match to your liking.<br><br>Looking at the lack of good cafés around Orchard road area, Wild Honey will always be my to go place if I need a good brunch spot knowing that they&#39;re always consistent with their quality and portion.

text: This is a great spot on the 3rd floor of Scott&#39;s Square.  They serve breakfast all day. Portions are large and there is plenty for vegetarians.  Prices are reasonable (by Orchard Road standards, anyways), and the staff was attentive when we were there, but this was closer to 2pm on a Monday, so not exactly peak time.<br><br>I really liked the Santa Fe eggs, though I&#39;m pretty sure they left off the cheddar cheese.  It was tortillas filled with pico de gallo, topped with fried eggs, corn and sour cream.  My boy had the Norwegian, which included perfectly poached eggs with salmon wrapped around them.<br><br>The coffee was too bitter for my taste, but that seems to be the case with everywhere here.<br><br>There&#39;s free wifi.

I suppose it&#39;s my fault for picking this place for dinner (like I&#39;ve mentioned before I love the ambience). I wanted something savory without eggs, and that was difficult to find. I ended up picking a sandwich with artichoke and cheese. I can&#39;t remember what it&#39;s called but it was average - 3 stars. The price would put it lower than that though. My friend picked the Portobello Road, again 3 stars. At the end of the day I&#39;m not sure it&#39;s quite worth the price!

text: Best breakfast/brunch restaurant there is!<br>They have all kinds of breakfast: Spanish with chorizo, the classic English breakfast which comprise of bacon eggs and baked beans, Tunisian breakfast, salmon, and so on. The portion is very filling. I went for English breakfast, which was very good. I will definitely go for Spanish next time!

Nice selection of western style breakfast food. I ordered the Santa fe which is two fried eggs sitting on top of two folded tortillas with some pico de gallo and tiny bits of avocado mixed in. (If you are from the south west region of the us or CA you are probably laughing at this type of presentation and mere the idea of eating tortillas with a fork and knife!)<br><br>My husband ordered the Norwegian which looked very nice too. Ironically, it was served with slices of avocado. (When was the last time you had avocado in Norway?)<br><br>We also had a raspberry smoothie that was essentially raspberry puree and ice blended together and served in a martini glass. Nice presentation but the flavor was fairly bland.<br><br>Topped off with hot herbal and black teas served in mini french press pots.<br><br>I&#39;d go here again, but I&#39;m curious to see other brunch spots as well.

text: Definitely on my go to list for weekend brunch. The ambiance here is quite pleasant for weekend gathering and stuff although it is rather noisy (lots of echoes but well it&#39;s quite common in dense SG isn&#39;t it?). The waiter are welcoming and are not intrusive at all despite the fact the place was crowded, which i really appreciate as I was able to catch up with my friend comfortably without feeling hurried to leave. <br><br>Onto the main highlight, food. Pricewise, it&#39;s rather pricey (bout $30/pax) but portion is quite generous. We ordered the English breakfast and the Boulevard St Michel and it was delicious. I like the fact that jn both of our dishes, they successfully poached the eggs so it has firm whites but runny yolks which I adore. I also liked that they serve our dishes at the same time and are responsive whenever we call them although it was a busy day. <br><br>Unfortunately, the coffee was a rather let down. We ordered the cold brew coffee but too bad it tasted more like your ordinary cup of joe on ice. I may be a bit of coffee snob but I believe cold brew should be slightly stronger and more aromatic. Nevertheless, my friend, whom is not a coffee drinker, enjoys it. So i guess it depends on your preferences.<br><br>All in all, i would recommend this place to people who seeks for a good brunch at central location. I would advice you to reserve your seats as it may be hard to get a seat, unless you don&#39;t mind sitting at the bar, facing the columns.

text: This place is pretty unspectacular. I had the Corsican and a friend had the Carribean for dinner.<br><br>This place hasn&#39;t changed its menu for ages. I don&#39;t feel there is anything spectacular here. My Corsican was an omelette stuffed with cheese, with some basil and bread on the side. The Carribean waffles were unimpressive, with insufficient mango and banana. I don&#39;t think the food here warrants their high prices. <br><br>Zero innovation, subpar food, high prices. Meh.

text: Hidden on an upper floor of the Scotts Square shopping centre, Wild Honey is a popular spot for brunch in Singapore. <br><br>I&#39;ve been 2x now for breakfast and both times I enjoyed my food and the casual cafe atmosphere. The menu is an eclectic mix of breakfast offerings you&#39;d find in Europe, Australia, and the Americas. <br><br>This last go I went with the Canadian option which consisted of fluffy pancakes, bacon (the Canadian kind), fruit compote and of course a heavy dousing of syrup.  Healthy, no, but sometimes a bit of a carb heavy decadence is needed to cure jet-lag.<br><br>Service is prompt/efficient though not especially warm.<br><br>As a tip, be sure to book ahead or get there early, last time I was there by 845am on a Friday morning and there was already a pre-opening queue!

text: Food is great depending on what you order, so I can&#39;t really generalize and say that everything is good. <br><br>The food looks great and appetizing though, I saw some plates being served. However, the taste of the food is mediocre. I got Spanish Hash which was a bit too oily. I also got a slice of Apple Crumble, I didn&#39;t like it as well. It was too sour for my taste and wasn&#39;t warm when I had it. <br><br>The ambiance though was average. I guess I expected too much because everyone was telling me about how pretty the place is and the food. Although style and taste is relative, you should still give this a shot.

text: This is a good place to have conversations with friends, and at the same time getting your tastebuds to work!

I think this place wins more for the ambience than the food. <br><br>Everything that we had is just okay. Not good not bad. But the place is beautiful. <br><br>For the price (average plate is about $25 for a relatively small portion), I think there are much better brunch options out there but maybe in a not as pretty setting.

text: All day breakfast mains here are priced at insanely high prices for the quality. The desserts were way better than the mains. Using the chope voucher, it was worth it, but if you&#39;re paying full price for the mains, it&#39;s definitely not worth it. Not sure if I will return for the desserts though. Service was really slow too on a Monday.

Visited Wild Honey at Scotts Square. It&#39;s actually located right next to the hair salon at Level 3. We had ordered the English breakfast, which I find the portion to be reasonable, not too big a portion but enough for a satisfying breakfast. When we got there, we happily went in and chose our table at the corner of the establishment, but was told by one of the staff that the table was reserved and that we can only sit at the long table in the middle.<br><br>The seats at the long table was uncomfortable, and the whole place feels gloomy when there&#39;s few customers but resembles a fish market when crowded. Although the breakfast was delicious and up to standard, I feel the service could be improved. That said, I will still return to Wild Honey in the near future.

Another great breakfast option in Singapore! I had the Canadian which was 3 perfectly fluffy pancakes, maple syrup, fruit compote and candied bacon. Absolutely delicious and just the right size. My fellow diners (breakfasters?) had the Flinders Street and the Corsican. Both looked excellent and were well received. <br>You definitely need to be book, we were there on a Wednesday at 10:00am and it was pretty full. I also wouldn&#39;t recommend it with small children, it&#39;s definitely more of an adult breakfast joint!<br>Didn&#39;t really enjoy the coffee though but realising that coffee is pretty personal I could make do.

text: Expensive but worth it. We had an amazing brunch ordering the Portobello Road and the European breakfast. The eggs were poached to perfection and the coffees were perfect. I was actually struggling to finish my meal given it&#39;s size. <br><br>We arrived around 11am on a Sunday and only bar seating was available. This was fine. It is near a hotel so you get many international travellers here having a leisurely breakfast. <br><br>Fantastic atmosphere and décor. Definitely on the pricey brunch end.

text: Great for big brunch excursions. Portion sizes are generous and coffee is good quality. Service is a bit slow and the wait staff do tend to forget requests (had to remind them about our pilsner and they brought the bill when we asked for milk). Overall, you&#39;re paying for the location and food, which is worth it.

text: This place was FANTASTIC!!! We came on Easter Sunday and it was a great atmosphere and it&#39;s very reasonable in price. My husband had the European and I had the coconut waffles. Both were excellent. We also ordered sausages and Canadian bacon. Again, simply amazing. We will definitely be back!!

Thoroughly enjoyed this!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "'Scandinavian'. Thoroughly enjoyed this!"}]
text: A business cum social meeting was the occassion and Wild Honey was chosen as the venue. I must say from the get-go, its popularity is warranted. <br><br>Location wise it is the most convenient to get to - minutes away from Orchard MRT station, with bus stops closeby and the Grand Hyatt taxi stand at your disposal next door - it was a breeze getting there.<br><br>Without the foresight of making a reservation, we were told it would be a half an hour wait at 11.30am on a Sunday, during which we decided to have coffee in the basement below. Their technologically advanced waiting list system was impressive. A few taps on the iPad located at their entrance, I was 7th in line and I received a call on my mobile, informing to choose if I would be there immediately or needed at 10 minute extension. A &#39;service&#39; I was particularly fond of.<br><br>Jumpin right in, we were seated outdoors (you can indicate preferences on the iPad), and it being my first time, I took about 5-7 minutes to decide what I wanted whilst we were served water and the orange juice I ordered (Which was fresh, not too sour, good job once again). I decided on the &#39;Scandinavian&#39;, which is grilled salmon fillet on potato rosti, chargrilled asparagus &amp; homemade Hollandaise sauce. It was right on the money,  approximate $25 bucks if I recall correctly. Salmon was grilled to perfection and the rosti was crispy (I am used to it being less crispy, but it clearly said &#39;crisp rosti&#39; on the menu so I guess it was done right). Do note it takes about 15-20 minutes to prepare, so if you feel like having this, get your order out right as you are seated. <br> <br>My friend ordered the &#39;Norwegian&#39; which consisted avocado, grilled asparagus spears, two perfectly poached eggs wrapped with imported Norwegian smoked salmon, homemade Hollandaise &amp; salmon pearls on a whole-wheat brioche. It looked fantastic, and he isn&#39;t too expressive about food but just gave me a thumbs up and a sigh of satisfaction when he was done.<br><br>Definitely coming back here for more. Service was great, a little too crowded for my liking but then again, Singapore is getting that way and perhaps making reservations in advance would save you unnecessary delays. Another great brunch menu checked off my list!

text: Looking for an American meal while in Singapore, Wild Honey is a must try. The food and service are excellent.
Visited a few times on an extended trip. Coffee is really good and the wait staff is friendly! Try to get a seat on the patio - it&#39;s a nice relaxing atmosphere

I believe most people are familiar with the fantastic range of all day breakfasts available at the Wild Honey. But due to the smaller set up in the Mandarin Gallery outlet, seating is limited and it is on a first come first serve on-site queue basis, no reservations allowed.<br><br>But guess what, at the Scotts Square branch, not only is the restaurant bigger, you can actually make reservations! No need to queue and you are guaranteed a table when you arrive! As this outlet is also larger, you wont have the issue of tables being too close to the next so you have more privacy when dining. Not only that, for those who love the Wild Honey Concept so much, you can actually reserve their terrace for private parties!<br><br>One thing to note though, due to the mall operating hours, this outlet closes slightly earlier than other regular restaurants not within a mall so do go early to maximise your dining experience.<br><br>Cant wait to go for my breakfast during dinner time again soon! :)

Located in an upscale mall, bright cheery decor.  Filled with &#34;teenagers and twenty somethings&#34;, so noisy. It was an &#34;ok&#34; place to grab a western style lunch. Service was pleasant, albeit slow. Had to hunt down my server more than once. Ordered a 250gm Australian sliced steak platter with a side salad and carrot juice. Very good, but very $$$$. Almost 60SPD! Lots of breakfast/brunch choices served all day.
I ordered a latte.  You would think for $7 they would know not to boil the milk.  Starbucks do better coffee and that&#39;s saying something

On a trip with a group of friends all from the US, we specifically sought out Wild Honey while in Singapore. It was completely worth it. A diverse, eclectic breakfast &amp; brunch menu with specialty dishes with US &amp; Asian<br>Flavor. It looks amazing as well. Be prepared to wait though. <br><br>Next time I&#39;m in Singapore, I will be first in line!

text: Wild Honey has the best Eggs Benedict in Singapore. Two perfectly poached eggs, sauteed mushrooms and prosciutto on toasted homemade brioche and hollandaise sauce. This has to be my favorite dish of all time. I always end up ordering this even though i always say i wanna try something new. Anyway, i think that the Mandarin Gallery branch does it better? Somehow the bread is over toasted and was too crunchy. Pretty dry. :(<br><br>The Wild Mocha Dolce is my poison. This is intensely sweet but packs in some serious caffeine. I always get super high after drinking this. Friends know not to feed me with too much coffee/tea because i&#39;d be bouncing off the walls. <br><br>I also love the scones at WH. For tea, i like to have their cranberry scone with a cuppa of hot mocha dolce. This has to be one of the better scones in town. I&#39;d put it in the same category as Foster&#39;s (another of my favorite). The exterior is crispy and the middle is dense and moist. I&#39;ll gently coat it with a thin layer of butter and sprinkle sea salt flakes on it- my very own version of salted butter (because WH doesn&#39;t provide salted ones). Yummy! And their fresh compote of berries to go with it. Perfecto.<br><br>I would be hanging out at the SS branch more often for the following reasons<br>1. Wider desserts selection<br>According to the manager, the kitchen at SS is 3 times bigger than that at MG. Therefore, more space to make pastries! I tried the sour cherry strudel when i was there recently (not fantastic) and they also have more tea cakes and stuff. :) I&#39;ll be sure to try more desserts soon.<br><br>2. More breathing space! I always felt that the MG store was really claustrophobic! In fact, the entire MG feels that way. I feel like i can easily touch the ceiling (ok i exaggerate). Also, because of the small size of the place, i do feel like i can&#39;t stay on for too long even though i just wanna chill out with my book sometimes. Scotts is more airy and there&#39;s more natural light hence the relaxed ambience. <br><br>So if you haven&#39;t tried WH (quite impossible IMO), do head on down. All day breakfast means that you never have to wake up early! As for me, ADB FTW!

text: The food here is good, but I don&#39;t think it&#39;s worth the prices they serve them at. Although the atmosphere and the service was really great. It&#39;s a nice &#34;I feel fancy today&#34; kind of a place... But definitely not coming back here anytime soon. <br><br>Still on the hunt for a regular brunch spot. Mainly breakfast and brunch place that serves brunch cocktails. Decent food and large servings but extremely pricey.

The food was fresh and the portions were good.  If you&#39;re not super hungry, you can split an entree to save on the high costs.  My friend and I got two coffees, some bread and split a breakfast entree and it was about 25 SPD each - ouch!  It&#39;s a good spot to get a Western breakfast and it&#39;s cute inside.  This is definitely a family establishment, but it&#39;s a good place to start your day.  Also, they didn&#39;t bat an eye when we told them we were splitting an entree, in fact, they split it onto two plates.

text: Meal ordered: Duck confit hash with eggs and potatoes<br><br>Pros: 1) There was a wait when I arrived on a Saturday morning, and I received a text message when they were ready to seat me. If you don&#39;t mind sitting at the bar, you&#39;ll be seated quickly. 2) I tried the duck confit hash meal since the chef was testing it out and the waitress recommended it. It was excellent. I hope they put it permanently on their menu. 3) Their customer service was excellent.<br><br>Cons: 1) It was on the pricey side, but it was an excellent meal so that&#39;s not really a con. 2) It might be difficult to get seated right away if you are in a large group. <br><br>Summary: Whenever I am back in Singapore, I will visit this restaurant again.

text: I am absolutely smitten with Wild Honey!!!<br><br>PROS:<br>-Location - quite rare to find nice brunch places in town nowadays <br>-Great service, the waiters were very attentive<br>-A lovely ambience, posh yet cosy (Saw Rebecca Lim dining there!)<br>-Great comfort food! I&#39;ve had the English Breakfast, Spanish Hash, Norwegian Breakfast, Monte Cubano Sandwich and their brownies, and I LOVE all of them!<br>-Wide choice of foods<br>-There&#39;s an iPad at the counter where they have pictures of all their dishes, which is useful when deciding what to order whilst waiting in the queue<br><br>CONS:<br>-Long queues, all members of your group must be present before they are willing to seat you<br>-Pretty expensive eg. (~22 dollars for sandwiches), but still worth it, I wholeheartedly believe<br>-Certain dishes have quite small portions when compared with others of the same price range on the menu (eg. the Norwegian breakfast is just veggies + two slices of brioche topped with eggs wrapped in salmon, kind of like an eggs benny --- I would rather pay a little more for the HUGE english breakfast)

text: Tried the Spanish Hash for brunch today - pretty good. I love poached eggs and the chorizo in the hash still had a nice snap to the skin. Definitely recommended! The patio seating was very laid back and comfy. I really enjoyed the atmosphere at Wild Honey. Downside: sour bitter tasting expresso, yuck! Bloody Mary was thin and there was no bite to it (had the spiciness but no horse radish). Still searching for the perfect Bloody Mary in Singapore...

My wife and I come from New York. The food at Wild Honey was fantastic. My wife had their Boulevard St. Michel and I had the European. My first choice was Norwegian, but they were &#34;out of it&#34;!  Their Mello Mellon fresh juice was great.  <br><br>The ambiance is good. The service was satisfactory. They can be a bit more friendly and attentive. After we were seated, no one came along to greet us until I managed to get a waiter&#39;s attention.<br><br>Prices are high - more than it should be. But for the high quality of the food, I don&#39;t mind it. I do mind it for unfriendly and unattentive service. For the price they are charging, they should add a smile!

text: Good eggs Benedict.

brunch as good as the states! lord, let me tell you, me and brunch have a long, intimate history together and our relationship has been a little bit on the rocks since coming to singapore. don&#39;t get me wrong, there&#39;s brunch places here but a truly good brunch consists of eggs, eggs, meat, carb and eggs and a very good bloody mary. wild honey does not disappoint!<br><br>tunisian - delicious! a lot of spice, great portion and just love the brioche that comes with it. i would come back for this dish alone.<br><br>breakfast sandwich - huge! delicious ciabatta placed on top of a mountain of eggs and meat. i got this with a side of pork sausage, all good. <br><br>the teas here are great too and the decor is beautiful. officially my new go-to brunch joint.

text: Sad to say, Wild Honey was an over-hyped and over rated restaurant for me. A couple of old friends suggested dinner there to try out their &#39;must-try&#39; all day brunches, and it was on the list of &#39;trendy cafes in Singapore&#39; that we&#39;ve heard so much about. We weren&#39;t allowed to make reservations, and despite arriving super early after rushing down from work, I couldn&#39;t get seated to ensure 4 of my other friends had seats either, which was quite disappointing service. So there I was waiting alone outside while the restaurant slowly filled up, to the point where by the time all my friends arrived, we had to be seated at a table for 4, with an additional chair squeezed in. <br><br>The food was greatly talked about, so we went all out and got a banana toffee milkshake that came served in a colour and shape that was honestly that of doo-doo. It tasted cloying and overly artificial, and the drink slowly congealed into a paste towards the end of the meal - not tasty at all! <br><br>We ordered several different pancakes from their all day brunch menu that they were famous for, and the top choice was the Norwegian pancakes, that came with smoked salmon on scone like breads. This was average at best, with the accompanying sauce a bit too sour for my taste since it just made the eggs taste sour and the salmon taste bad. 2 stars at most for just having a good ambience in the restaurant.

text: Wild Honey @ Mandarin Gallery<br><br>Wild Honey dared to be different by serving all day breakfasts - even for dinner.  Totally against the grain but it works! With queues even at dinner time, expect to wait 15-30 mins for a table. <br><br>Service is mediocre, the staff aren&#39;t exceptionally cheerful (or efficient) for that matter, but you&#39;re really here for the atmosphere - plush cosy chairs in little corners, dim lights and a strong cinnamon-y sweet scent. <br><br>Love how the dishes are named after different cities / areas - one of my favourites is the &#39;Belgian&#39;, fluffly waffles with grilled mango and blueberries.  An instant hit for my sweet tooth - beware though, it IS sweet and may not go down well as a main for dinner.  Perhaps better to share as a desert :)

This is one of my favourite brunch places for a few reasons: its accessible(for me) smack in town, the service and food quality is consistent, wide range of  menu, cosy ambience, delicious smoothies. The downside is the price (well its in Orchard road, what do you expect), some dishes aren&#39;t too fantastic (e.g. Mexican), some of the portions are too small for my liking in relation to the price. Also you can&#39;t make a reservation for the mandarin gallery branch, although this is not a problem for the Scott&#39;s branch.<br><br>In conclusion: not perfect but always a reliable place to go for brunch. I&#39;m still waiting for the seats out on the patio!

text: I went to Wild Honey with my SO for a special occasion brunch. It is AMAZING! I got the eggs with smoked fish. They had gluten free bread that was actually so good that I was afraid it wasn&#39;t actually gluten free. The hot chocolate was ridiculous with the housemade marshmellow. WH also had the only Bloody Mary that I&#39;ve had in Singapore so far that was actually good. Overall, I wish my stomach could have fit more in it cause it was all so delicious. My only complaint is it was very pricey. It&#39;s definitely not something we could do regularly as it was over $100 for the two of us.

text: We have been coming to Wild Honey since this branch opened and are pretty much regulars on the patio at opening on Sundays.  It helps that one of our friends has a baby but the rest of us are just naturally early risers.  <br>I&#39;ve tried most of the menu and would say my ideal meal is the European with a side of Brazilian bread and a Queen Bee.  The dishes are all named after a geographic location but are pretty imaginative from there. The European is their take on eggs Benedict: seriously thick brioche with parma ham and poached eggs.  The brazilian bread is this cheesy little roll thing, amazing. And the queen bee is a honey grapefruit mocktail.  Yum.<br>Other highlights of the menu are the Tunisian and the English.  Enjoy breakfast!

A beautiful breakfast parlor in the heart of Orchard road has been the talk of the town since its opening. The beeline at its 1st outlet; Mandarin Gallery, has become a common sight. Due to the limited seats, many find it frustrating to wait. The restaurant did excite me but not the queue. I wouldn&#39;t brave myself to Wild Honey until its 2nd outlet at Scott&#39;s Square becomes operational; there - I have gotten my most important meal of the day fixed without having to wait, any time of the day.    <br><br>Serving an array of breakfast dishes; distinguished by country that ranges from English, European, Belgian, Canadian,Tunisian to Japanese et cetra. While many raved about European - eggs Benedict; I heart English instead.<br><br>The portion has been massive; it can feed 2 ladies with small appetite. Routinely, I would portion the plate unless I declared a NO dessert and could leave the place without any. What have been so enjoyable in the plate are those juicy pork meat cased in its crispy sausage skin. They are perfectly grilled without drying out and loosing their flavour. The toasted brioche is more provocative - rich in taste with a strong buttery note. Slightly fluffy yet crumbly in some parts. While the briny bacons compliment well with the bread, the scrambled eggs add moist and even-out the saltiness in the former. <br><br>When waffles becomes unavailable, I will make good with a stack of pancake - Canadian. These thick fermented round flapjacks are doubled in size; 3s are somewhat excessive - sharing is more ideal. I am particularly fond of its texture - very light yet with some volume. They are relatively moist but not dampish. For a savory note, nibble on the bacons along with the cake. Otherwise, top it up either with maple syrup or homemade jam - the morning becomes more angelic.

text: Tried this breakfast joint recently as it rated highly on Yelp. text: Most sets cost around $20. The menu looks interesting with breakfast inspired by all parts of the world. I had the Tunisian breakfast set served in a pan - I loved the seasoning used, and how it looked. You pay at the counter before getting your set. Prepare for a long wait though, as this place is always crowded. More importantly, i liked the cosy cafe setting with nice sofa chairs. What I disliked is the queue!

text: My wife and I had breakfast here on a Monday morning, and loved it. The service, food and atmosphere were all great. The food is quite expensive, but for a schmancy breakfast spot in downtown Singapore, that&#39;s to be expected. One thing I really liked was that both of our entrees came out together. In Singapore it is very common for different people at the same table to be served minutes apart, which is a major faux pas in decent restaurants all over the world. My Bloody Mary could have been spicier and had another splash of vodka, but it was still good, and a great compliment to my eggs bennie and fruit.

Chops for ambience and location but food is rather overpriced for the quality. Had the Santa Fe and the Brittany, both of which were served at room temperature. Would have been nice for the food to have been served warmed. In any case, I suspect we&#39;re paying for the rent here. Could be better...

text: How can breakfasts be so expensive? Singaporeans must really love their breakfasts to pay these prices. <br><br>I skipped the breakfast items (so cannot comment on them, and therefore, I suppose I shouldn&#39;t judge the pricing, as the breakfast items could be really crazy good) and ordered a &#34;chicken salad chop chop&#34; or something with an equally silly name. Possibly &#34;chop chop chicken salad&#34;??<br><br>Anyway, the salad is NOT like a salad at all. Firstly, there were no greens. Ok, fine, there was some lettuce in the salad. But the lettuce was coated in some brown coloured seasoning (curry powder? no idea). In fact, the entire bowl of &#34;salad&#34; was one single colour - brown! Definitely not appetizing and not the fresh, healthy bowl of salad I was expecting. However, having said that, the salad tasted fine and I grew to like the crunchy crackers in the salad. So much for trying to have a healthy meal. <br><br>In a bid to keep up with my attempt to have a healthy meal, I ordered the mixed beetroot juice - this was expensive, but not too bad, quite tasty and was freshly squeezed, of course.<br><br>Service was slow. Our glasses of water were not topped up. <br><br>I&#39;m not used to paying such sky high prices for breakfast food and won&#39;t be coming back. It&#39;s not like the food I had was that great, or the service, that good. In fact, everything was pretty average to me, down to the ambience. Only advantage I suppose would be the location, although to me, I&#39;d very much prefer a relaxing, quieter cafe to have my breakfast at.

text: Expensive......<br>Be prepared to pay S$40 a head easy... for breakfast. Are you kidding me?<br>Went there with my gf whose friend is a fan, she made reservations.<br>Even though we had reservations we still had to wait about 10min.<br>They made the reservations process so troublesome but still had to queu up, really? what was the point?<br>Decor is nice, however crowded.<br>Just be prepared to have a packed restaurant and many many kids, so if you are looking for relaxing look elsewhere.<br>Service was so so. Still had to chase down the server for salt, although pepper was readily available on the table. text: Had a really awful experience at Wild Honey where we waited over an hour for our food. When we finally asked about our order, we realized that it never actually went into their system, with the only explanation being a breakdown in their system. When we asked to speak to the manager, the only thing he said was that it must have been a bad day and didn&#39;t try to offer anything else to compensate us. When my order finally came, it was incorrect (I asked for sauce on the side and it was piled on top of my order). I used to frequent Wild Honey at Scotts Square, but given this unacceptable experience which is the worst I&#39;ve had in Singapore, I highly recommend avoiding this place!!

Holiday weekend and we walked to Wild Honey to get a change of pace from The Line at Shangri La. The hostess stand had an iPad where we checked in digitally and received texts regarding the status of our table. The wait time was estimated at 45-60 minutes and we waited only 40 minutes. We walked around the mall and did some shopping to pass the time more quickly, which was a nice change of pace to lingering around the entrance. We received a call when our table was ready and were greeted by a friendly gentleman apologizing for how crazy it was, but we weren&#39;t concerned at all because it was a holiday weekend. We were seated at the round counter and quickly greeted and put in drink orders - iced coffee. The menu had a lot of variety and offered meals from many regions around the world. I chose the Tunisian, which was chorizo and eggs in a tomato based sauce, with two hearty pieces of toast and a cucumber and tomato salad. It was incredibly tasty but not very filling since my Paleo lifestyle doesn&#39;t allow me to consume grains. My hubby tried the special - duck confit potato hash topped with poached eggs and hollandaise. It was also very good. We topped off our meals with the berries, but passed on the yogurt. The service was good. The menu is a little limited if you&#39;re paleo, but it&#39;s not too hard to make it work. The atmosphere was cozy and inviting, and I was a fan of the music selection, which would fit into the &#34;coffee house&#34; genre. Overall, we were very pleased and will be back.

text: We normally love this place, but today the three of us left very disappointed and may not go back. We had an 11 am reservation for 3. Two of us arrived 20 minutes early and asked if the table was free for us to go ahead a sit down. We were shown to our table and reminded about the 90 min reservation. We thought that started from our 11:00 reservation time, so no problem. We each ordered a drink, our friend arrived we ordered a second drink and our food. Our second drinks did not come. They came to take our food order and we asked about the drinks. They hadn&#39;t made them yet. The food was good as always. At 12:10 they brought the check and asked us to leave for the next reservation who were waiting outside. We said that we had the table until 12:30. She told us that since we came early, the 90 minutes started when we sat down. We did not argue and left. A disappointing experience.

Wild Honey at Scotts Square is a vast improvement on its sister outlet at Mandarin Gallery. For starters, there&#39;s a lot more space and a wider variety on its menu, and we can finally make reservations online instead of having to wake up at the crack of dawn on a weekend to queue for a table.<br><br>Food : The best eggs Benedict I&#39;ve had in Singapore. We shared the Tunisian, the Scandinavian, the European, the English, the Australian and I Love New York amongst us so that we could all get a taste of the different breakfast sets. The coffees were well made and a couple of us tried this Banoffee drink which was mad yummy! Being a ravenous lot, we also shared a bread basket while waiting for our breakfast sets to arrive. We particularly liked the croissant, evident in the fact we almost came to blows over the sole croissant in the basket. The homemade jams and honey too, were the perfect complement to the bread basket. If we hadn&#39;t wanted to save some stomach space for our breakfast sets, we would have ordered one more! The most difficult decision you will face at Wild Honey is deciding which breakfast set to order, but whichever you decide, rest assured they are all equally tasty in their own indigenous way.<br><br>Ambience : Love the mosaic tiles on the floor and the airy feel of the restaurant. The dark wood works well with the colorful furniture and drapes. Overall, the atmosphere is bustling yet comfortable, and is a great place to people watch on weekends. We like!<br><br>Service : Can be a bit sketchy if one is sitting outside on the verandah. It is practically impossible to get service after the server takes our initial order, and the wait staff inside the restaurant are too busy to pay us any attention. If you can get their attention however, they are perfectly pleasant.<br><br>Perfect if they can improve service standards. Prices are a bit steep for brunch but at least the large portions compensate somewhat. Reservations for weekend brunch at prime time absolutely necessary at least a week in advance.

text: Quiet hospitality, tasty Peranakan food. During the 16th and 17th century, Chinese young men went to Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia to find their fortune. They intermarried with non-Muslim women, birthing the Peranakan culture which has its own unique cuisine. One the of most unique ingredients they use in this food is the buah keluak or Pangium Edule seed. It is actually a poisonous seed that needs to be buried after harvesting to leach the toxins. However, the delicious, nutty, slightly bitter savory and soft flesh inside when cooked in a rich gravy is amazing. Chili Padi does a nice job picking, choosing good sized seeds that are not to old.<br><br>The Ngoh Hiang or mined pork wrapped and deep fried in tofu skin also has a nice texture and is served with a slightly sweet sauce. <br><br>Order the Bakwang Kepiting, a soup with meatballs. The broth is delicate and the meatballs, pretty good. I enjoyed eating it with their mild sambal belacan, chili sauce made with fermented shrimp and red chilies. Yum!<br><br>The Chap Chye, braised mixed vegetables and Egg Foo Yong were okay, but not memorable.<br><br>Desserts we tried included the Chendol and the Sago Pudding. Both were okay. If you have a sweet tooth, ask for extra Gula Melaka or palm sugar in syrup form.<br><br>I enjoyed my experience at Chili Padi.

What happened to the Ayam Buah Keluak???<br><br>The nut meat which was velvety and nutty tasted like they were soaked in sugar water! Robbing me of the bitter, pungent, dark chocolate tang like experience. <br><br>The prices are exorbitant,  and the portions small. So for the kitchen to screw up the headliner of the meal was deeply disappointing. <br><br>I sulked away and pacified my frustration the next morning with a delightful Rawon from Bedok South.

text: For a $20 per person lunch buffet, there was a laksa station, kueh counter, kueh pie tee station and cooked food with dishes like rendang and pork belly buns. The quality of the food here is not very good, and I wouldn&#39;t come here specially for a buffet or lunch. Nothing was bad or very good, but service was prompt and it can accommodate about 100 people, which was why we had a corporate lunch here. <br><br>You best call for a cab if you didn&#39;t drive. There aren&#39;t many taxis around this part of NUS!

text: will not bother to go if not for my friend who wanted to try nonya food.  The front server was so rude to us and practically said the price loud to us several times while rolling her eyes. As my friend was visiting, I was just going to leave it. Worst part was when I was taking food at the buffet line, another server push me aside to grab the dish plate. As I was talking to my friend about it, the same server came by with her cart and knocked into my chair without apologising. Food was way too salty and not authentic as described. Don&#39;t waste money and time, go somewhere else. <br>PS: their laksa fish cake and chendol coconut milk turned bad, it was sour and yet they still served it. there wasn&#39;t many people when we went there and I know the reason.

Yelp has no classification for the food of the culture of Peranakan.  What is it?  It&#39;s a bit of south east asia.  It&#39;s a bit Malay.  It&#39;s a bit Chinese.  It&#39;s totally Singapore.  And here, it&#39;s in buffet form.  What I liked about this buffet is it&#39;s DIY (Do it yourself).  Many of the dishes are there in their elements and you put it together.  Laksa, MeeSaim, BBQ meat buns.  All off it there to adjust to your spice and taste level and it&#39;s a bit fresher than sitting out in a normal buffet line.  Course you can&#39;t complain to the chef if you don&#39;t like it because you kinda made it.  What I thought was fun was experimenting and making my own Peranakan fusions (like putting the stewed beef inside the steamed buns).  Fun indeed.

text: Shen &amp; Co<br>Barbecue may not be the road to world peace, but it&#39;s a start. Here&#39;s my order of Barbeque Pork loin ribs with drizzled in their house special sauce with garlic butter herb rice and salad. Feels like there isn&#39;t much meat but the sauce is...

text: I loved this Starbucks! Definitely one of my favorite Starbucks locations. They have more delicious choices in food and drinks than we have here in the US. It&#39;s poshly decorated and with lots of magazines to read while waiting for the rest to be exhausted from Universal Studios&#39; amusements. (Lol). The service was on point. <br><br>It was packed, but I would&#39;ve expected it to be so. <br>They have clover machine but all I really wanted at the time was a cooling concoction consisting of green tea (frap). At that time, the Singaporean dollar was 23%-25% higher , thus the higher price here. With their fancy mugs and plates combined with a really nice ambiance, it was undoubtedly a par up the Starbucks I&#39;m used to here in US.

Food court areas in Sentosa resorts.  This is a nice and cooler location near the universal studios and sea aquarium.  They got my order wrong but it&#39;s ok, it&#39;s cool inside and has decent WiFi.  Good place to chill and catch your breath.

text: How many Starbucks are there on Sentosa Island itself? So far I could only find 3 -- RWS, USS and the one at Imbiah. Proud to say that I&#39;ve visited all three. But if I were to choose, it&#39;s this one. <br><br>It has a nice pretty entrance and although the place is smaller than the nearby one at Universal Studios, I feel that it&#39;s much calmer here.<br><br>Like what the previous Yelper mentioned in her review, yes. This is one of the exclusive Starbucks in Singapore which houses the Clover Machine.<br><br>I get instantly impressed when a Starbucks staff asked for the customer&#39;s name to be written on the cups. It shows their organisational skills. I&#39;ve been to some with messy confused service due to the crowd and... failing to write the names. Writing names would easily evade such things from happening. <br><br>Even then, when I wanted to retrieve a straw for my frappucino, I realised the straw container was empty. But just a few moments later, I saw it filled. &#34;When did that happen?&#34;<br><br>So yes, hands down. RWS&#39; Starbucks gets a thumbs up from me for good service.

Clover machine!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Clover machine!'}]
text: The only Clover machine in Singapore is located here.<br><br>This is no ordinary Starbucks, for it houses a Clover machine, a USD $11k machine that vacuum brews the coffee. What results is a pretty consistent and nicely extracted coffee that has the connoisseurs waxing lyrical. In 2008, Starbucks bought the company, which sold fewer than 250 machines around the world. All future Clovers appear exclusively in specially selected Starbucks - the reason for the machine&#39;s cult status.<br><br>This store also sells Starbucks Reserve Coffee, higher quality single origin beans that go by the pound. Sumatra, Ethiopia, Zambia, Kona, you can find them here. Do yourself a favour and pick one of the single origin beans and have the barista make you a coffee from the Clover machine.<br><br>Is it worth the price of Sentosa admission to get in here? I don&#39;t know. With the independent coffee shop competition on the mainland, you need a larger excuse than simply coffee to make it out across the water...<br><br>Edit: I&#39;m hearing there may be another Clover machine hiding out there in Singapore. Message me if you spot it.

Tried this after reading Jackay&#39;s review! Went on a Friday night.<br><br>The selection for toppings is endless. from kimchi to century eggs and there are safe selections too. Interestingly, they serve waffles, soups and other desserts too.<br><br>I had a wrap+chicken+5 toppings and my partner had a single salad consisting of 5 toppings. It cost under $16 and was very fulfiling. This is easily one of the most value for money salad places in Singapore, besides cold storage. Others are incredibly overpriced!<br><br>The staff recommended me to take an extra meat but I declined so it can make me &#39;full&#39; as I chose mainly light ingredients. <br><br> A constant stream of customers arrived, most likely Kaplan students. <br><br>Happy Tummy is new to market, and I saw on their Fb that they are opening a new outlet at Yishun! Lucky Yishunittes.<br>.Definitely coming back to try!

text: Happy Tummy, Happy Yummy! This is my all-time favourite salad bar. I probably go there twice a week. Fresh ingredients, friendly peeps and so much cheaper than Salad Stop!<br><br>A Single, gets you a base of romaine and 5 toppings for $6.80. A Double (which supposedly feeds 2 peeps, but I eat it all by myself. Moo!) gets you a generous base of romaine and 8 toppings, all for $10. They also give unlimited herbs and condiments, like basil, oregeno, parsley, fried shallots, garlic and sesame seeds. I usually get the Roasted Sesame or Miso Sesame dressing. Premium items, like spinach, roast chicken or freshly grilled salmon (made in house), cost anything from $1 to $2.50 more each. Even then, my Doubles never cost more than $13. If I went to Salad Stop, I&#39;d get half the amount for the same price. And for half the smiles too. (Alright, I&#39;ll stop knocking Salad Stop!) They also serve wraps, soups, ice-cream waffles, cold pressed juices, coffee/tea and baked goods like macaroons, muffins, tarts. But I&#39;m usually there to eat &#34;clean&#34;, so I just take in the smells. <br><br>There is a seating area for about 15-20, but it looks a little crammed, so I usually take out. Probably not good for big groups. If you&#39;re a student/staff from SMU, Kaplan, NAFA or Lasalle, you get one free additional topping, and if you are from RSM International, the Ascott Limited or Citadines, you get a special discount. They also have a loyalty card. 4 orders gets you a free topping, 8 gets you a free premium, and 13 gets you a free Single salad. <br><br>I LOVE HAPPY TUMMY!

Not the highest quality ingredients, but a welcome breath of fresh air in a mall with very few cheap decent options. <br><br>I got stuck in Wilkie by the rain. It was lunchtime so I thought why not. <br><br>The position of the restaurant is quite nice, having the seating in a corner means a spacious view including on the street (seeing the sky in a mall! who&#39;d have thought), although the tables are very close together and you will bump into people. <br><br>The burger patty definitely came from the freezer as did the sliced Kraft cheese on top. Salad was alright, although a few of the grapes were very soft. The sesame dressing was great, the chef has taste. The lemonade was enjoyable and did not have the cleaning fluid feel of the artificial stuff you find in food courts.  I just want to point out this is not a hipster salad bar with specially imported ingredients, just Cold Storage/Fairprice stuff thrown together at an attractive price, not a destination, but a good place to hang out if you already live here. Definitely a good option for a traditional breakfast, and I guess I should try the salads people are raving about. <br><br>All in all, but a welcome addition to Wilkie for those of us who just want a simple healthy lunch without paying $20 at any of the mediocre &#34;food concepts&#34; nearby. Together with the arrival of Hao Wei Lai opposite, things are looking up in the not-hipster, not-hawker segment for the neighbourhood.

text: It&#39;s hard to review a franchise that is so remarkable in it&#39;s consistency, but I thought it was worth noting that another location opened up in the heartland. In addition to everything you expect when you walk into a Starbucks, this shop has a better than average pastry case. (See photo.) It seemed a little chaotic despite not being very busy. After being open for only 2 weeks they still have to refine their production a bit. That being said, the coffee is fresh and, of course, just the same standard you get at all Starbucks locations.

text: Chocolate and cheese buffet on top of MBS!<br><br>Skip dinner and come hungry. Skip lunch that day too if you can. Or go for a long swim before and after the meal. Or in my case, stuff yourself as much as you can while promising that you will start a juice cleanse the following day. <br><br>Back to the experience, we came on a weekday without a reservation but didn&#39;t have any problem getting a table. You have to first reserve with the concierge on the lobby level, who will talk to the reception at Rise restaurant for some reasons. They will then give you a card that allows you to enter the pool area because this is located right in the middle Tower 2.<br><br>The most wonderful thing about this is of course the view. You can choose to sit inside the adorably decorated restaurant or outside with a view of the harbour and ocean. It was a little dark for us sitting outside but if you reserve you could ask for a table with better lighting.<br><br>Now on to the food, I was not blown away by one particular thing but generally the buffet was not too bad. There were around 10+ types of cheeses (mostly French I believe) and countless chocolaty desserts. I wonder if cheese is a new addition because none of the previous reviews mentioned it. Coffee or tea is complimentary but they also have a wine menu. <br><br>Overall a must try experience especially if you have a sweet tooth :)

text: Given that each person has to pay about $90 for entry to MBS&#39;s famous Chocolate Bar on the 55th floor, I would have expected a much larger more extravagant selection of chocolates and cheeses.<br><br>I&#39;m most definitely not a platinum member of a club or a high-roller who flies first class (economy all the way!), but shelling out so much for a buffet...and for chocolates and cheese?! I&#39;d expect a much more extensive selection! I can get a much better meal in Vegas at Wicked Spoon (not just a chocolate selection) for $100 per person, and I&#39;d hands down pay that much again for their beautifully crafted and variety of delectables! <br><br>We were greeted warmly by the hostess, who I think deserves all of the stars from this review. She did not make us two twenty-somethings seem out of place or overlooked, and that&#39;s almost a yes in the industry. We had an average server who was there to refill our hot coffee and teas (included! which is a nice touch) when needed. Granted, we began our feast around 9PM, but our service wasn&#39;t extraordinary and neither were the selections.<br><br>I&#39;d suggest more chocolate choices for non-nut eaters, although I do appreciate all of the allergens and gluten signs for those with restrictive eating plans. The cheeses were a letdown too. Only three hard cheeses, and a small selection of brie, blue, and soft? I&#39;d expect so much more from MBS but also from an expensive buffet. I wouldn&#39;t recommend coming here if you&#39;re really a chocolate maniac like we were, but also if you&#39;ve been to places like Vegas or the States for buffets, I&#39;d pass this place. It&#39;s a beautiful and sexy venue with great potential, but it was a wilted experience.
