text: Nestled by the millennium pool on the roof of Marina Bay Sands is Chocolate Bar, an all-you-can-eat dessert bar. Yes, you heard me right -- all-you-can-eat.  I totally understand that I&#39;m playing the tourist when I come here. But you know what, I do it anyway. I think it would also be a great place to bring out-of-town guests. <br><br>They open at 8pm, making it sound like a dessert place, but don&#39;t be fooled. Here&#39;s some advice. Don&#39;t eat dinner! Come hungry so you can try all the different cakes, cookies, fondue, tarts, ice cream, hot chocolate and more that they have to offer. Trust me, if you eat anything before you come, you&#39;re just not going to make it through. <br><br>The dessert here is very good. I&#39;m not going to say that it&#39;s amazing or mind-blowing, because it&#39;s not. But it&#39;s very good. There is a passionfruit and chocolate cake there that I&#39;m crazy about though. Not everything is pure chocolate. Everything does has something chocolate in it though, even if it&#39;s just garnish. So there are many fruity things, light things, and very different things. This actually makes it nice because, realistically, how much chocolate could you really eat? There are so many choices of dessert, good luck trying everything. Don&#39;t miss the fondue with the homemade marshmallows. <br><br>Coffee and hot chocolate is included and you can pay for cocktails. <br><br>Unfortunately, there are no tables in this place that has a view off the front of the hotel. There is outdoor seating, but it faces the back, and so not over the city, Marina Bay and the pool. But, being able to get up to the pool is pretty great. And you should definitely walk around up there before or after your sugar overdose. Don&#39;t tell the staff at the restaurant that though, because they will tell you that you have to straight back down, and that walking around is not allowed -- just do it, and no one will bother you.

First of all, the view is fantastic. Perfect for any day of the time. <br><br>The chocolate and cheese buffet are also superb. Great variety and selection. I cannot find anything wrong with the spread.<br><br>But I would like to point out the WORST SERVICE ever for a great establishment. The waitresses assigned to my section were not attentive, not service oriented and rude.<br>They are always not available to be called for beverage orders. It&#39;s amazing difficult to call them to your table. When they do come to your table, they don&#39;t seems to be interested in their services. They don&#39;t ask what kind or coffee/tea you wanted. Hey, at least ask if u want a latte or black or etc. In addition, they don&#39;t automatically clear your plates and cups. If they don&#39;t clear those used utensils, who will?!? What a f-Ing morons. If these waitresses don&#39;t like what they do, then quit! I don&#39;t have to get serviced by low class waitresses. <br><br>Definitely spoiled my night. <br><br>However, I have to single out our hostess, she is very polite and professional. She greeted us well and brought us to our table promptly. That&#39;s the service I actually expected. <br><br>Management should fire most of the waitresses that work tonight, Nov 7, 2015. We are the first seating guest at 8pm.

text: This is one of my most favorite places in Singapore. The view from the restaurant is stunning! Being a chocolate addict, I went to have not my dessert, but dinner. The buffet has a wide spread of desserts starting from banana steamed chocolate, milk chocolate macaroons and lime tarts to orange mousse, brownies and fudge. I ate like my stomach was a bottomless pit. My friends who are not such a big fan of chocolate had a tough time though. My adorable friends were the ones who introduced this place to me and I love them for that!

When you&#39;re craving for some American style Chinese comfort food and a flight to Australia for the next best thing is not in the cards, get your fix at Chop Suey, but prepare to pay up what the food you remember from back home in the US.<br><br>High end service, well executed food and prices to match.<br><br>Our favorite dish was the Crispy Orange Beef featuring tender strips of beef fried nicely and coated with orange flavored glaze.<br><br>The Wok Breath Rice Noodle was nice as well as the sticky crunchy baby squid.<br><br>Cocktails were tasty with appealing Asian accents, especially the Hot Lychee Margarita.<br><br>PARTING THOUGHT: sooner or later we&#39;ll save enough room to finally try the desserts!

text: I attended the July UYE at Chop Suey Cafe today at 38 Martin Road and meet yelppers like lawrence, peter &amp; gloria from USA as well as the local yelppers like Nik, Sonya, Ping etc<br><br>Thanks Sonya for arranging this brunch. The food is fantastic and great ambience ... oh my it&#39;s so relaxing. I had a great time today brunch-ing with all the lovely people.<br><br>This cafe serve American Chinese cuisine, i ordered a smoke duck with herb omelette and the portion serve is big and it&#39;s really tasty. I expect the smoke duck to be placed on top the omelette but it caught my surprise. The smoke duck is wrap within the omelette and it&#39;s placed above the toast with alittle veg &amp; marmalade garnish on top of it and the sides dish is 2 roasted tomatoes and mushroom.<br><br>Oh my ..... I never regret ordering this ..... It&#39;s simply delicious and I&#39;m really full.  BLURP! <br><br>I envy those people who stay around here .... They have nice cafe around the vicinity and you people are so lucky.<br><br>Tumbs up ...... I will recommend my friends to visit ......

Chopsuey is an Asian-American fusion restaurant that also serve brunch. They have an elaborate menu so everyone can have their pick. I got their duck omelet from their brunch menu and it was a generous amount with juicy sides - tomato and mushroom infused with delicious herby sauce. The duck was very well cooked and flavorful. The bread that came with the omelet was the downside of the meal - it was dry and did not serve a purpose at all. In fact, it absorbed a large portion of the moisture from the omelet. <br><br>I also got to try their French bean in Szechuan sauce - this is like your regular si ji dou - except cooked with lots of flavor. Highly recommended to fulfill your vege of the day! <br><br>Besides their food, their service was very friendly and food served in a timely manner. I would give this place a visit again, maybe to try their main dishes next time.
WE HAD AN AWESOME TIME.<br>good food, nice people, and a beautiful space - what else could you ask for!

We&#39;re having an old friends get together at this restaurant. The food to say the least is &#34;unusual&#34; in that it&#39;s a fusion of Chinese and western. Whatever! But the bottom line is that it&#39;s interesting and the food is very flavorful. Definitely worth a visit especially if you&#39;ve become jaded on the regular stuff. Arguably it is a little unhealthy in that we tried most of the fried stuff. But what can you say. Anything fried always tastes better. Sigh! Looks like a diet over the weekend. Anyhow I enjoyed the meal and company and will probably come again, this time with the family. Parking though is challenging so take a cab or plan well.

text: Well what a nice surprise: I did not want to venture too far from home today as lots to do, and decided to give the bakery a few minutes walk away a try. And lo and behold - this place is tiny and beautiful, and features &#34;Austrian&#34; croissants! <br><br>Most of you might not know this, but the Austrians (or shall I say Viennese :-)) invented the croissant, as the Kipferl, a crescent-shaped viennoiserie made of yeast dough, was the forerunner of what the French turned into the buttery, crispy friend we all love.<br><br>Thus, I was curious as to why they called it specifically &#34;Austrian&#34;: apparently it is the production process with special butter, so the consistency would be different from the French cousin.<br><br>Two minutes later I sat down with my plain croissant - which I had halved, to try one half warmed up, the other not.<br><br>It was a nice surprise tasting it, as it tasted just like a Kipferl, so less fatty, sugary and buttery, with a denser quality than your typical croissant. <br><br>The Latte I had ordered was lovely, too, and I took another one with me to stimulate - hopefully - my brain cells.<br><br>Most of you won&#39;t venture out to this corner of town unless you live here - but check out their signature cakes for take away (only large boxed sizes!) for your next birthday or anniversary - the NY cheesecake looked delicious. Ok I am raving so I&#39;ll stop here. So glad I live close by :-))

Haiwaiian wave burger ($8.80) - 4 stars<br>Good flavoring and I liked the pineapple, which was soft and juicy. Seemed like a small portion but half of this and half of the clubman sandwich along with the hot chocolate kept me pretty full.<br><br>Rendang curry clubman sandwich ($8.80) - 2.5 stars<br>There was hardly any filling! My friend and I agreed it just didn&#39;t taste like anything - not like rendang. It wasn&#39;t bad - the &#34;rendang&#34; filling was pretty good but there was really little of it.<br><br>Hot lava chocolate ($6.90) - 3 stars<br>Nothing special. Way overpriced tbh.<br><br>Ambience - 2.5 stars<br>Good for coffee but too small for lunch - the table was so small (barely enough for 2 people) I knocked my friend&#39;s paper sandwich basket and it landed on his lap. It was pretty funny and then I felt pretty bad.

text: I like the passion of the person of who served me, it was pretty infectious and you could really feel the energy emanating from him. I am not sure if he is the owner or just an employee, but it does not matter. Everyone should have a passion for what they do. Because of him and his zeal for the food, I actually bought more than I initially wanted.<br><br>I went in wanting to buy the gula melaka kaya jam. I love kaya and gula melaka, combine them together and it seemed like heaven. It does taste very nice too, a softer sweetness from the gula melaka. <br><br>The cakes caught my attention and I decided to have a slice of cake with coffee. Again, the guy was so into his stuff that he paired my drink with the cake. Latte with hokkaido roll (green tea with red bean flavor). The cake was light and not very sweet but it was enough to complement the smoothness of the latte which was not too acidic. I usually doctored my coffee liberally with milk and sugar. He told me to try it without any sugar, and it was fine. <br><br>I also bought a tiramisu to go. That was very rich and creamy. <br><br>The place is small with just a couple of small tables. Definitely not a place for big groups of people to chill, but it is cozy enough for 1 or 2 persons for a cuppa and slice of cake. <br><br>I would love to try the sandwiches and sourdough bread and the signature cake - Chocolate Trovana which needs advance order. <br><br>If the location is more convenient to me, I think I will be a regular at Chef Icon. <br><br>Yelp Feb 2014 Challenge: 26/28

Popped in here to buy some jars of kaya to bring home, but they are no longer making it!  Apparently it was too much work for them and so for now, they&#39;ve stopped production.  Still, a great place for cheesecakes and other all natural bakery items, but their kaya will be sorely missed.

text: Chef icon nature bakery is one of those place that no one knows about, but once you have had their signature cakes. you will want to know where it is.<br><br>their 2 signature cakes are Chocolate Trovana &amp; new york cheese cake, and they are only available in whole cakes (500g, 1kg, Choco Trovana also comes in 2kg) and you gotta order them 2 to 3 days in advance. <br><br>Francis also makes a whole list of stuff, baked goods, cakes (yes there are cakes available in slices), kaya, peanut butter with the same principles: Best natural ingredients, no preservatives, with lots of passion and love.<br><br>Drop by, get a clubman sandwich. and a flat white. (i know the duxton/ everton road area is full of gourmet coffeeshops, but he does a good cuppa too)<br><br>Closed on Sunday and Public Holidays.

Delicious! Clubman sandwiches are SO GOOD. Maybe I was just hungry, but it was deliciously toasted, thin bread, chockful of veggies :) Nice ham and cheese (mozzarella and somewhat else that I&#39;ve forgotten) - this was the Mexican dream. ($8.80 I think)<br><br>Hokkaido roll was nice and soft, with a huge dollop of cream in the middle. Shared a matcha one with red bean cream, liked that there were whole pieces of red bean! yay. Apparently the matcha is from Korea or something, I forget.<br><br>Decided to try the guava tea on a whim, $4.90 for a hot cup, I believe. Very fragrant!<br><br>They clearly take pride in providing quality ingredients (which shows in their prices too, haha). Guy at the counter was very friendly and didn&#39;t mind us moving two tables together (although it clearly states NOT to) since it was nearing closing time..<br><br>Wish it was in a more convenient place for me to visit more often! Was very tempted by their Sakura bread (dark choc and banana bread) but at $2.90... had to think twice. Ah well.

text: Delicious food. I don&#39;t know much about bread but whatever they are doing here, the bread tastes 100 times better than Subway Sandwich. The food here is amazing and light enough so you can still function. The coffee comes in one size...and it&#39;s pretty small but I guess coming from the states, where everything is big, small coffee is just a part if the Singapore culture of efficiency. If u r nearby or staying in one of the condos...def try this place out. The owner is super passionate and will spend a few minutes talking about his delicious creations

Tried coffee after lunch. Standard quality, consider not expensive. Cakes look nice, will leave to next trial. Custom service need improvement, it is probably previaling issue in Singapore hospitality industry.

text: Stumbled upon this find as Strangers&#39; Reunion was closed on Tuesday. It is a really hidden gem in a stretch that&#39;s overpopulated with little cafes. What I like about this cafe is that it is unpretentious, serves good, natural food in a very chill out setting. Unfortunately, there isn&#39;t a big capacity for sit ins. 8 people would already be pushing it. I had coffee, the Hokkaido roll (chocolate &amp; strawberry), the Yakiniku Sandwich in my visits there. Everything did not disappoint. The sandwich was fantastic! It was tasty, healthy with fresh greens and yummy yakiniku mushrooms all stuffed into a sesame bread. As for the Hokkaido roll, the sponge cake was moist yet light and fluffy but dense. How did he do it? The strawberry is good with the coffee while the chocolate (Belgian, no less!) was slightly sweeter and heavier on the palate. My colleague bought the Banana chocolate cake and it was heavenly! Moist yet rich with chocolate flavour, it blended really well with the banana as well. The owner, whom I spoke to, mentioned the food has no preservatives which means it also doesn&#39;t sell any products with animal based ingredients. Have been there twice. Would definitely drop by when I&#39;m in the neighbourhood. Love it!

text: I&#39;m a little spoiled now, and won&#39;t settle for a Coke any more - I need some bubble tea, and since these guys are everywhere now, it&#39;s an easy choice. Also, because they&#39;re everywhere now, the queues have vanished, which makes me a happy camper. One thing that makes me mad tho - Y U GET RID OF BROWN CRYSTAL JELLY?! That was my favourite, and now I have to pick for herbal jelly (chin chow, essentially) or regular pearls. First world problems, I&#39;ll be the first to admit.<br><br>These guys are a well-oiled machine, and you get your drink in the length it takes you to read this review... Okay read it a little slower.

text: Got the black plum tea with white pearls ($2.90) and caplis green tea with white pearls ($4.00).  Never had the white pearl jellys before and they were excellent.  Crunchy and chewy at the same time :).

This hit the spot and you can find many of them sprawled around Singapore. It was great for an afternoon tea/coffee break, while also substituting as a rest stop for some AC in the hot Singapore weather. <br><br>I recommend the usual kaya toast with pandan and butter as well as a an iced coffee or kopi. It is made with condensed milk and not your usual iced coffee here, but it&#39;s the right amount of sweetnedd without being overwhelming. This chain has been around for years and I can&#39;t complain. I think the only thing that could make it better was more butter on the bread!

text: Ya Kun has dozens of outlets in Singapore but this is the original location. It was conveniently located near our hotel in Chinatown and was a great way to start the morning.<br><br>It was his first time in Singapore and we shared one order of kaya toast, eggs, and tea. It was not a bad way to spend a few dollars.

text: I wanted in on this kaya business, as I saw references to it everywhere. Asked my friend KM what it actually was. Just toast with Asiany brioche-like bread with a slather of coconut jam atop.<br><br>Liked so much, I ordered it again at Terminal 1 in Changi, where there is also a little first floor kiosk!

Chasu toast.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Chasu toast.'}]
text: It&#39;s hard to miss Ya Kun Kaya, they are everywhere in Singapore! <br><br>This particular joint is located near Far East Square, a much bigger venue than the other Ya Kun Kaya outlets. Plus point that they are open at 7: 30 am, to have your early breakfast in solitude. Their menu is simple - it&#39;s all about toast+ coffee/tea + soft boiled eggs, but those three things have served me well!<br><br>I got the savory chasu toast and the durian kaya toast. The chasu toast was quite flavorful, but the DURIAN kaya toast won a sweet spot in my heart!!  Perfectly toasted crisp bread sandwiching the rich and creamy durian paste added with kaya and butter - delicious and they smell so good *sniff sniff* :P <br><br>Service was not exactly friendly, but at least they are speedy and efficient. Overall, Ya Kun Kaya Toast is an awesome spot to get your quick breakfast fix. I&#39;ll most definitely be back!

text: Despite the many recommendations that came to us from friends to try this place when visiting Singapore, it had just an average impression on us. <br><br>FOOD:<br>- Kaya Toast +3.5/5<br>It&#39;s just toast with their famous spread &amp; butter. While it is definitely unique, taste-wise it was just ok.<br>- Soft boiled eggs +3.5/5<br>I&#39;m a HUGE fan of eggs and was excited for this but this also was just... ok. <br><br>SERVICE:<br>- is quick and fast. Be prepared to pay as soon as your food comes out - that&#39;s just the way they roll here. <br><br>While I would still recommend newcomers to Singapore to try this place when visiting, I would say it&#39;s a one-time visit spot only.

Singaporean take on dessert for breakfast.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Singaporean take on dessert for breakfast.'}]
text: Put down that nasty free hostel breakfast and go spend the $6 SGD on breakfast here. Gotta eat kaya toast when in Sing; it&#39;s their version of dessert for breakfast. <br><br>This is the orig, so skip all the makeup and go sweat it out at breakfast. The sweetened iced coffee is strong and delicious. Runny eggs you should mix a little with soy sauce and salt. Yum. <br><br>As others suggested, bring wet wipes! Kaya will glue to your fingers, and Sing is a land of BYOT (tissue) wherever you go. <br> <br>Staff is so very friendly, but when the boss lady walks around to collect before you eat, better pay up quick!

text: LOVE YA KUN KAYA!<br><br>This was our first ever bite of kaya toast. We came here for breakfast one morning before exploring S&#39;pore&#39;s Clarke Quay and Chinatown areas. This is the ORIGINAL YK location and it automatically feels &#34;authentic&#34; and &#34;historic.&#34;<br><br>This location has the most seating out of all the other YK locations we visited. There is outside seating as well as fans-equipped inside tables. We the set of kaya toast and sugar kaya toast with iced coffee/tea and soft-boiled eggs. HOLY SMOKES. We&#39;ve never had kaya toast or traditional Singaporean brekkie before and our minds were blown. I still salivate a little thinking about that delicious savory runny and sweet crunchy combo. Pandan is what makes up a lot of the kaya spread...and by golly it&#39;s amazing. <br><br>The servers here all speak flawless English and Mandarin--as well as other languages! Bosses. The service was amazingly quick and efficient, and their menus are easy to navigate--so fret not, foreigners. Shoutout to the amazing staff. We were tourists totally soaking up the atmosphere and DELICIOUS food, but we also saw lots of locals eating here from families to single customers.

text: Classic Singaporean breakfast that you have to try! The toast on its own is really sweet, but the key to enjoying it is to add soy sauce to the liquid eggs, mix it up and then dunk the toast into the egg mixture, making sure it is well coated. Don&#39;t be afraid to scoop more on top! The cold drinks were good as well.

text: Quintessential Singaporean breakfast! Kaya toast, runny eggs, and coffee. Well I don&#39;t drink coffee, so I had tea with milk and sugar instead.<br><br>A really nice man asked me if I was eating there or for takeaway, and when I said it was for there, he told me to take a seat anywhere and then brought over a menu. I got the above mentioned breakfast set, which was set A. There was a set B, C, and D, which had different kinds of kaya toast. I remember set D was a kaya peanut butter toast which also sounded amazing. <br><br>The kaya butter toast was pretty delicious the bread is very toasted and crispy. At one point, the nice old man sat down with me and showed me how to properly eat kaya toast. He asked to put soy sauce and some black pepper into my runny eggs. Then I mixed it and he told me to dip my toast into the runny egg/soy sauce mixture. Really tasty! Great hearty way to start the day!

Kaya toast with butter and iced Milo', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Kaya toast with butter and iced Milo'}]
text: Although this place is a chain, I&#39;m still a big fan of this classic Singaporean breakfast chain. The usual kaya toast with butter, and soft-boiled eggs and iced Milo is the winning combo.<br><br>My boyfriend and I walked into this place on one morning and got told that the hot drinks maker was down, but Singapore is always warm anyway, so why get the hot drinks? We were however puzzled on how on earth the soft-boiled eggs would be consumed, but the instinct took over and we soon munched the toast-dipped-in egg like a local would.<br><br>Service is neither friendly nor rude, just the usual efficiency you see in Singapore and I was at least being grateful to be greeted in English, and not Chinese as everyone in Chinatown assumed that I could speak Mandarin (in which I couldn&#39;t). I would still go to this place again if I&#39;m nearby, but for now - a jar of kaya jam bought from Singapore should do the trick when I&#39;m at home in Copenhagen. It won&#39;t be the same, but at least I didn&#39;t have to endure the 12-hour flight.

text: My friend highly recommended the coconut jam here and told us to save room after dinner to try their toast.  Good thing we walked around before trying this place out and glad I had extra room to stuff this down.<br><br>My husband had a small cup of coffee. He said it was too sweet for him. I personally did not try this so I can&#39;t comment on that. Hes also the type of person who drinks coffee black with no sugar or creams. <br><br>Their Ya Kun Kaya Toast... omg.. i just have to say.. I have never had anything like this before. Super delicious where it wasnt super sweet and just the right amount of jam to make me want to finosh my toast even if i was full from dinner. PLEAsEEEE open in the US!!! I saw they had multiple locations around Asia but non in the US!!! Im going to be sad once my jar runs out of jam! Soooo delicious. Once you try it youre gonna wanna bring a ton back home!!!

text: This place was closed for 2 days for Chinese New Year but finally opened on last day of our Singapore trip. Had to try the traditional breakfast. This place has interesting history that you can read about while waiting in the queue. Once we ordered, the food came out fairly quickly. It&#39;s a family business and the service was excellent. The coffee was amazing and made the old fashion way w a sock! Order one of the Kaya Value sets and you can&#39;t go wrong. Great prices too! Would highly recommend this place for traditional Kaya toast

I actually didn&#39;t go to this location but I couldn&#39;t find a yelp page for the location that I did go to (it was in some mall that is connected to my hotel).. so I&#39;m just going to post my review here lol<br><br>I came to Ya Kun Kaya Toast for breakfast and ordered the Kaya Butter Toast Set (#1), which came with a coffee and runny eggs. The coffee was good, but it didn&#39;t taste that out of the ordinary. I have a really weak stomach when it comes to runny eggs and these eggs were SUPERRRRR runny.. so I didn&#39;t eat them and can&#39;t comment on how good it is.<br><br>But the kaya toast... omg SO GOOD. I will admit that I felt a little sick afterwards because of how buttery and sweet it was but it was so worth it! The jam that they put in it was heaven!! <br><br>Highly recommend a visit if you&#39;re in Singapore!

text: Wow! Amazing! It&#39;s so simple but so good! Kaya is the coconut jam that&#39;s spread onto the toast then they also put a sliced of butter in the middle. I love how it&#39;s dipped into the soft boiled egg, the whole combination is quite unique. Don&#39;t forget to add the sweet soy sauce into the egg! <br>This is a popular shop with numerous franchises all over town, I find this location&#39;s decor to stand out more than ones you find at the malls! So come to this shop! It&#39;s also in a nice area with other restaurants because this is obviously just an appetizer.

Toast and Barley drink', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Toast and Barley drink'}]
text: A classic establishment in Singapore. Would go for the famous kaya toast, which is surprisingly good considering how simple the dish is. Their kaya paste is not too sweet and has a good sticky texture. The bread is toasted well and the butter adds to the decadence /creaminess. The traditional coffee/tea (Kopi, Teh) are ok - you can find better ones elsewhere.

Really good kaya toast and coffee. It&#39;s a bit strange with the whole paying and ordering system. First you sit down,someone comes and takes your order then your drink will come out first and you pay when your toast gets here and the lady tells you the amount. In our case we order two sets of toasts so she asked for the money when my first toast got to the table and asked us to pay again when my second toast arrived, until I gave her a weird look and she said you paid? I said yes, you collected the money two minutes ago. Be careful of their inefficient system.

text: This was a very solid breakfast that felt very authentic.<br><br>While this was my first time having kaya toast, the down-to-earth staff and the other people reflected how this isn&#39;t a tourist trap type restaurant. Now about the actual food<br><br>Kaya Toast - kaya jam is made from eggs, coconut, and pandan. While eating the kaya toast, the flavor is primarily sweet with a hint of coconut richness and a whiff of floral pandan, but sweetness is really the primary impression here. Also, due to the generous spread of butter/margarine, kaya toast feels a lot heavier than you might expect. I thought that the soft and runny soft boiled eggs would be too much for me but I think the quality of the eggs are better here or they&#39;re just perfectly cooked. They didn&#39;t have any of that raw eggy aroma that can sometimes make me retch a bit.<br><br>Milk Tea - not quite as rich as hong kong milk tea. I think the UHT milk gives it a bit more of a cooked milk flavor which is quite nice. It&#39;s not too sweet, has some decent depth of tea flavor.

text: Starbucks Singapore style style? <br><br>There are are several of these in Singapore. They do coffee, soft boiled eggs and toast with butter and kaya (coconut) jam. Comfort food.<br><br>My only gripe is they have too much butter and not enough jam on their toast.

text: Obsessed with Kaya Toast. One of the few spots I went religiously every morning on my trip. Great spot with fast service.<br><br>Tips:<br>- Try the white bread kaya toast (no crust). Soft &amp; delightful!<br>- Kaya toast comes with a sliver of butter inside with Kaya<br>- Coffee: Coffee with Milk<br>- Coffee-O: Black Coffee with sugar<br>- Coffee-C: Coffee with sugar &amp; cream (condensed milk)

This is a very famous Singaporean style breakfast/brunch cafe.  They have locations all over Singapore.  Supposedly they have been in business since 1944. Our aunt took us there to try it.  Like most of the local markets in Singapore, the place is cramped (although not outdoors).  The small wooden chairs and tables are packed tightly together that it is hard to get around when crowded. Yet it is worth the wait, even with the long queue (line).<br><br> They have a very strong milk tea that is best served hot.  Get the Kaya Toast with butter.  You can usually mix it up with two runny eggs, or you can just have it plain.  Either way, you will enjoy the lightness of the bread, the crunch of the toast, and the rich full bodied taste of the coffee.  Come here if you want to enjoy a good start to the day!

text: This is the original Ya Kun Kaya Toast Shop. It&#39;s just outside of the Far East Square along China Street with a few other great eateries!<br><br>If you&#39;re ever visiting Singapore, everyone will tell you to try the famous kaya toast at Ya Kun. I honestly think you should try kaya toast when you&#39;re in Singapore, but not at Ya Kun (I like Toast Box better). I don&#39;t understand the hype of this place. I&#39;m not a fan of over-toasted, hard bread. With very little kaya jam and way too much butter, I had to go to another kaya toast shop later that day just to make up for the disappointing experience. I just wanted to try one slice of their toast with the kaya jam. But they suckered me in to their pricey combo special: 2 toasts, soft boiled egg, and a drink. Overall, I was super disappointed with my first kaya toast experience here.<br><br>Service: 4 stars<br>Kaya Toast: 1 star<br><br>Opening Hours<br>Monday to Friday: 7.30am to 6.30pm<br>Saturday and Sunday: 8.30am to 5.00pm<br>Public Holiday: Closed

Firstly, this review is for the store in united square off Thompson Rd but I could not find it on Yelp. I ordered the toast set which comes with two soft boiled eggs, two kaya and butter toast sandwiches and a cup of coffee. All-in-all a fairly good deal for the price. The meal brought back many memories from my past and it felt good.

text: Straight forward, no frill, solid Kaya toast! <br>Ya Kun dates back DECADES perfecting the Kaya toast and you just cannot go wrong. When there&#39;s barely a menu and the auntie asking you straight up &#34;how many&#34;, you know you&#39;ve come to the authentic place.<br>The toasts are crunchy on the outside, and sweet and tad creamy inside... hmmm taste of singapore in one small bite!

text: I don&#39;t care what anyone else says: this is the best thing I ate in Singapore. <br><br>I got the standard set butter kaya toast with milk tea and 2 soft boiled eggs. It was delicious and the only thing I could ever ask for in a breakfast. Toast was perfectly crunchy and toasted; the butter inside not yet melted which is apparently how it is supposed to be. The kaya was the perfect amount of sweetness. <br>My friend who just got an iced coffee said it was delicious too. Don&#39;t think you can go wrong here. I could eat this everyday.

text: I can not find any listing for the Ya Kun Kaya Toast located at Tiong Bahru Plaza, 302 Tiong Bahru Road, Singapore.<br>I have therefor posted it here, but I wish to stress that this review is in no way reflective of the other outlets.<br><br>This is not a one day occurrence, in fact it happened two days... in a row!<br>I went there to have a cup of coffee and some kaya toast.<br>The coffee came out after five minutes.   I finished drinking it before the toast came out....12 minutes later and stone cold.<br>How long, I ask you, does it take to make toast....what were they doing...grinding the wheat to make the flour to make the dough to bake the bread to slice it so that they could make toast??<br>Next day, same deal...coffee after a few minutes, and then the wait...and wait....and wait.<br>Finally, after waiting 15 minutes for kaya toast.....and outrageous amount of time, even by the pitifully poor standards of service in Singapore....I very obviously got up and walked out.....even after I had ordered and paid.<br>Can you imagine a Singaporean getting up and walking out after paying for food and not getting it??!......that would NEVER happen.<br>The service in this place stink...stinks... it stinks to high heaven..it stinks worse than rotten tuna fish left out on a hot August day.<br>How is that for hyperbole?<br>I challenge any Singaporean to verbally spar with me on this issue.<br>This place deserves to go out of business.
hmmm kinda runny for my taste but glad I tried it. Id eat it again and bought Kaya jam? to give out as a present.

text: LOVE YA KUN KAYA!<br><br>This was our first ever bite of kaya toast. We came here for breakfast one morning before exploring S&#39;pore&#39;s Clarke Quay and Chinatown areas. This is the ORIGINAL YK location and it automatically feels &#34;authentic&#34; and &#34;historic.&#34;<br><br>This location has the most seating out of all the other YK locations we visited. There is outside seating as well as fans-equipped inside tables. We the set of kaya toast and sugar kaya toast with iced coffee/tea and soft-boiled eggs. HOLY SMOKES. We&#39;ve never had kaya toast or traditional Singaporean brekkie before and our minds were blown. I still salivate a little thinking about that delicious savory runny and sweet crunchy combo. Pandan is what makes up a lot of the kaya spread...and by golly it&#39;s amazing. <br><br>The servers here all speak flawless English and Mandarin--as well as other languages! Bosses. The service was amazingly quick and efficient, and their menus are easy to navigate--so fret not, foreigners. Shoutout to the amazing staff. We were tourists totally soaking up the atmosphere and DELICIOUS food, but we also saw lots of locals eating here from families to single customers.

text: I knew I had to at least try a traditional Singaporean breakfast before leaving.  The menu is stripped back and simple - choose from coffee/tea kaya/kaya french toast all for the equivalent of about 5 quid.  This is a stripped back (as others have mentioned) cafe and if you&#39;re in a rush it&#39;s probably best to order at the counter and take it to go - once you seat yourself it&#39;s all about getting the attention of the staff, so you definitely need to make your presence known by a few waves and constant eye contact. My food came out piecemeal - coffee, then 10 minutes later eggs, and another 15 later the toast but luckily I had the whole morning to hang around so enjoyed people watching in the interim.  This was clearly a super popular spot, and you can see why. If you like a breakfast on the sweeter side, you&#39;ll likely enjoy this runny egg/jam and french toast like concoction with sweet Singapore coffee. Be prepared for the sugar rush that follows and don&#39;t forget to bring your own wet wipes/napkins (probably an obvious for most of you used to Singapore but I was constantly walking around with sticky hands!)

This is a very famous Singaporean style breakfast/brunch cafe.  They have locations all over Singapore.  Supposedly they have been in business since 1944. Our aunt took us there to try it.  Like most of the local markets in Singapore, the place is cramped (although not outdoors).  The small wooden chairs and tables are packed tightly together that it is hard to get around when crowded. Yet it is worth the wait, even with the long queue (line).<br><br> They have a very strong milk tea that is best served hot.  Get the Kaya Toast with butter.  You can usually mix it up with two runny eggs, or you can just have it plain.  Either way, you will enjoy the lightness of the bread, the crunch of the toast, and the rich full bodied taste of the coffee.  Come here if you want to enjoy a good start to the day!

text: So apparently this is the traditional Singaporean breakfast, coffee brewed in bags (which you can see hanging up), runny eggs and Kaya Toast (coconut jam/french toast kinda thing) in a stripped back, functional cafe.<br><br>Ya Kun is a franchise, there is a model of the first store in here, but don&#39;t expect anything posh and fancy, half the point is that it&#39;s &#39;as was&#39;. Metal tables and chairs, plastic cutlery but hey, who cares as long as the food is good, right?<br><br>And it was! Coffee with condensed milk, runny eggs with a dash of soy, and Kaya toast, all delicious! They have a few different options/combinations, all of which are cheap.<br><br>Definitely worth a visit if you get the chance.
hmmm kinda runny for my taste but glad I tried it. Id eat it again and bought Kaya jam? to give out as a present.

text: Quintessential Singaporean breakfast! Kaya toast, runny eggs, and coffee. Well I don&#39;t drink coffee, so I had tea with milk and sugar instead.<br><br>A really nice man asked me if I was eating there or for takeaway, and when I said it was for there, he told me to take a seat anywhere and then brought over a menu. I got the above mentioned breakfast set, which was set A. There was a set B, C, and D, which had different kinds of kaya toast. I remember set D was a kaya peanut butter toast which also sounded amazing. <br><br>The kaya butter toast was pretty delicious the bread is very toasted and crispy. At one point, the nice old man sat down with me and showed me how to properly eat kaya toast. He asked to put soy sauce and some black pepper into my runny eggs. Then I mixed it and he told me to dip my toast into the runny egg/soy sauce mixture. Really tasty! Great hearty way to start the day!

text: I like coming to Ya Kun when I am in Singapore.  Yes, it is overhyped among tourists but I still find myself coming back every time.  The food is solid.  It&#39;s very filling too.  I feel like I could skip lunch after eating the &#34;full breakfast&#34; here.  If you come early enough, you may even avoid the tourists (who generally comes later during the day).

text: I remember asking everyone about what I should eat or buy when I was in Singapore. <br>Kaya (toast) came up multiple times.<br>I was like...&#34;yeah, that sounds so good!&#34; <br>In reality, I was thinking...&#34;what the eff is kaya?!&#34;<br><br>For those of you who don&#39;t know, kaya is a spread made with coconut, eggs, sugar and pandan...or so Wikipedia says.<br><br>So I walked into Ya Kun Kaya Toast and of course ordered the kaya toast with butter, and decided on an iced milk tea to go with it. I guess this is a very traditional breakfast for Singaporeans, so I had to try it since breakfast is my absolute favorite meal of the day. I could seriously eat it for every meal. I loved the flavor of the kaya and it meshed really well with the toasted, warm bread. The butter was something I had a hard time with. I felt like when I got to the middle of the toast, I was just eating an entire tablespoon of butter along with the toast/kaya. I could seriously feel my arteries clogging by the second. However, when I asked a Singaporean if it was supposed to be like that, she said yes, and the butter is the best part! Perhaps I&#39;m not cultured enough to understand all that butter, and next time, I&#39;m just going to get kaya toast, no butter! I mean, the butter was good, I just couldn&#39;t stand eating it, knowing that it was just a chunk of butter. On the other hand, the milk tea here had good flavor, although it was a little too sweet for my liking. However, it was a great drink to drink with my food! <br><br>Overall, my first experience with kaya was really good, and I even went to the store later on to purchase a jar of it to bring home. I&#39;m just going to cut down on the butter when I do make my own!

text: So I like too much butter and I don&#39;t care if it&#39;s melted or not and iced coffee to wash the toast down with was perfect for me. <br><br>I didn&#39;t eat enough kaya toast in different places to make proper comparisons and having just gotten off a really long flight and not adjusting well to Singapore&#39;s weather I def didn&#39;t want to eat half boiled eggs with soy but I could see how the contrast with the sweet toast would work well.

I guess everybody has their preference on where to get the best Kaya toast, but Ya Kun is definitely one of my favorites. The thin toast, runny soft-boiled eggs and teh tarik make a great breakfast and for S$4 you just can&#39;t beat it anywhere.

during my first visit to singapore, i knew i wanted to try Kaya toast for breakfast! luckily Ya Kun Kaya Toast was right next to our hotel (AMOY). while I knew this was a chain, every time we walked by this location, it was full of people so i figured it still had to be good if locals were frequenting it haha. we came right around opening (8am i think) and the place wasnt crowded yet. of course i had to order the Kaya Toast with butter set  (~$4 USD) that comes with boiled eggs and kopi. i must say that i thought the kaya jam was a bit too sweet for me, but when dipped into the soft boiled eggs, it was delicious! and omg i was all about that kopi. the kopi still had a strong flavor and the condensed milk gave it just enough sweetness. service was quick and efficient, but this was a quick breakfast stop anyway so i wasnt expecting anything more haha. loved my first taste of a Singaporean breakfast!

text: This place has both indoor and outdoor dining areas. When we arrived, we found that the place was not too crowded and there were plenty of seats around, so a reservation did not seem to be necessary.<br>Anyway, we ordered the following: garlic bread, the deep fried combo, Italian sausage baked rice, garlic prawn baked rice and some other dishes which I can&#39;t remember at this point in time. <br>We had the soup of the day, which was the clam chowder. This one was average at best; I&#39;ve had better ones elsewhere. The garlic bread was satisfying though: it was crunchy and mixed with the garlic and parsley, was very fragrant indeed.<br>Our main dish was the deep fried combo, which consisted of a mixture of fried stuff like chicken tenders, buffalo wings, onion wings and fries. The portion wasn&#39;t big enough for us though, but the taste was pretty ok. I guess you can&#39;t really go wrong with fried stuff.<br>Overall, an ok place to visit.

Great service and people that made us feel so welcome. <br><br>It was a sumptous meal with finger foods like the cripsy drumlets and waffle fries with cheese, mayo and BBQ sauce. Definitely satisfied my palate!

text: A Good Habit To Pick-Up!<br><br>Tucked away on top of a hill in Telok Blangah Rise is Old Habits.<br>Opened by a husband and wife team, Old Habits is part museum, part cafe, part antique store. <br>The feel of the area itself brings you back a few decades, with only a small market and a few shops serving this quiet community. <br>First impression? Old Habit brings back even more nostalgia with their old outdoor seating area. Made up of vintage clam shell chairs, you would have expected a couple of old uncles in singlets to be asleep on the chairs, if not for the bright lights of the cafe.<br><br>Opening the door, we were expecting to be hit by a wave of muskiness from the old items on display but was pleasantly surprised when the place smelt pretty.... Good! <br><br>If you&#39;re looking for a fun antique items to buy than this is the place for you! <br>Old telephones, photos, textbooks, comics, you name it, they have it. It&#39;s like being a 5 year old again. With their extensive collection of view finders / view masters, it was hours of  fun going through everything they had to offer and the best part? Almost everything&#39;s for sale!<br><br>Now to the food. A simple menu made up of around 5-6 items per category (Appetizers, mains etc), &#34;Old Habit&#34; chooses to keep it simple and manageable, ensuring that by not over stretching themselves with an overly extensive menu, they will not sacrifice the quality of the food being served.<br><br>Drinks: <br>Lemon Lime Float &amp; CoCo Melaka <br><br>What better way to add to the nostalgia of the cafe than with a drink that reminds us of the past. Well thought through and re-created, the Lemon Lime Float tastes exactly like Solero, a lime and vanilla ice cream that I&#39;m sure many of us LOVED while we were younger. <br>A perfect drink for a really really hot day! <br>The CoCo Melaka Soda was a nice twist. Coconut juice, with a hint of Gula Melaka topped with a scoop of vanilla ice cream. <br>The Gula Melaka adds a nice richness n sweetness to an otherwise ordinary drink and even helps in bringing out the sweetness and fragrance of the coconut juice. <br><br>Spaghetti Carbonara. <br>Will I ever learn my lesson? Ordering Carbonaras even though I see the words &#34;creamy&#34;. I&#39;m proud to finally say that, this carbonara is pretty darn good! <br><br>Unlike most Carbonaras, we could actually taste the eggs in the sauce. <br>The sauce was rich, eggy and so delicious! Pasta was al Dante and that sprinkle of chilli powder gave it an extra kick. Only thing is lacked was a good sprinkle of parmesan to give is that sharpness but overall, definitely one the nicest we&#39;ve had under $15.00.<br><br>Jessy&#39;s Spicy Casserole<br>Now this was an interesting twist! Unlike the normal Shepard&#39;s Pie, this was done with a chicken chunks marinated in a Nonya sauce. <br>The initial scoop felt a little disappointing, with the lack of gravy and meat, but as we slowly dug in, revealing the juicy pieces of chicken, we soon realised that a gravy wasn&#39;t really needed! <br><br>The nonya sauce or marinade used was so tasty! And the mashed used had a hint of curry powder which added to the fragrance of the dish, elevating the potatoes to a whole different level of yumness.<br><br>This was a very well constructed dish that turned an otherwise ordinary shepherd&#39;s pie into something a little more local. <br><br>Coconut kueh with Vanilla Ice cream. <br>What a way to end our meal with this delicious dessert! With crunchy coconut flakes prominent in the kueh, this felt like an Asian take on a bread and butter pudding. The fragrant smell of toasted coconut flakes mixed with the sweetness from the ice cream and the slight saltiness from kueh makes this an absolute delight to have. <br><br>Overall, this place is fantastic, with the owners taking the time to slowly show you some of the cool toys they have available. They&#39;re friendly and very welcoming and you can tell that they have the dedication and passion to keep this place going, ensuring that whether you&#39;re 6 or 60, you&#39;ll feel like a kid again once you step through the doors of Old Habits.

text: Must tries here: The iced tea, tofu salad, chicken masala wrap, turkey cranberry sandwich and peanut butter cupcake.

Used to be much better before they renovated. Portions used to be bigger, the quality better and the price lower. Nonetheless, I LOVE their toufu and pumpkin salad :) <br><br>Sandwich wise - I would recommend the caesar wrap and chicken. toasted. <br><br>Desserts - Definitely the recommend the lemon meringue cake. Although it can come off a tad bit too sweet for some. Another popular one are the cupcakes - peanut butter seems to be the favorite among my friends. Cheesecakes are pretty decent too. <br><br>Great place to grab a take-out lunch. A bit too squeezy for sit-in lunch. We kept bumping into other tables.

Part of the Marmalade Pantry group, Toast is made more for speedy lunches than for lingering and being seen. After all, you first have to find the darned place (look for the lobby near Chloe). Once there, choose between the various salads (you can mix them! I like wild rice with tofu and pumpkin), quiche and sandwich options. If you want something warm, there is always soup, but remember to save room for dessert. Or you could always bring back one of MP&#39;s cupcakes for afternoon tea...

text: Looking for somewhere secluded in the noisy and crowded Raffles City for a nice quiet meal? Cedele at Raffles City Level 3 is your answer! <br><br>Located right at the back, it overlooks the lobby of one of the hotels. There&#39;s table service here so just allow the service staff to take you to an available table and you can sit and enjoy your meal. They serve a full Cedele menu in their open kitchen.<br><br>For weekday lunch, it can get full very quickly so do head there early to get a table.

text: Used to love this place as it&#39;s more secluded and food was good. Since a couple of years now, I find the location always understaffed so during peak hours, the food takes a while to be ordered and arrive. Good thing is there&#39;s no additional service tax

I work in RCT and in the evening, there are not many options left. So I go there quite often. Decent sandwiches and soups. <br>Sandwiches: I like the brie one, the beef pastrami. For the soups: mushroom and tomato &amp; bell pepper are great. Moroccan carrots - stay away, (it tastes like baby food so if you force yourself to eat it, you will immediately feel like you are a 3 year old, being force fed vegetables you dont like :) )<br>Good place but slow.... too slow service. Their bred is decent when toasted but the one that&#39;s free on the side is actually very chewy... not a fan.

text: Not the best branch of LiHo Tea in Singapore. There&#39;s a long line because they don&#39;t have a visible menu for you until you get to the counter. That makes for a wait when people need time to decide what to get at the cashier. <br><br>I ordered the Strawberry cream Oolong tea, which was noted as a popular pick. I asked the cashier what she recommended but she didn&#39;t really respond. She also didn&#39;t tell me that there were no more boba pearls left! Lame! No bubbles at a bubble tea spot.<br><br>I requested the drink to be 70 percent sweet with less ice. But the strawberry cream was still sickly sweet. Not my favorite! Wish there was a stronger oolong tea flavor instead.<br><br>Will try another branch of LiHo. But this busy spot wasn&#39;t the best!

text: This place is only hip because of its location. It&#39;s kind of cramped, and the food is no better than Sushi Tei. Not too pricey, but that&#39;s not enough a reason to go back.

This has now become my favorite sushi place in Singapore!  <br><br>what is there not to love?  they don&#39;t put tons of mayo on every roll they make, the fish tastes very fresh, everything is made right there in front of you (if you sit at the counter).  I also love the fact that you can get other Japanese dishes, like curry rice and udon.<br><br>i think my favorite little nuance is that they allow you to pick a unique sake class whenever you order a sake and will even let you try them before you buy them.<br><br>check this place out, but don&#39;t tell too many people as it is small and i still want to be able to get a seat!

I was here a couple of nights ago with some friends, and this place really reminds me of Asian fusion places in the states. You get sushi rolls and $26 entrees and the standard Asian fusion appetizers. We tried the chirashi bowl, ramen aglio olio with foie gras and smoked duck, as well as the miso cod.<br><br>The miso cod was really good, portion size is pretty small but unsurprising given how miso cods are always served in really tiny portions in restaurants. I tried making miso cod once, and to stick it to restaurants&#39; faces I made quite a large portion, and it ended up kinda jelat with all the sweet seasoning, so maybe that&#39;s why. TFS&#39;s miso cod was very tender and well marinated, would definitely recommend it if you&#39;re half hungry. Otherwise it&#39;ll only make you hungrier.<br><br>The ramen was somewhat of a disappointment. The smoked duck was too dry, I presume they sautéed it as well with the ramen but that process probably drained out some of the juices. There were 2 tiny tiny pieces of foie gras, which given the price of the dish seems slightly unreasonable. I mean it&#39;s literally fried instant ramen, so that&#39;s probably not where the cost went. That leaves the 3-4 pieces of smoked duck and 2 pieces of foie gras the size of my thumb. Which makes it the most expensive piece of foie gras I ever ate. <br><br>The sushi looks fresh though, and their uni dishes look pretty good though I didnt try it. Basically, if you have cash to blow, definitely come here for the great sushi and fresh seafood. Otherwise, you&#39;ll be somewhat disappointed.

text: Did a walk-in here on a Thursday night, for two.<br><br>Japanese-fusion sort of place, in a little alley. Sounds like a cliché, hey?<br><br>This place is actually decent. Okay food, okay service, okay decor, okay toilets, okay everything (okay maybe, soso drinks). I&#39;m just unsure if the prices here actually give value, which is the main driver of my reviews.<br><br>We had the chirashi don, some signature maki, an onsen egg each (what is with the dashi JELLY?!), wine, and my greatest disappointment, my shiso martini. A martini with a shiso leaf in, makes it a shiso martini, NOT. This is partially my fault for having high hopes. I once had the greatest shiso drink ever, and I was hoping to recreate that moment/feeling/taste. Okay reminiscence over. The food here is generally acceptable, fish is acceptably fresh, but nothing is a great stand-out. <br><br>A very minor grouse, I dislike the black napkins here, because I can&#39;t gauge how clean my mouth is when I wipe it or if I need to reapply some lippie. I think women who wear lipstick might agree with me, but I&#39;m just nitpicking.<br><br>Would I come back? Maybe.

text: If you are looking for delicate flavors and intimate conversation, TFS is your spot! <br><br>Food here is a little pricy but really depends on how you order. Instead of getting sushi or rolls, we opted for small plates and entrées to share. The Onsen Tamago is the BOMB! I don&#39;t know how they make it but it is this heavenly mix of salmon roe, spring egg, seaweed, spring onion, and some sort of jelly. Also recommend their udon linguine with clam and vegi, very light yet balanced. Besides these two, we ordered seafood salad, fried truffle prawn as well as fried chicken, all pretty good.<br><br>Cocktails are delicious but the prices are on the higher end. I got two earl grey martinis and they are about $19 each.<br><br>The light was soft but not too dark. The night we were here they were playing pop and rock ballads from Sam Smith, Goo goo dolls and alike. Super intimate and great for date night!

The look and feel of this place reminds me of a small neighborhood sushi joint, very cool. It&#39;s in walking distance of where we live to so I was really excited to find out about it. The first time we came, I ordered the TFS chirashi and my husband got the TFS maki. Around $20 for each of these,the price is a bit steep, but I thought the chirashi bowl was well worth it. You get a lot of fish and not too much rice, so you feel like you&#39;re getting your money&#39;s worth :) Not only that but the chirashi bowl is like an explosion of flavors with sweet sauce from the eel combined with bursting of the salmon roe and the sashimi, it&#39;s pretty amazing. So the next time we went to the restaurant, we both ordered the chirashi bowl :)
Its the places you will go when you wanna chitchat n have japanese food with some sake. The owners are v friendly too.

While waiting for our seats at the Market Grill, I decided to check out the Flying Squirrel since I passed it during a fun Friday a few weeks back. The entire restaurant was booked up but the waitress, who knows how to work a business, said I could have 2 bar seats before an 8.45 reservation. <br><br>I thought some parts of the menu looked interesting and gave those items a try.  We had the grilled fugu and it was delicious and quite a steal. The dude said  it tasted like fish jerky while I put it down to FISH BAK KWA. Complete with wide eyes and lick of the lips. The (I think) slightly fermented octopus and cucumber was a refreshing version of kimchi and was very small even for a bar bite. We rounded things off with chicken karaage as a tummy filler. Quite a poor cousin of 5 Izakaya&#39;s version but then again, most places do crappy soggy fried chicken these days.<br><br>For drinks, I tried the yuzu prosecco, which was not as sweet as I expected (in a good way). The drink as a whole was light, fresh and balanced and a perfect starter to a meal. The dude had a pint of Asahi and there were no complaints there. Overall the food &amp; drink did the job.

text: Really not worth it. So what&#39;s the fuss with this whole Japanese fusion thing? Been there and done that, and Friend, if you can&#39;t do it well, please don&#39;t do it at all. <br><br>First off, the collection of Asahi beer deserves a pat on the back. I recommend trying the Asahi Black, a bit like Guinness but with more of a punch. Service-wise...uh, we did have to pay 10% for that, right? I&#39;m so tired of going to restaurants when the server has no idea what&#39;s going on, takes 10 minutes to bring in an associate to explain, and this associate has no idea that I can spot bull all the way to KL. There was one Australian (?) server who was pretty knowledgeable though he left mid-way through our meal. The sashimi platter was good but definitely not as fresh as other places I&#39;ve tried. I would say the sashimi at TFS is aligned with Sakae Sushi but with prices aligned with Sushi Tei. Out of the 7 tapas we tried, I only really enjoyed the truffle fried ebi. But I enjoy everything with truffle oil so no crowd pleaser here. <br><br>Am I being too mean here? Wweeelll...I def. won&#39;t come back here again. After a meal that left all four of us hungry, we stopped by WaBar for a real dinner. TFS certainly made me appreciate Tanuki more than ever--for the prices, creativity, and fusion. Well done Tanuki, and keep on trying TFS.
Its the places you will go when you wanna chitchat n have japanese food with some sake. The owners are v friendly too.

text: Nice, low-key Japanese-food driven joint.  The fare isn&#39;t something to totally scream over, but given the price point which is reasonable and the cool NYC decor, it&#39;s a winner in my view.

The inside layers of the Thai Basil Mango Mousse ($7.80). Highly recommend', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The inside layers of the Thai Basil Mango Mousse ($7.80). Highly recommend'}]
text: Unique dishes with a local twist. Abundant seating. Good deals right now through Eatigo (10-50% discount). If you book through Eatigo do note there are two separate menus and seating for Coalesce Dining vs. Coalesce Bar. <br><br>Waited 45 minutes for one order (Bar Sampler) which was small and expensive for its full price ($35). The pumpkin wontons were fine but again very small. The Thai Basil Mango Mousse was the highlight of the night, excellent balance of flavours.<br><br>Minus one star for long wait time for order to arrive. Another minus one star for portions that are small for their value.

Squid ink linguine with soft shell crab', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Squid ink linguine with soft shell crab'}]
text: I don&#39;t remember when it became acceptable for cafes - not restaurants mind you - to charge $6.50 for a cup of coffee or have an average brunch dish cost $17. (Brunch dishes - they&#39;re just eggs y&#39;all!) I suppose when youngsters (and older, aka me) started turning up at cafes in droves with their laptops and staying for hours.<br><br>At least with Regroup, I didn&#39;t feel too bad parting with $17 for my squid ink linguine (4 stars). For starters, it had soft shell crab in it. While the crab wasn&#39;t as delicately crispy as others I&#39;ve had, the garlicky, spicy sauce was right up my alley. Typically, I feel like I order squid ink pasta more for its unique colour (I&#39;m a sucker for green tea and pistachio flavoured items because of their gorgeous colours. Heck, I swear it was the wildly unnatural, beautiful lilac skins of yam baos [taro buns] that conned me into consuming far more of them than is probably advisable). But this time, the linguine itself seemed to be that much more flavourful. Warning: Don&#39;t eat this before an important presentation or risk looking like a toothless pirate.<br><br>Tried some of my friend&#39;s truffle mushroom soup (4 stars) - it didn&#39;t taste creamy and wasn&#39;t salty. She found it a bit bland though. Also had some of her goldrush waffle (4 stars). The waffle was somewhere nicely between being soft and crispy, the dark chocolate ice cream was solid, and the honeycomb crumbs were a nice touch. The salted egg sauce was good, but it&#39;s not my thing to begin with. I had a single scoop of ice cream and the girl at the counter very nicely agreed to do 2 generous half scoops for me, making it $4 well-spent. Their pistachio (4 stars) is definitely one of the better ones I&#39;ve had. The stout butterbeer (3.5 stars) had a good flavour but melted too quickly.<br><br>Besides the food, I love the decor of the place (5 stars). It&#39;s spacious, brightly lit, and minimalist. They also have 3 fans going in addition to the air-conditioning - I&#39;m guessing because the large windows make it fairly warm in the day. It was pretty empty on a weekday afternoon, and I got some studying done. Note that there&#39;s no wifi available. I see their pistachio latte, smoked salmon salad, and a good book making a perfect afternoon in my near future.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/XDyfhO7wXg_tsTNJPco2gg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/regroup-singapore?reviewid=JE4NPh6iuCSDmtyitmQRlw&select=XDyfhO7wXg_tsTNJPco2gg', 'altText': 'Photo of Regroup - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: The coffee here is ok to nice. They do latte art. Flavour wise, it&#39;s on the safe side and even slightly on the bland side. But the nearest decent coffee at a walk is Wheeler&#39;s Yard but that place you&#39;ll probably have a much longer wait albeit tastier cup. 3.5 for the coffee.<br><br>Waffles take quite a prominent spot on the menu but we were in the mood for some salt so we ordered the truffle fries. I have to say the fries were not very good. Firstly they are thick cut but more importantly the oil seemed a little over-used and the insides weren&#39;t fluffy..like the fries were a little old. Simple dish that a lot of places sell and make good margins on, so it was an unpleasant surprise that it was subpar.<br><br>I do like the atmosphere of the place. It&#39;s laidback. Kudos for the cool stylish tap for getting your own water. Other than that, it doesn&#39;t stand out that much. It doesn&#39;t have the charm of the Duxton flagship I would say.<br><br>I was there on a Sunday morning before 11am and the place was nearly empty.<br><br>They don&#39;t have parking so maybe it appeals more to residents. I have a friend who stays round the corner and I actually drive by weekly but the fact is, I&#39;ve only been in once..so that is saying something. If I need a coffee and can be fussed to park at my friend&#39;s condo and walk. But if I were gonna drive to drink and I&#39;m not crunched for time, I would head over to Old Hen for a bit more life and vibe and taste.<br><br>Icecream here is rich and sweet. Some almost too sweet for my taste but it&#39;s quite creamy and should please be a crowd pleaser. I&#39;ll try the waffles when I come back next time and see if it warrants an update!

text: Happy to find this cafe and ice cream bar just around the corner from the office. They have a small but quite good food menu as well. Some pasta dishes, salads and sandwiches to choose from. Coffee was not the best I have had, but still okay. Will come back!

I had heard a bit about FIne Palate but had never had a chance to stop by until a few weeks ago when I came with a friend for a work photo shoot. <br><br>I came in on a Saturday at around 2 and made it just in time for their brunch menu. I ordered the Breakfast Cook Up ($20) which served two eggs any style served on fresh homemade bread, bacon, apple and sage sausage, and potatoes. The apple and sage sausage was my personal favorite and extremely flavorful. I also ordered a cappuccino which was also delicious surprisingly enough<br><br>The atmosphere was perfect as they share a wall with a Church next door so you often hear singing. <br><br>The staff were lovely! Attentive and so polite. Great great place for brunch on a lazy saturday afternoon!

The Dragonfruit Dip - Isnt the colour pretty?', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'The Dragonfruit Dip - Isnt the colour pretty?'}]
text: Breakfast food is truly my all time favourite and nothing excites me more than a brunch menu. Came here for lunch on a saturday ard 12nn and all the indoor seats were taken so we had to settle with sitting outside along the corridor.<br><br>While Fine Palate is well-known for it&#39;s catering service, dinning at the restaurant is equally enjoyable though I have to say that the price is slightly steep. My friend and I ordered the Eggs Benedict and Steak &amp; Eggs to share. I really love the steak. It&#39;s moist and tender though we had to send it back to get the steak cooked again cos while we asked for medium rare, the steak came out a little too rare for us.<br><br>The meal started with a serving of some fresh bread (that tasted really well) with a purple dragonfruit dip. The colour of the dip was amazing with a rich purple that actually made us really curious how the dip would taste like (instead of a turn off as with some scary coloured food). It has the fragrance of the dragonfruit and richness of olive oil and a slightly salted taste. <br><br>The service staff were also extremely helpful and personable. The overall experience would had been fantastic except it got terribly upsetting cos of the rain. While we were enjoying ourselves catching up over a great meal, the sky starting pouring and the rain splattered all over our table. There was no where we could shift to cos the indoor seating were all taken and the restaurant had no other form of shelter or sorts to shelter us and the food. I had to take out my own foldable umbrella to try to keep my friend and i, together with our food, safe from the pouring rain.<br><br>I hope Fine Palate will seriously look into the conditions of their outdoor dinning so that patrons&#39; experience will not be at risk due to adverse weather conditions.<br><br>Note: Fine Palate is now open for dinner too!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/8XTPuYpNgSjqHSjib1-t2w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/mugiya-singapore?reviewid=HjeXeSxSx93zSbFruJGCVQ&select=8XTPuYpNgSjqHSjib1-t2w', 'altText': 'Photo of Mugiya - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Walking out from the MRT station into City Square Mall today, I was greeted with the pleasant aroma of freshly baked bread. I could not help myself but stop at the source of the smell - Mugiya. They sell a pretty decent variety of buns and cakes and I had a taste of their cranberry cheese bun, which I heard was their specialty. It was still warm when I bought it and was an absolute delight. The bread was soft and light, yet not too airy. My only comment is that there could have been more cream cheese as I was eating plain bread in some of my bites.<br><br>Their chocolate buns are brilliant and their tiramisu is not too bad. While the tiramisu is not exactly the traditional ones you get in italy or in decent italian restaurants, it is light and has a nice coffee flavour. Their buns and cakes are priced pretty average. I can&#39;t remember how much the cakes cost but the cream cheese cranberry bun cost $1.50 which is pretty standard these days.

text: Mugiya is a bakery that offers Japanese bread and cakes. This particular location is among other food stalls just outside the MRT Lavender Station, next to V Hotel. <br><br>Whenever you pass by here, you can&#39;t simply ignore the tempting smell of newly baked bread. Just follow the smell with your nose and you&#39;ll be greeted by stacks of delectable goodies in different shapes and flavors. <br><br>I usually buy just a few pieces of bread here although they also sell adorable cakes for any occasion. Just pick whatever bread you like from the shelves and bring them to the cashier to pay. <br><br>Although the interaction between clients and staff are strictly business, I don&#39;t hold anything against them. It&#39;s understandably the culture here. As long as I get my oven fresh bread, I&#39;m all good!

Small shop tucked in Level One @ Far East Plaza, this crepe place is just next to the bubble tea shop.<br><br>I ordered a banana chocolate cheese crepe which I thought sounded like a pretty weird combination - sweet at savory together, but it turned out pretty good! <br><br>The crepe was slightly crispy (kinda like fortune cookie but not as thick... maybe a thicker papadam might be a better description) which was a little surprising because I&#39;m used to soft crepe (kinda like popiah skin types). I&#39;m not sure if it is supposed to be this way since I suspect it might have been overcooked as the place is run only by 1 chef, who also doubles as the cashier taking orders - and she was busy.<br><br>Nonetheless, it worked pretty well and I think the crisp is pretty good, especially with the chocolate! I wish there was more cheese in it as the savory and sweet combination is pretty tasty.<br><br>Will visit again if I&#39;m ever in this part of town!

text: Do you know that one could play golf in CDB area? One will think how can especially when the area is filled to maxmium with various tall buildings. There is no big green patch in the city area. In this small place, it looks like a bar from outside which the the nearby white collar office workers will come for a drink or two after work. Inside there is two indoor golf range, where one can book a simulator to putt. Don&#39;t worry if you do not know how to putt. There is a pro guy inhouse to give some lessons on the spot.<br><br>By day the place is a cafe, while at night it will turn into a bar. So it is a place for cafe cum bar cum golf. The menu available is limited with just light bites and drinks.<br><br>Chardonnay ($14/ glass)<br>White from France<br>The wine was light and smooth, without being too dry.<br><br>Beer LAO  ($11)<br>from Laos<br>The beer was quite light in taste. Cool and refreshing.<br><br>Cranberry Juice<br>Not too sweet in taste.<br><br>Delhi Belly Good (V) ($12)<br>Flat bread, feta, red pepper, Spanish onion, coriander<br>Althought there was feta cheese, it did not taste strong and was nicely balanced by the sweet caramelised onion.<br><br>Oh Calcutta ($14)<br>Original chicken tikka kati roll, poppadoms, mint yoghurt<br>The chicken tasted a bit spicy. A bit messy to have as the chicken was quite juicy. There was some juice flowing out when I bit into one.<br><br>Balls On Fire ($15)<br>Pork meatballs, spicy tomato sauce<br>The meatball was very juicy and meaty. It was heavenly topped with the melted cheese.<br><br>Wrap &amp; Roll ($14)<br>Rice paper, coriander, cucumber, carrots, glass noodles, soy, lime, chilli<br>A light refreshing roll, but I did not quite take to the mint in the roll.<br><br>Overall the food was not bad but limited. Best get some food after the games here. The staffs were friendly and easy to get their attention.

text: Another GREAT yelp elite event. Shout out to our CM Michelle M who again did a wonderful job along with her 2 sidekicks CheeKeong and Anz (sorry i couldn&#39;t make out your name) But i know i will see more of you.<br><br>The event was very well thought out. It gave us plenty of time to socialize. And tried our hand at the Golf simulator. It was indeed top notch equipment being used. The drinks were good. Tried the LaoBeer and it was good and strong. Goes really well with the tapas served. Their Flatbread was really good and authentic flavors were introduced. The meatballs were cooked to perfection. Soft and luscious in the middle which is always what you&#39;re looking for.<br><br>Unfortunately we were seated at the back so we weren&#39;t served the other food that were only presented at the front of the event. awwww.<br><br>But all in all. it was a great time talking. Great prizes were again given out. we had a GREAT time. On to the next event!

text: This place is clean and looks nice, but I don&#39;t really get the concept.<br><br>I went here for a Tuesday Quiz night and while I was happy that they had Guinness and some cool-looking golf simulators, there was hardly any bar food available and only one bathroom.<br><br>Not exactly sure if this is trying to be a social club, a golfing instructional place or a bar, but it&#39;s definitely not too great a venue to host an eating or drinking session (unless you plan to eat and use the bathroom somewhere else).

When tea is your thing, this may be your place: large selection of all sorts of tea (Chinese or Taiwanese - unfortunately no Korean Ginseng tea which I&#39;m still trying to spot here). Particularly a wide range of green teas. Friendly service in halting Singlish in a street that also offers alluring antiques (or antique looking objects) and surprising shops like the one specialized in smoked thin pork slices coated in some sweet mixture (New Year delicacy)

This Artease outlet opens till 10pm. Yay! I know where I can get an iced cold bubble tea when I am craving for one. I have always been a bubble tea fan even before the recent bubble tea craze. <br><br>At this particular bubble tea joint, they sell more than just bubble tea. They also have coffee, waffles and salads too. <br><br>Recently, they have introduced Yuzu Green Tea to their menu and it is simply refreshing for a warm summer day.  Since I tried it, it has been the item I order from their menu.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/wSAipJWmwXjpxeobFdywzg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/artease-singapore-2?reviewid=c18grkUp7x6zGgK12fb51A&select=wSAipJWmwXjpxeobFdywzg', 'altText': 'Photo of Artease - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: As the name suggests, it prides itself on being an artsy-fartsy bubble tea shop. I think the artwork they have on the walls are really nice though. They claim to use only premium ingredients but there&#39;s no indication of what they mean by &#34;premium&#34; so don&#39;t expect artisan bubble tea when you come here.<br><br>What you can expect though is really yummy bubble tea. I had the Apple Rose Tea and it was really nice. I like how you can choose your sugar level in these bubble tea shops these days and this place is no different. One of the best things I like is that pearls, whether mini or regular, are FREE!! Yes. I don&#39;t understand why some places think it necessary to charge for pearls. Pearls are the best part of bubble tea.<br><br>Other than bubble tea, they&#39;ve also got coffee, pudding and waffles if you want something to bite on to go with your beverage. Oh, and ice-blended drinks as well. Definitely a place you wanna check out if you&#39;re tired of Gong Cha and all that. Staff are also very friendly so they get my vote!

text: Our favourite juicr/smoothie brand in Singapore. We csn highly recommend the Mango Tango.<br><br>It has mango and passion fruit and a bit or sorbet.<br>Love it. Always fresh.

My friend and I are tourists spending a couple days in Singapore and were looking for breakfast and we saw this place with a good amount of people so we decided to eat here as well. I got the nasi lemak which contained rice which I remembered to be a little dry, roasted peanuts (added good texture and had a nice roasting flavor), a little bit of fresh veggies (mainly a cucumber, had a good crunch), anchovies/fish like thing that was pungent (would not have them add this next time), and a fried chicken leg. The fried chicken leg was my favorite part as it was fried to perfection and was very well flavored. <br><br>If I could do it over again, I would probably order something else and a side of chicken but overall a good experience.

text: One of the few places that were open on a Saturday morning. I ordered the Mee Rebus - a noodle dish popular in Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore. Or the Singapore Debit Card.

text: My boyfriend and I are addicted to the waffle and ice creams at Simplicite. We tried other waffle places but none can compare.<br><br>Crispy on the outside, soft and fluffy on the inside. Sink your teeth into the East&#39;s lightest waffles.
