photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/nQjsg09adLO8SlNOqho08w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/toast-box-singapore-11?reviewid=3ORy0BzkwjIAbvcrvbRHpg&select=nQjsg09adLO8SlNOqho08w', 'altText': 'Photo of Toast Box - Singapore, Singapore. Peanut butter thick toast', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Peanut butter thick toast'}]
text: Toast Box is a hugely popular chain in Singapore and this location tends to feature a line of locals 10+ deep.  That being said, the line moves pretty quickly, so don&#39;t let the line deter you if you want to try the local goodies at Toast Box.  I&#39;ve had a chance to try a few of the goodies, but plan to try more:<br><br>1. Kaya Toast (~$1.50): I&#39;ve tried this a few times and I&#39;m not hooked, but I know it is extremely popular.  The dish is made by liberally spreading butter and kaya (eggs, sugar, coconut milk and pandan) on 2 thin slices of white toast and making a sandwich<br><br>2. Peanut Butter Thick Toast ($1.70): A few bites of this and you may feel that you have enough sustenence to run a marathon.  The thick cut toast is buttered and toasted slightly crispy and then slathered with chunky, not too sweet peanut butter.  Before handing it over, they cut the piece of toast into 9 small squares and provide a toothpick to eat it without getting your hands dirty.  It is extremely potent, and you may want to bring a buddy for sharing<br><br>3. Kopi (~$1.50): Classic kopi is the local coffee and reminds me a bit of Vietnamese coffee.  It is made with thick, dark coffee and condensed milk.  If you prefer your coffee unsweeted with evaporated milk, make sure you order &#34;kopi &#39;c&#39; kosong&#34;.  Standard kopi is served sweetened<br><br>PARTING THOUGHT: My colleagues told me that you can actually get the already extravagant peanut butter thick toast kicked up a notch with a liberal drizzle of condensed milk, so that is on my list next!

Toast? Seriously? The idea of buying prepared toast and peanut butter doesn&#39;t sit well with me.But the location was nice, and I try to have an open mind and palate.<br>It is what it is, it is good toast and it came with kopi in a set so it worked out well. I guess this place is for those moments you miss breakfast food and dont have time to prepare it.

Croque Monsieur', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Croque Monsieur'}]
text: I still don&#39;t get why people can&#39;t distinguish macaron from macaroon. I guess this is one of those things that irritates the hell out of me. <br><br>Macaron - a French meringue based confection filled with butter cream, ganache or jam sandwiched between two cookies, characterized by smooth domed top, ruffled edge and a flat base. <br><br>Macaroon - a type of small circular cake originated from Italy which usually has coconut as one of the ingredients; crispy on the outside and chewy in the inside. <br><br>Even when one fellow yelper here who was so kind to point out it was really not macaroons but macarons, some yelpers still continued to label macarons as macaroons. Learn it right before one ends up becoming a laughing stock somewhere. And I am serious! <br><br>Enough of my ranting (can you really blame me?), this TWG location is located on the 2nd floor, near Harry Winston and the entrance/exit which leads to the taxi stand. I supposed they closed the other TWG on the first floor which I like very much. <br><br>Came here last month with my friend and we had a good brunch (Croque Monsieur) with two pots of Golden Rose. I found the Croque Monsieur a tad salty but as always I love the Golden Rose tea and the company. Thanks Christine for buying me brunch; hope you enjoyed our recent session at Antoinette too.<br><br>This morning I popped over there to pick up some Golden Rose loose tea leaves. The staff was so friendly and helpful. He gave me some pointers on how to brew a perfect tea.<br><br>Staff here are always nice and service impeccable. <br><br>Note: I was told if the tea leaves are to store in one of those canisters, the tea leaves will be fresh for 3 years. So yes, I bought a canister too! :)

text: Love having tea here, a little too cramped for my liking but the food is good. Service is a little slow at times only because it&#39;s always so crowded but I&#39;d still come back and I&#39;d still recommend this place to others

Afternoon tea in the middle of busy mall? I was at first skeptical about this place when suggested my friend.  Well, I was wrong. I truly enjoyed high tea here.<br><br>Location: conveniently located at the inside the ION mall, L1 and L2, just escalator away from the Orchard subway station. Even though it is inside the busy mall once inside, you will enjoy quietness of the restaurant.  Unlike those at five star hotels, (lobby area with many people walking by), glass wall keeps inside quiet.<br><br>High tea experience: we ordered high tea set with several small sandwich and sweets in tiered trays. Everything I tasted was very good. We ordered additional macarons, they were so delicate and amazingly good. $2 each was very reasonable too. I normally pay more for macarons.<br><br>Tea: I tried French Earl Grey. They are known for good tea and they are here to maintain their reputation. Only if I have room in my suitcase, I would definitely buy some to bring home.<br><br>We stayed for a little over one hour and enjoyed leisurely afternoon with good conversation and amazing high tea. I would highly recommend high tea experience here over five star hotel.

text: This review is about TWG product, not their store locations, which I&#39;ve never been to. I&#39;m new to tea drinking and wanted to try switching from coffee all day to something a little less jarring in the afternoons. I&#39;d read good things about TWG in other reviews and decided to order a variety of their products to taste. Specifically, I ordered about 25 different varieties of loose tea, which they sell in 50g batches.<br><br>I admit I&#39;m not a connoisseur, but I found their teas to be delicious. Not just the higher priced ones either. In fact, their house brand &#39;1837 White Tea&#39; is actually my favorite and is on the low-end of the price scale. I&#39;ve quickly grown addicted to both the amazing smell and taste every day. I would also add that they included several free samples of other teas (in decent amounts as well, enough for several pots at least) in my order that they thought I would like based upon my purchase. Especially for a beginner like me, this is particularly useful as they have a bewildering array (hundreds) of varieties.<br><br>I will definitely continue to be a customer going forward, and I would recommend their product to anyone.

text: I&#39;ve been here for high tea with the set. The staff was really friendly and helped me choose a tea since they had too much for me to choose myself. The atmosphere was really great and for being in a busy mall, it&#39;s surprisingly nice and quiet. Most of their food was good as well, but some of them could use some work. The tea though was really amazing. It is overpriced though and I felt as if I was paying more for the atmosphere than the food itself.

I&#39;m a fan of the macaroons, especially the matcha one!<br><br>For $2 a piece, I&#39;d say the price is decent for some pretty good macaroons!<br><br>I always do take out, but will probably find a day to go there for tea!

text: A lot of people do not realise this about this Salon de Thé - it is a Singaporean company that stands for the Wellness Group. Another thing that a lot of people do not realise - it is a totally rip off from a Salon de Thé in Paris called Mariage Frères. Everything, from the décor to the teapots to the OCD need to have the logo embossed or embroidered on all the items, down to the waiter&#39;s outfits, all copied. It has an overwhelming colonial, &#39;raffles&#39; sort of feel, and everything on the menu has a tea element in it. <br><br>The mains are not really the main stars at this place, with small portions and the tea element felt very forced, such as in the lasagna which did not bode well, and the wagyu beef burger which could be finished in a few bites and the only tea element was the sauce for the chips. The dessert is not bad, though a little hit and miss.

You know I would have never thought I would have such a fabulous time having tea in the middle of the mall, but I truly did! Despite it being in the center of a walkway, the shopping center wasn&#39;t that packed and it wasn&#39;t noisy, so I had a grand time.<br><br>It is indeed a special little place planted in the center of Ion Mall, and the airiness and surrounded by top designer shops gives it another posh feel--I never thought I could feel so posh having tea in the mall before. The service was pleasant and I felt like I was transported to some 5-star afternoon tea paradise (despite it being the middle of the night). I loved the huge tea selection, and the waiter made some nice suggestions after I asked for something flowery and light. I got the 1 tea + dessert combination (~20SGD) to share with my friend since we had just completed a delicious dinner earlier.<br><br>If I were back in Singapore, I could see this as a great hang-out spot to catch up with friends and drink some fancy tea + have cake at any hour of the day. It is pricey, but it&#39;s what do you expect for &#34;the world&#39;s finest, luxury, tea brand.&#34; Indulge, and enjoy!<br><br>They also have a small shelf of tea you can purchase that smelled amazing.

I&#39;ve been kind of obsessed with TWG ever since my cousin came to the states a few years ago and brought a beautiful tin of green tea + rose petals.   So on my last visit, she took me to ION to check out the mother ship, and it was such a fun experience!  <br><br>Yep, I know TWG is a direct ripoff of the French Mariage Frères, but at least it&#39;s done incredibly well-- one of the creators of TWG worked at MF for years before coming to Singapore to start the brand.<br><br>The shop/cafe really is heaven for someone as into tea as I am, though the variety of teas is actually a bit overwhelming.  They have a huge selection of teas, tea accessories, and a counter with macarons and other baked goods. <br><br>An awesomely nice French employee took me under his wing and opened up half a dozen canisters for me to peruse.   The only unfortunate thing here is that they don&#39;t really let you sample the teas themselves.  <br><br>I ended up buying one of their classic black teas as a gift for a friend, and was so surprised to be gifted with another selection of tea (black tea with hibiscus- highly recommended) for myself.  Who knew people could be so nice?  Totally made my day and made me love TWG even more. And the tea really is wonderful too!

text: This is a replacement review for one that mysteriously disappeared..<br><br>This was an introductory/first date.  The joys of a blind date.  So, we selected a casual place.<br><br>The staff was friendly, polite, and professional.<br><br>The ambiance really speaks to being a classic tea room.  Plus, with the glass walls you can see everything that is going on around you in the mall.  But it does have a touch of a feeling of having a meal in an aquarium.<br><br>VEAL BLANQUETTE (Rich veal stew served with button mushrooms and baby onions in lemon cream sauce infused with Mistral Tea.) - This was a rather bland dish.  It didn&#39;t really stand out at all.  I wouldn&#39;t order it again.<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fa5ue3vu&amp;s=11a607583db431d4692532eab61a9623410487d9e476bfd16496985b4e9b755a" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/a5ue3vu</a><br><br>Chocolate Cake - I also had a slice of chocolate cake.   I quite enjoyed it.  It was moist and there was a plentiful amount of chocolate in it.<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fb9uup99&amp;s=c0d9505a359d5450b95f45f6aa5b763b8f54e549a31cedb1efd011b33f6cdfc0" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/b9uup99</a><br><br>Overall - For something casual, it will work.  I certainly do not consider it a destination spot though.  But, if you are in the mall, and want a bite to eat, dessert, or tea, I think that this TWG Tea Salon is a decent, if not spectacular, option.

A charming salon de thé, TWG is a welcome oasis for the weary shopper to have a refreshing pot of tea in the heart of the gigantic Ion mall. Spread across two floors, the main salon is on the second foor, surrounded by the likes of Harry Winston Jewelers, Dior, and D&amp;G. <br><br>Offering a multitude of teas, sandwiches, pastries, as well as &#34;real food&#34;, its fare is almost as rich as the clientele walking out of the many luxury boutiques near by. Service is usually impeccable, boasting dapper servers in formal waiters jackets, with friendly yet genteel dispositions, and a great knowledge of their product. <br><br>Although not as private a location as one would expect from a tea room, the ambiance is still one of refinery and elegance. Perfect for a light high tea, and a chance to catch up with friends or to people watch. Make sure to keep an eye out for their beautiful rotating tea wall!

text: Every TWG shop is Singapore is beautifully decorated. It gave me a feeling that i&#39;m in some European countries. <br><br>Love their Moroccan Mint Tea. It has a strong peppermint smell. They are all nicely packed in tiny silky tea bag. Not forgetting TWG Macaron, Napoleon Tea &amp; Caramel. Bravo! One of the best thing you can ever ask for for an afternoon tea session with your beloved friends.<br><br>Really worth paying every single cent spent in TWG. They totally own my heart.

text: TWG is my fave, fave, fave, fave tea! This outlet has an amazing selection of tea, like literally dozens. All the way up the ceiling. It has almost every type of tea you could imagine - and great quality too. It&#39;s location is strategic - you get to sit in this glass interior - where you can see the outside - and everyone that is passing by. All the big brands are next door.<br><br>It&#39;s quite a chi chi place - the waiters are dressed in suits, and everyone&#39;s very proper and all.<br><br>What I Love: For brunch, there&#39;s a set - where some pastries, salads and breads, are put in a platter - and it&#39;s pretty okay, in terms of price. At least, better than the dinner prices. The menu is really comprehensive - for tea! Take a look, sample the ones you like and just enjoy it. The tea bags are soft, exquisite cloth bags, and the teapots are tiny and beautiful. It&#39;s just a place to treat yourself.<br><br>What I Don&#39;t Love: The prices. Eeeek. It will set you back $50 per person... so keep it for special occasions then! ;)

This is entirely just about TWG&#39;s macarons.<br><br>I&#39;ve been a fan of macarons for about 6 years now (while the cupcake craze was going on) and now macarons are getting their own craze. I&#39;m not complaining. More variety and places to get macarons!<br><br>Notice: Macarons not Macaroons - the latter being a coconut cookie popular among the kosher set.<br><br>I was definitely enticed by interesting tea-infused macarons. My favorite being the Earl Grey chocolate macaron. I also like the Rose Tea and the Black Tea with salted caramel filling. I think they make the best macarons in Singapore. The crunchy but soft shell, interesting flavors, and it keeps pretty well in the fridge for a few days.

text: Tea in a busy mall surrounded by expensive shops??!! Not bad vacation.  The finger sandwiches are most def worth a try :) amazing tea and food 5 story mall with exquisite food choices and decor.  Clothes tables and 5-star services :) cant wait to come back

Okay as most people have spoken about their sit-down experience, I guess I&#39;ll talk about my favourite TWG teas in general, as the choice is so vast you can&#39;t help but feeling lost when you stare at their list. How is the discerning tea drinker ever supposed to figure anything out? <br><br>First off:  <br><br>For green tea, I&#39;m a fan of Silver Moon and my friends like it too. It&#39;s green tea with a twist : the tea is infused with chunks of berries (I detect strawberries and raspberries) and comes with the prettiest blue / silver packaging... I&#39;m such a sucker for pretty packaging. It&#39;s quite light and fragrant, and perfect for something lighter on caffeine in the evening.  <br><br>The Emperor Sencha is also quite good, although it&#39;s stronger than Silver Moon.<br><br>Earl Grey Buddha is another one I enjoy - it has a twist of Bergamot instead of the usual Lavender, etc.<br><br>Black tea: <br><br>Strangely enough I&#39;ve just realised I don&#39;t get much black tea from TWG (I prefer my single-blend straight from Ceylonese estates) , but you can&#39;t go wrong with their English Breakfast and Five O&#39;Clock Tea . <br><br>It only gets 4 stars because the teas are expensive! The loose-leaf sometimes cost me $20. It&#39;s good though, I kind of want to buy every single tea in this shop.  I also buy their cotton bags when I&#39;m lazy to brew my tea and just want to dump it in the cotton bags - they&#39;re expensive though, about $5 + for 10 bags, so I use them sparingly. <br><br>P/S: Try the rose macaroons too. Macaroons at TWG cost $2 / piece (take-out) ... 6 in a box for $12.

text: Was here with friends for tea one afternoon; good range of tea and food was pretty good but definitely overpriced<br><br>The boxed and loose leaf teas make a great, classy local gift for tea lovers everywhere though; be sure to grab a few boxes

My weakness has always been a French Macaroon. I keep finding that I give into this weakness often in Singapore. Partially because I walk close to 10 miles a day and partially because these little delicacies are so readily available in Singapore. I have picked one up at Jason&#39;s grocery and also at The American Club. Both were good, but the lemon one today from this lovely tea spot was fabulous! I did not eat anything else there. I only walked in and picked up a lemon macaroon for the reasonable price of $2 SGD to go. It was pure perfection! I will be back to try other flavours, but that lemon one will be hard to beat!

The only things that I have tried here are the pastries and I always do takeaway. Having been supporting TWG since its first outlet at Republic Plaza, I am glad to say that the quality of their pastries have remained consistent even after so many years. I am not over-exaggerating when I said that I have tried nearly all their cakes and is recognised as the &#34;girl who always buy cakes&#34;.  However, I am still trying out new stuff because the selection is always ever-changing.<br> <br>The patisseries at TWG there rarely disappoint and I would dare say that it is the only place in Singapore that matches those in Paris or Japan. ( I was surprised when I walked past one branch in Jiyugaoka). Why? Simply because the pastries have textuality, technicality, creativity and of course flavours.<br> <br>Most of the pastries at TWG are mousse cakes besides tarts. What impresses me is that the texture of the mousse is always just right while the sponge remains moist (perhaps some have been soaked in liquids). Fruit compotes of different berries ( raspberry/blueberry/cassis) are usually very sour which curbs the creaminess from other components. The tart shell has remained consistently crispy so far. While I can&#39;t say that every single piece I&#39;ve tried is 100% perfect, I appreciate the chef&#39;s efforts to keep on inventing, playing with the flavours, textures and presentation. It is hard to spot a classic pastry here (perhaps the millefeuille or the signature chocolate fondant) but it is still possible to find new flavours in their classic pastries.<br> <br>I doubt what I have commented will be readily available since the selection keeps changing. Amazed by the rapid expansion of this Singapore tea brand in Singapore and overseas in such a short period of time, it will be interesting to see what new exciting flavours TWG will offer in future.

The good thing about TWG is that it conjures up an experience that makes you feel like you are not in Singapore, but in some chi chi cafe in Paris or London. However, be prepared to pay through the nose for that experience.<br><br>The tea at TWG is OK, it&#39;s not spectacular and one can get rather overwhelmed with the plethora of tea options available. What I really like though is the Singapore Surprise, a strawberry and creme brulee tart. The matcha cream cake is just OK, and the mains (we had salmon) was rather dry and terribly average. The macarons are not bad but I didn&#39;t think the flavours terribly innovative although the pastry itself was executed well.

text: My tea experience with TWG boils down too one cup of tea, Bourbon Vanilla. You usually get coffee infused with alcohol like an Irish coffee for example but you hardly hear of tea infusions with alcohol so I had to try this one for myself. I don&#39;t know how the bourbon was extracted but it was apparent in the tea and further accentuated by the heat. Like bourbon or whiskey, too much leaves a bad aftertaste in your mouth and same goes for this tea. No more than one cup for this particular tea. Overall TWG is your typical English inspired high tea place with gold trimmings to mimic upper class society dining similar to the era of the Titanic. Surrounded by high end boutiques, this TWG outlet definitely oozes class and embraces high society!

text: I&#39;m sure we&#39;ve all walked past the shiny golden doors of TWG café at Orchard Ion, and felt like it was the gates to Willy Wonka&#39;s chocolate stores. Walking in, you&#39;re greeted by some enthusiastic and well-trained wait staff who guide you to your seat. <br>They have a mind-boggling list of teas that span 6 pages front and back - which meant it took us 3 girls about an hour just to decide which 2 teas we wanted with our high-tea set menu. <br><br>The set costs just over $30, and comes with a selection of about 6 pastries like their scones and macarons, as well as 2 types of savory sandwiches and 2 pots of tea. After much hem-hawing and asking for complicated recommendations, we settled for the chocolate bourbon and vanilla tea. Both were tinged with a little sweetness even without sugar, but the chocolate tea eventually became too hard to swallow after it cooled. I would definitely suggest going for a more traditional or common tea if you&#39;re no connoisseur like me! <br><br>5 stars for service and hospitality, and getting your tea served in a shiny golden pot holder to feel posh!

text: Came here on a weekend for a temporary -- and tragically illusory -- escape from the madding crowd. Well, at least the portion of it sensible enough not to splurge on high tea, I suppose. The tea-related desserts were good! But mains and ice cream flavours were a little hit and miss.<br><br>Mains: <br>We had scrambled egg with saffron, and foie gras terrine which came with fresh brioche toast. For the egg, you get to choose between three flavours: matcha, saffron, and truffle oil. Matcha+egg sounded a little Dr Seuss so we skipped over that. But I think picking saffron was a mistake, since the saffron flavour didn&#39;t come out at all. I was initially skeptical about the foie gras but it turned out to be a winner. The toast was crispy, and soft but not soggy, and the foie gras spread perfectly over it.<br><br>Tea:<br>The selection of tea here really is overwhelming. We zoomed in to the &#34;exclusive blends&#34; section of the menu and ended up with something called Snow Mountain Tea, which is white tea. It was light, clear, and refreshing, and went really well with the dessert.<br><br>Dessert:<br>Madeleines with clotted cream and some TWG Tea jelly, and three macarons. I adore the macarons here. Flavours are rich enough and ingredients are fairly decent quality, something I can&#39;t say for many other macarons made in SG. The madeleines were also a delight -- fluffy and warm and perfect with the cream and the jelly. I love the jelly so much I wouldn&#39;t mind eating it every day. We also had two scoops of ice cream. One was dark pink and tasted of berries, I can&#39;t remember its name but it might have been the Timeless. Not memorable, not worth getting. The other was the Napoleon which had macadamias. This was good.

text: Went for a breakfast on the run right as they opened at 8 AM. Coffee and kaya toast to-go. The Kaya toast was probably the best of all the ones I tried. It&#39;s perfectly sweet and a nice coconut balance without being too overpowering or strong. The coffee was ok, but not my favorite. It was too sweet and too weak for my liking. <br><br>I loved the kaya so much though that I returned and bought jars to take home with me!

Since the dessert slection at Makansutra is limited, go ahead and swing by Toast Box for some local coffee or tea with kaya toast or pandan sponge cake.<br><br>Not as good as Ya Kun but okay. Toast wasn&#39;t crunchy enough and they skimped on the kaya but the milk iced tea was perfect. <br><br>Cash only.

text: 1. Great wanton noodles! $3.80 - 4.30 <br>- Warning: the chilli is really spicy! so you might wanna stick to just the black bean sauce or may ask them to put less. <br>- The wanton ares great but the cha sew needs works. It doesn&#39;t taste as fresh and looks a tad but dark. Dubious color. <br><br>2. Fried wantons $3.80<br>- So crispy! love it. People order these by the dozens.<br><br>It&#39;s a really no fuss place. Kinda like a hawker centre/ food court. The sitting area is casual, maybe even a little cramp. <br><br>***NOTE: I found the exact same noodles at Serangoon gardens (not chomp chomp but the other hawker centre. there are 2 located there.) Anyways, it serves exactly the same tasting wanton noodles and wantons (I am not sure if they are related) but the prices are much cheaper there since it&#39;s not air-conditioned. $3 a bowl and $3 a plate of fried wanton.

I didn&#39;t get anything to eat here - just a kopi (coffee) with milk. <br><br>I don&#39;t think I&#39;m a fan of Singapore-style coffee, but this was acceptable and better tasting than the kopi I had the previous morning. The iced coffee was strong, but I&#39;m not sure what kind of milk they put in it. <br><br>Advice - bring a local and have them order for you. Ordering coffee in this country is so confusing for an American!!<br><br>Service is quick.

text: I used to patronise this outlet but have not for a long time.<br><br>I remember having had lunch here occasionally and the food and drinks were good.<br><br>However, that was not the case tonight. <br><br>Th soft boiled eggs were semi-hard. They must been left lying around for a long time as they were not even hot to the touch.<br><br>The toast was the biggest disappointment - Super light weight, not even warm which only means it had been sitting around for some time.<br><br>The coffee was also not hot; taste was okay.<br><br>It also seems to have a confused branding as they now serve panini bread, pasta aglio olio and other western food. <br><br>Italian food has no place in a kopitiam!<br><br>What has become of Killiney Kopitiam?!! Totally disappointed!

text: This would be a favourite of mine if I was to live here.. Quick fast decent service and food. Love the coffee here

Epic fail at Killiney in Marina Square. Ordered the Marinara Pasta ($8.20) for lunch and it was below average. Pasta was not al dente and too hot, methinks it was cooked earlier and microwaved to order. The marinara sauce was pretty plain, it is supposed to have a medium strength flavour, and was disappointing.<br><br>No serviettes or tissues on the table, place was fairly empty when I arrived at 12:30pm whereas other restaurants were full, avoid this like organised religion.
